<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 00:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Threat of teachers strike looms over start of school; Talks continue </HEADLINE>
By CAROLYN THOMPSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) - A late night round of negotiations Tuesday
apparently smoothed what had threatened to be a contentious start
of the new school year for the 47,000-student Buffalo school
district.
</P>
<P>
   The executive committee of the Buffalo Federation of Teachers
emerged from talks with district officials saying any strike action
would not occur Wednesday, the first day of school for the state's
second largest district. Talks were to continue Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ''This does not mean that there still is not a crisis, anything
can fall apart tomorrow'' BFT President Philip Rumore said. ''We've
made enough progress that it would be irresponsible to do anything
tonight,'' said Philip Rumore, president of the BFT.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Maddigan, spokesman for the district, said ''we're very
encouraged with the prospect of reaching an agreement soon.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, union members unanimously authorized the executive
board to take any necessary action, including a strike, to secure a
contract. Teachers for the district are still working under the
terms of a contract that expired in June 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Union officials said the five-year contract offered by the board
includes no pay raise in the first year and increases of 1 percent,
2 percent, 1.5 percent and 2 percent in subsequent years. Teachers
also are being asked to work an extra two days a year with no
additional pay and the board wants retirees to accept a cut in
health benefits, according to the union.
</P>
<P>
   The district's 3,800 teachers earn an average of $55,000 a year,
Maddigan said, and three-quarters also receive annual pay
increments ranging from 1.5 percent to 5 percent, depending on
their levels of education and service to the district.
</P>
<P>
   BTF members voted to authorize a strike last year, too, but
ended up going to work without a contract. Many teachers said that
was not likely to happen again.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than an all-out walkout, the teachers would likely stage
so-called ''rotating strikes,'' in which all of the teachers at
randomly targeted schools fail to report to work on specific days.
Such strikes cause districtwide disruptions while allowing teachers
to report for work four out of five days a week.
</P>
<P>
   While declining to comment on stumbling blocks, city officials
say a tight budget is the general problem. Adding to that is the
fact that the district is about to start making payments of $2
million a year to cover the cost of a lawsuit by teachers settled
for $73 million in March. That lawsuit stemmed from an earlier
contract dispute.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-06-00 0004 </TRAILER>
