<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 00:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexico's Congress Gets Under Way  </HEADLINE>
By LISA J. ADAMS
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY -- Mexico's most diverse congress in history launched
its first working sessions Tuesday driven by a necessity to
negotiate and buoyed by promises of consensus over partisanship.
</P>
<P>
   The new political dynamics pose a great challenge to
President-elect Vicente Fox, who will have to barter like no chief
executive before him.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, presidents of the long-ruling Institutional
Revolutionary Party simply passed down legislative initiatives to
be rubber-stamped by loyal soldiers in the party-dominated
congresses.
</P>
<P>
   But now the country's fractured ruling party is trying to hold
itself together after losing the presidency for the first time in
71 years. Fox is a member of the National Action Party.
</P>
<P>
   ''The people want us to formulate an agenda that represents
their interests not ours. .... They do not want clashes and
confrontations,'' said PRI legislator Eduardo Andrade. ''We need to
work together. When this happens the nation as a whole moves
forward.''
</P>
<P>
   The new congress spent most of its first day behind closed doors
negotiating which members will head up its various working
committees, and giving speeches about the challenges facing the
most independent legislature in the country's history.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have the country's problems in our hands. Legislation is
going to be initiated here,'' said Green Party legislator Maria
Teresa Campoy. ''Before, for the most part, there was one official
party that made almost all of the decisions, but now today we are
all here for a common purpose, which is Mexico.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the issues legislators took up Monday was a program
criticized by many in Mexico for charging too much to register
cars. The PRI and the leftist Democratic Revolution Party proposed
getting rid of the recently implemented program.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
