<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 00:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Charges Dropped Vs. DNC Protesters  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Two reporters and 10 protesters arrested at a
bike rally last month during the Democratic National Convention
were cleared of charges Tuesday related to the demonstration.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 194 people arrested during the convention Aug. 14-17, two
still remain in custody, District Attorney's spokeswoman Sandi
Gibbons said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   One is an animal rights activist accused of plotting to damage
local fur shops, and the other is accused of throwing bottles at
police from an apartment rooftop, Gibbons said. Officials are
pursuing four federal cases against five people, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy City Attorney Howard Gluck recommended charges against
the bicyclists be dismissed because most had spent time in jail and
had their bikes temporarily confiscated. Charges against 57 others
were dropped Friday. All had previously been released from jail.
</P>
<P>
   ''I wasn't going to go tying up these courts when penalty has
been exacted and I have wife beaters and child abusers and drunk
drivers to prosecute,'' Gluck said.
</P>
<P>
   Police said the bikers, who were trying to promote a more
bike-friendly environment, zoomed through traffic, ignored safety,
frightened pedestrians and nearly caused accidents.
</P>
<P>
   The American Civil Liberties Union of Southern California has
filed a federal lawsuit charging that police targeted media members
in their attempts to control demonstrators.
</P>
<P>
   Associated Press broadcast correspondent Brian Bland and Chicago
Tribune reporter Flynn McRoberts were arrested while covering the
demonstration. Their charges were among those dropped.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-06-00 0033 </TRAILER>
