<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Threat of NY Teachers Strike Looms  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- A late night round of negotiations Tuesday
apparently smoothed what had threatened to be a contentious start
of the new school year for the 47,000-student Buffalo school
district.
</P>
<P>
   The executive committee of the Buffalo Federation of Teachers
emerged from talks with district officials saying any strike action
would not occur Wednesday, the first day of school for the state's
second largest district.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've made enough progress that it would be irresponsible to
do anything tonight,'' said Philip Rumore, president of the BFT.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Maddigan, spokesman for the district, said ''we're very
encouraged with the prospect of reaching an agreement soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Talks were to continue Wednesday. While optimistic, Rumore did
not rule out the possibility that negotiations could again
collapse.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, union members unanimously authorized the executive
board to take any necessary action, including a strike, to secure a
contract.
</P>
<P>
   State law forbids public employees from participating in
strikes, and imposes fines on those who do.
</P>
<P>
   But with a strike fund of more than $5.5 million in place,
several teachers have suggested so-called ''rotating strikes,'' in
which teachers at randomly targeted schools would fail to report to
work, Rumore said.
</P>
<P>
   The teachers' last contract expired in June 1999. Rumore said
the latest offer from the board calls for no pay increase the first
year, a 1 percent hike the next, followed by pay increases of 2
percent, 1.5 percent and 2 percent the final year of a five-year
contract.
</P>
<P>
   Teachers are also being asked to work an extra two days a year
with no additional pay and the board wants retirees to accept a cut
in their health benefits, Rumore said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
