<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 00:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientist's Lawyers File Petition  </HEADLINE>
By RICHARD BENKE
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) -- Lawyers for jailed Los Alamos nuclear
scientist Wen Ho Lee, whose scheduled release on bail was blocked
at the last minute Friday, made another plea Tuesday to the 10th
U.S. Circuit Appeals Court to release him.
</P>
<P>
   ''Surely it does not serve the public interest to maintain an
imprisonment that erodes the basic sense of fairness that
undergirds the Constitution,'' Lee's attorneys wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The petition was their second appeal to the 10th Circuit, which
on Friday superseded a bail-release order that had been signed by
U.S. District Judge James Parker.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorney John Cline said he hadn't heard from the
appeals court since filing a petition Friday for reconsideration of
its ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Betsy Shumaker, chief deputy clerk of the Circuit Court, said
the judges hadn't indicated whether they would schedule a hearing
on the petitions.
</P>
<P>
   Lee, 60, is accused of downloading restricted material about
nuclear weapons to unsecured computers and tapes while he worked at
Los Alamos. He has been jailed since Dec. 10, charged with 59
counts, and could face life in prison if convicted.
</P>
<P>
   Parker, who signed Lee's release on $1 million bail last week,
sent the appeals court a 17-page memorandum on Friday explaining
his reasoning. He said he was concerned that the appeals court
might not have enough time to review all the evidence, much of it
classified, to make a well-reasoned ruling.
</P>
<P>
   In the memorandum, Parker said the government had failed to
present convincing arguments for keeping Lee in the Santa Fe County
jail pending trial, scheduled for Nov. 6. The judge also said he
wasn't convinced that the materials Lee is accused of mishandling
were the ''crown jewels'' of U.S. nuclear technology, as the
government contends.
</P>
<P>
   He added that the government ''has never presented direct
evidence that Dr. Lee intended to harm the United States or to
secure an advantage for a foreign nation.'' Prosecutors must prove
those two elements to convict Lee.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters say Lee, a naturalized citizen who was born in
Taiwan, is being singled out because of his ethnicity, a charge
prosecutors deny.
</P>
<P>
   The appellate court's decision surprised Parker, who said he had
been about to refuse the prosecution's bid for a stay.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant U.S. Attorney George Stamboulidis said he had been
unaware that the Justice Department had contacted the appeals court
until Parker read the court's order from the bench Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Parker had also set strict conditions on Lee's release,
including electronic monitoring, video surveillance, a phone tap,
restrictions on travel and severe limits on the number of people
with whom Lee could communicate.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of Lee: http://www.wenholee.org
</P>
<P>
   Department of Justice: http://www.usdoj.gov
</P>
<P>
   Los Alamos National Laboratory: http://www.lanl.gov/worldview
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-06-00 0043 </TRAILER>
