<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 01:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Historic newspaper the subject of 2 lawsuits  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) - A historic South Carolina newspaper
remains locked in a New York vault while judges in the two states
consider who is the paper's rightful owner.
</P>
<P>
   The Aug. 2-14, 1776, issue of the South-Carolina and American
General Gazette was the only South Carolina newspaper to print the
full text of the Declaration of Independence contemporary to the
event.
</P>
<P>
   The Post and Courier Foundation bought the paper in May in an
auction at Christie's in New York City. The foundation is a
nonprofit corporation created by The (Charleston) Post and Courier
newspaper to facilitate community giving.
</P>
<P>
   Since the auction, the Charleston Library Society has filed suit
in the Charleston County Court of Common Pleas against Christie's,
the foundation and Mark Mitchell, a rare-newspaper dealer from
Virginia who sold the paper through Christie's. The library society
says stains on the newspaper identify it as part of the society's
collection. The society's suit seeks to return the newspaper to the
society's collection.
</P>
<P>
   ''There clearly is disputed ownership, and I believe that both
parties think, in good faith, that they have title,'' said Ivan V.
Anderson, publisher of The Post and Courier. ''Nobody likes a
lawsuit, but in this case it is a way of bringing all the parties
together to try to clear up the title.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Post and Courier Foundation continues to be receptive to
working out an agreement so that this historic newspaper can be
returned to Charleston and shared with the community.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell, the dealer, also has sued in U.S. District Court in
New York against the Library Society, Christie's and a bidding
agent for the Post and Courier Foundation. Mitchell has asked the
court to give him the newspaper and for $131,600 - the amount he
would have gotten from the auction - for what he calls damage to
his reputation.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper has been locked in a vault at Christie's since the
auction house learned of the ownership dispute. Christie's says it
is a neutral party in the lawsuits and has asked the courts to take
possession of the newspaper until the issue is decided.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Lewis Kaplan in New York has scheduled a
meeting Sept. 14 with the parties to determine whether he should
stop the South Carolina court action until the federal case is
resolved.
</P>
<P>
   Although the newspaper came out weeks after the July 4 signing
of the Declaration, it was a breaking news story because it took so
long for news to travel from Philadelphia to Charleston. The paper
reports the adoption of the Declaration both in Philadelphia and,
subsequently, in Charleston.
</P>
<P>
   In July, Anderson said The Post and Courier Foundation bought
the paper wanting ''to return the only known copy of this important
edition of the Gazette to Charleston and to find a way to share it
with the community.''
</P>
<P>
   At that time, Mitchell said that when he first bought the paper
he called the Charleston Library Society to assess its rarity. He
said the society did not indicate then that it might be the
rightful owner.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was ecstatic when I heard the paper was bought by someone in
Charleston,'' Mitchell said in July. ''I'd like to see it come back
to where it's from. ... I'm devastated by this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
