<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 1 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Tuesday, Sept. 5, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
World Leaders Assemble for U.N. Millennium Summit
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Secretary-General Kofi Annan Tuesday urged the kings,
generals and presidents descending on New York for the U.N. Millennium Summit to
use the unprecedented meeting to forge peace and end poverty in the 21st
century. But some heads of state are expected to use the three days of speeches,
discussions and meetings beginning tomorrow to push their own agendas --
including those that are critical of the United States. In a taste of what may
come, North Korea denounced the United States as a ''rogue state'' Tuesday,
claiming the government was responsible for allegedly ordering the strip search
of members of the delegation as they switched planes in Germany.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Mexico's Congress Gets Under Way
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY -- Mexico's most diverse congress in history launched its first
working sessions Tuesday driven by a necessity to negotiate and buoyed by
promises of consensus over partisanship. The new political dynamics pose a great
challenge to President-elect Vicente Fox, who will have to barter like no chief
executive before him. Historically, presidents of the long-ruling Institutional
Revolutionary Party simply passed down legislative initiatives to be
rubber-stamped by loyal soldiers in the party-dominated congresses.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Scientist's Lawyers File Petition
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) -- Lawyers for jailed Los Alamos nuclear scientist Wen
Ho Lee, whose scheduled release on bail was blocked at the last minute Friday,
made another plea Tuesday to the 10th U.S. Circuit Appeals Court to release him.
The petition was their second appeal to the 10th Circuit, which on Friday
superseded a bail-release order that had been signed by U.S. District Judge
James Parker. Defense attorney John Cline said he hadn't heard from the appeals
court since filing a petition Friday for reconsideration of its ruling.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Barak Rules Out Breakthrough in Mideat Peacemaking
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak on Tuesday ruled out any
breakthrough in Mideast peacemaking unless Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat
changes his stand on terms of a settlement. Barak's office made the statement
after the Israeli met with Secretary of State Madeleine Albright to preview
President Clinton's planned back-to-back sessions Wednesday with the two Mideast
leaders on the fringes of the U.N. Millennium Summit. Barak's summit with Arafat
at the presidential retreat in Maryland collapsed in July largely over Arafat's
rejection of an offer by Barak for limited control over east Jerusalem.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Mich. Under Court Restraining Order
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   DETROIT (AP) -- A federal judge Tuesday extended a temporary restraining
order forbidding the state from requiring drug testing for welfare recipients.
The state last October began requiring welfare applicants in a handful of
Michigan communities to provide urine samples for drug screening before they
could be considered for benefits. Under the rules of the state's pilot program,
the drug test results wouldn't affect access to food stamps and police wouldn't
be notified, but applicants who tested positive for drugs would be sent to
treatment and could gradually lose benefits if they failed to go.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Bush Unveils $158 Billion Drug Plan
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ALLENTOWN, Pa. (AP) -- Republican presidential candidate, George W. Bush
outlined a $158 billion prescription drug plan Tuesday that he said would offer
senior citizens more choices and quicker coverage than Al Gore's competing
Medicare expansion. The Bush plan would fundamentally restructure Medicare,
forcing the government plan to compete with private plans for the first time. In
comparison, Bush said Gore's $253 billion 10-year plan would provide ''resources
without reform.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Senate Moves On China Trade Vote
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- As the Senate returned from its summer recess China trade
was the first order of business Tuesday, with leaders of both parties determined
to approve the normalization of trade relations before lawmakers close shop to
campaign before the November elections. Passing the bill this year is
''profoundly important for the country,'' said Sen. Max Baucus, D-Mont., a
leading advocate of widening trade with China.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Japan's Key Stock Index Up
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- The Tokyo Stock Exchange's main index edged higher Wednesday
morning after six straight losing sessions. The Nikkei gained 8.89 points, or
0.05 percent, to 16,461.16 at the end of the morning session.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Yankees 10, Royals 5
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- David Cone went down too early to get the win, but
reliever Dwight Gooden never lost the New York Yankees' early lead Tuesday night
in a 10-5 victory over the Kansas City Royals. No. 9 hitter Jose Vizcaino went
4-for-5 and Scott Brosius hit an eighth-inning grand slam for the Yankees, who
maintained their six-game lead over second-place Boston in the AL East.
AP NewsBrief by VINCENT K. WILLIS 
</P>
