<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 02:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Miami-Dade Mayor Faces Tough Fight  </HEADLINE>
By ROBERT TANNER
<TEXT>
<P>
   Miami-Dade Mayor Alex Penelas fought to avoid a runoff Tuesday
as nine challengers sought to deny him a second term after months
of tumult over the Elian Gonzalez case.
</P>
<P>
   With 89 percent of precincts reporting, Penelas had 118,391
votes, or 51 percent, to county Commissioner Miguel Diaz de la
Portilla's 47,847 votes, or 21 percent. Businessman Jay Love had
46,728 votes, or 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Penelas needed to win more than 50 percent to win Tuesday's
general election outright and avoid a runoff.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, in primaries in Florida and Nevada, favored
candidates for open Senate and House seats handily defeated their
opposition.
</P>
<P>
   In Florida, Democrat Bill Nelson and GOP Rep. Bill McCollum
easily won their parties' nominations for an open Senate seat,
setting up a competitive race in the fall with national importance.
</P>
<P>
   In Nevada, former Republican Rep. John Ensign swiftly won the
GOP primary for an open Senate seat, defeating two little-known
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   In the Miami-Dade race, Diaz de la Portilla, who lost the
campaign fund-raising race to Penelas by a 4-to-1 margin, said
Penelas ''split the community'' when he vowed that local police
would not help federal authorities return Elian to his father in
Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Penelas later said police would help keep the peace, and has
emphasized ''healing the wounds'' left by the boy's case. The Elian
furor has not been a prominent part of the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   With 98 percent of precincts reporting, Nelson, the state
insurance commissioner, got 675,731 votes, or 77 percent, to win
the nomination to seek the seat of retiring GOP Sen. Connie Mack.
McCollum had 649,544 votes, or 81 percent, for his party's
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats, who have made inroads in the South in recent
years, hope to take the Senate seat given up by Mack, who is
retiring after two terms.
</P>
<P>
   The seat left vacant by McCollum, a 10-term GOP member of
Congress who is hoping to succeed Mack, becomes part of the
national battle for control of the House, as does a Republican seat
left open by retiring four-term Rep. Tillie Fowler.
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Bill Sublette and first-time candidate Ric Keller
split the GOP vote 43 percent to 31 percent and went to a runoff
for the nomination for McCollum's seat near Orlando. The winner
will face Democrat Linda Chapin, who was unopposed.
</P>
<P>
   In the race for Fowler's seat near Jacksonville, former state
Senate President Ander Crenshaw won the GOP nomination. Retired
motel owner-manager Tom Sullivan won the Democratic nomination.
</P>
<P>
   In Nevada, Democratic Sen. Richard Bryan's decision to retire
after two terms set off a scramble. John Ensign, a veterinarian and
former two-term GOP congressman, easily faced two little-known
candidates in his bid for the Republican nomination. Ensign lost
his 1998 bid to unseat the state's senior senator, Democrat Harry
Reid, by 428 votes.
</P>
<P>
   With 95 percent of precincts reporting, Ensign won the
nomination with 88 percent of the vote. In the fall, he will face
Las Vegas lawyer Ed Bernstein, who was unopposed for the Democratic
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Also in Florida, a white sheriff defeated a black police chief
who challenged him in a Democratic race rocked by allegations of
racism. Gadsden County Sheriff W.A. Woodham, in office for 29 years
in the state's only majority-black county, defeated Rodney Moore by
a 52 percent-48 percent margin.
</P>
<P>
   Moore was arrested last month and charged with ticket-fixing and
other corruption. He, along with many of the state's top black
leaders, complained of racism. The county is west of Tallahassee in
the Panhandle.
</P>
<P>
   Woodham faces nominal Republican opposition in the fall.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-06-00 0210 </TRAILER>
