<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 02:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Vows To Create High-Tech Jobs  </HEADLINE>
By MIKE GLOVER
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND (AP) -- Al Gore is offering up a voluminous and richly
detailed spending plan for the nation, promising to create 10
million high-tech jobs, send poverty to historic lows and boost
family income by a third if his policies are put in place, aides
say.
</P>
<P>
   Senior aides familiar with Gore's plan, titled ''Prosperity for
America's Families,'' said one linchpin is paying down the debt,
casting the Democratic presidential candidate as the fiscal
conservative in his fight with Republican George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Gore described his speech Wednesday at Cleveland State
University, in which he essentially will lay out the first budget
he would send to Congress if elected, as ''comprehensive and
detailed and chock-full of specifics.'' It is part of his ongoing
effort to argue to voters that he is offering them specifics and
real choices while Bush is serving up vague proposals.
</P>
<P>
   The 191-page, 69,000-word blueprint has 12 chapters and is
stuffed with charts, graphs and footnotes.
</P>
<P>
   By adopting more conservative budget projections, Gore also
would set aside a $300 billion ''surplus reserve fund'' to cover
any shortfalls.
</P>
<P>
   Among his promises:
</P>
<P>
   -- Increase real family income by a third over the next decade,
from this year's average of $47,000. Aides said a combination of
productivity increases, as well as new worker training would make
that happen.
</P>
<P>
   -- Boost home ownership rates to 70 percent, largely by paying
off the debt. Aides said that would keep interest rates low. He has
pledged to eliminate the debt by 2012, with most paid by 2010. Gore
also wants to boost low-income tax credits and increase community
investment incentives for lenders.
</P>
<P>
   -- Reduce poverty rates to below 10 percent for the first time in
history, largely by increasing the minimum wage, bolstering
welfare-to-work efforts and increasing Social Security benefits for
elderly women.
</P>
<P>
   -- Double the number of people with accumulated savings of more
than $50,000. There are currently 32 million such families, and
Gore said he would boost that number largely through new retirement
savings incentives he has proposed.
</P>
<P>
   -- Increase college attendance and graduation rates. Currently,
67 percent of high school seniors go to college. Gore wants to
increase that to 75 percent. His key proposal is to make up to
$10,000 in college tuition tax deductible.
</P>
<P>
   --Create 10 million new, high-tech jobs. With unemployment low,
the need is to focus more on better paying jobs.
</P>
<P>
   -- Reduce by half the pay gap between men and women, largely by
toughening enforcement of discrimination laws. Women currently make
73 cents for every $1 men earn.
</P>
<P>
   -- Cut the tax burden on average families, earning $47,000, to
the lowest level in 50 years within the first two years in office.
Aides argued that Gore's targeted tax cuts would do that because
they would go on the books quicker than Bush's larger $1.3 trillion
across-the-board reduction.
</P>
<P>
   By casting himself as a fiscal conservative while stressing debt
reduction, the vice president seeks to paint Bush as the big
spender. He argues that much of the nation's economic prosperity
comes because President Clinton has kept the nation's books in
order and interest rates low.
</P>
<P>
   His aides contend that the package of proposals Bush has
outlined -- including for tax cuts, Medicare drug coverage and
education -- would leave the nation $2.8 trillion in debt, while
Gore proposes to ''make America debt-free by 2012.''
</P>
<P>
   Most polls have shown Gore gaining on Bush since the Democratic
convention last month. He has campaigned on health care and other
proposals since then, dwelling at length on the details.
</P>
<P>
   He says much of his improvement in public opinion has come
because many voters are just now tuning into the presidential
campaign and are hungry for a real discussion of issues.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-06-00 0217 </TRAILER>
