<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 03:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Presses for Its Spending Demands  </HEADLINE>
By ALAN FRAM
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- While congressional Republicans are eager to
wrap up legislative business for the year and hit the campaign
trail, White House officials say they are in no hurry to cut budget
deals unless President Clinton's spending demands are met.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not the calendar'' that gives the White House leverage in
Congress' waning weeks, White House budget chief Jack Lew said in
an interview. ''It's the substance that gives us the ability to
hold our ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers began returning to the Capitol on Tuesday after their
August recess hoping to adjourn in five or six weeks. Most are
yearning to get home for this fall's elections, in which control of
the White House and Congress are up for grabs.
</P>
<P>
   But first, the 11 remaining spending bills for fiscal 2001,
which starts Oct. 1, must become law. Only two spending measures
have been signed, covering most defense programs.
</P>
<P>
   The unfinished bills cover the budgets of 13 Cabinet-level
agencies from the Agriculture Department to Veterans' Affairs, plus
spending for Congress, the courts and foreign aid. Clinton wants
about $20 billion more than lawmakers have been ready to spend, and
the two sides also differ over local control over education
programs, mining and other environmental issues, and other policy
disputes.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans say they are ready to do what it takes to get those
bills signed, including giving Clinton much of the extra money he
needs. But many of them say they believe the administration prefers
a lengthy confrontation that would minimize GOP accomplishments,
highlight Democratic issues and keep Republicans from going home to
campaign for re-election.
</P>
<P>
   ''They want to get finished,'' Senate Budget Committee Chairman
Pete Domenici, R-N.M., said of his colleagues Tuesday. ''But
there's a concern about whether or not the White House and
Democrats want to get things done.''
</P>
<P>
   Both sides insist there will be no government shutdown, such as
the 1995 and 1996 closures of federal agencies that the public
blamed on aggressive Republicans in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're not looking for that kind of confrontation,'' Lew said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Democrats must be careful to not press their hand too
hard and risk a public backlash, given that the battle for the
White House and control of the House is expected to be close.
Democrats even have an outside chance at winning a Senate majority.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides know the GOP will have to yield to most of Clinton's
demands for billions of dollars in extra domestic and foreign aid
spending before remaining bills can be signed and lawmakers can
return to their districts. But realizing their leverage, Democrats
say they will be aggressive in pressing their budget demands.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're not going anywhere until we're satisfied,'' Senate
Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Though spending legislation will be Congress' chief focus in its
remaining weeks, lawmakers also will devote time to other issues.
These include some measures that have virtually no chance of
becoming law but will allow one party or the other to make
political statements in time for the nationwide elections on Nov.
7.
</P>
<P>
   The House plans to vote Thursday to override Clinton's veto of a
bill phasing out estate taxes. That effort and one next week
against Clinton's veto of a bill cutting taxes for many married
couples are virtually sure to fail but will let Republicans argue
that taxes would decrease with a Republican in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans hope, however, to pass tax bills this year expanding
the amounts people can contribute to IRAs and 401(k) plans,
repealing the 3 percent telephone excise tax and providing $6
billion in tax breaks over five years to spur investment in poor
urban and rural areas.
</P>
<P>
   They also hope for small business tax breaks that they have
attached to a bill designed to meet Clinton's demand to boost the
$5.15-an-hour minimum wage by $1 hourly by Jan. 1, 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Daschle said Democrats will continue trying to force
votes on issues they want to spotlight for the elections, such as
increased rights for managed-care patients, gun safety and the
minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
   Hopes for approval this session of broad new prescription drug
coverage are all but dead, amid partisan differences over the
program's scope and the desire by some Democrats to keep the
dispute as a campaign issue.
</P>
<P>
   Some Senate Republicans already are discussing a scaled-down,
$25 billion to $40 billion version over five years that would give
states money to cover some low-income senior citizens, which they
think would let the GOP argue it had at least advanced something on
prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   GOP presidential nominee George W. Bush on Tuesday unveiled a
Medicare prescription drug proposal that would give states $48
billion over the next four years to help low-income seniors pay for
drugs in the short term while a broader, $110 billion overhaul of
Medicare was being phased in.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's opponent, Vice President Al Gore, has proposed adding a
prescription drug program to Medicare over 10 years at an estimated
cost of $253 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate also seems likely to provide final legislative
approval next week to a bill that would permanently extend normal
trade relations to China.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-06-00 0308 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
