<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Gains 29 As Nasdaq Slips 13  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks opened mixed Wednesday on the news of a
major deal in the financial services industry, surging oil prices
and a new low for the Euro currency overseas.
</P>
<P>
   In the first hour of trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones
industrial average was up 29.22 at 11,289.83.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index was off 13.30 at 4,129.88, The
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was up 1.42 at 1,508.50
</P>
<P>
   Citigroup, the nation's biggest financial services company, said
it will buy lending company Associates First Capital for about
$31.1 billion in stock. The deal should speed up Citigroup's global
expansion in lending to consumers, giving it control of the U.S.'s
largest publicly traded finance company and Japan's fifth largest
consumer finance company.
</P>
<P>
   Citigroup fell $2.06 to $55.88 in early trading, but shares of
Associates First Capital jumped $11 -- more than 40 percent -- to
$39.38.
</P>
<P>
   Across the ocean, European money traders Wednesday drove the
continent's common currency to record lows against the yen and
dollar because of concerns that European politicians and the
European Central Bank do not agree on monetary policy.
</P>
<P>
   The euro fell to 87.88 cents, smashing through last Thursday's
previous low of 88.37 cents. The currency also fell to a new low
against the yen, falling to 93.00 yen from its previous benchmark
of 93.76 yen.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Wednesday in London, prices of Brent crude for delivery
in October hit a new 10-year high, rising to $33.50 a barrel. Crude
for delivery in October flirted with a nine-year high of $34.37 on
the New York Mercantile Exchange, reaching $34.35 before declining
somewhat to $34.15.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index was down 0.23 at 538.79.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 0.32 percent. In
afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was down 0.58 percent,
Britain's FT-SE 100 was down 0.60 percent, and France's CAC-40 was
down 0.63 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
