<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 10:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Jumps 111; Nasdaq Falls 14  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Blue chip stocks soared today, boosted by news
of a major deal in the financial services industry, surging oil
prices and a new low for the euro currency overseas.
</P>
<P>
   In early trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average was up 111.35 at 11,371.96.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index was off 14.21 at 4,128.97. The
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was up 4.21 at 1,511.29.
</P>
<P>
   Citigroup, the nation's biggest financial services company, said
it will buy lending company Associates First Capital for about
$31.1 billion in stock. The deal should speed Citigroup's global
expansion in lending to consumers, giving it control of the U.S.'s
largest publicly traded finance company and Japan's fifth largest
consumer finance company.
</P>
<P>
   Citigroup fell $2.19 to $55.75 early Wednesday, but shares of
Associates First Capital jumped $11.44 -- nearly 41 percent -- to
$39.41.
</P>
<P>
   The euro fell to 87.88 cents, smashing through last Thursday's
previous low of 88.37 cents. The currency also fell to a new low
against the yen, falling to 93.00 yen from its previous benchmark
of 93.76 yen.
</P>
<P>
   The downturn could translate into a boost for U.S. currency and
markets, as those previously invested in the European exchanges
look for somewhere else to put their money.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Wednesday in London, prices of Brent crude for delivery
in October hit a new 10-year high, rising to $33.50 a barrel. Crude
for delivery in October flirted with a 10-year high of $34.37 on
the New York Mercantile Exchange, reaching $34.35 before declining
somewhat to $34.
</P>
<P>
   Higher prices could result in a corresponding increase in oil
company stock prices, although in early trading it wasn't clear if
it would. Shares of Exxon Mobil were up $1.19 to $84, but
Schlumberger, the oil services company, was down 38 cents at
$85.31.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues narrowly led decliners on the New York Stock
Exchange. Volume came to 135.16 million shares, compared to 110.35
million the previous session.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index was down 0.84 at 538.18.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 0.32 percent. In
afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was down 0.58 percent,
Britain's FT-SE 100 was down 0.60 percent, and France's CAC-40 was
down 0.63 percent.
</P>
