<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Gains 75; Nasdaq Loses 62  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Blue chip stocks moved higher Wednesday, boosted
by news of a major deal in the financial services industry,
increased U.S. productivity, surging oil prices and a new low for
the euro currency overseas.
</P>
<P>
   In late morning trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average was up 75.10 at 11,335.71.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index was off 61.50 at 4,081.68. The
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was down 2.64 at 1,504.45.
</P>
<P>
   Citigroup, the nation's biggest financial services company, said
it will buy lending company Associates First Capital for about
$31.1 billion in stock. The deal should speed Citigroup's global
expansion in lending to consumers, giving it control of the U.S.'s
largest publicly traded finance company and Japan's fifth largest
consumer finance company.
</P>
<P>
   Citigroup fell $2.81 to $55.13 in morning trading Wednesday, but
shares of Associates First Capital jumped $10.88 -- nearly 39
percent -- to $38.88.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Labor Department said Americans' productivity, a
key measure of rising living standards, surged at a 5.7 percent
rate in the second quarter. The strong gain pushed unit labor
costs, a key gauge of inflation pressures, down by a rate of 0.4
percent, the lowest since the end of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, the euro fell to 87.88 cents, smashing through last
Thursday's previous low of 88.37 cents. The currency also fell to a
new low against the yen, falling to 93.00 yen from its previous
benchmark of 93.76 yen.
</P>
<P>
   The downturn could translate into a boost for U.S. currency and
markets, as those previously invested in the European exchanges
look for somewhere else to put their money.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Wednesday in London, prices of Brent crude for delivery
in October hit a new 10-year high, rising to $33.50 a barrel. Crude
for delivery in October flirted with a 10-year high of $34.37 on
the New York Mercantile Exchange, reaching $34.35 before declining
somewhat to $34. Higher oil prices are considered by some to be a
potential inflationary pressure, but at least one analyst wasn't
worried.
</P>
<P>
   ''If this truly was a long-term inflationary threat, that would
be showing up at the bond market in form of higher interest rates
and we don't see that happening,'' said Alan Skrainka, chief market
strategist at Edward Jones of St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   In tech stocks, movement was downward. Shares of Micron
Technology fell $7.75 to $70.50 after Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette
downgraded the stock from ''buy'' to ''underperform.'' Shares of
circuit maker Applied Microcircuits were down $9.69 at $180.13.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues narrowly led decliners on the New York Stock
Exchange. Volume came to 314.39 million shares, compared to 266.56
million the previous session.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index was down 3.19 at 535.83.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
