<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 25 Killed in Somalia Violence  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOGADISHU, Somalia (AP) -- Fighting involving hundreds of Somali
gunmen armed with heavy machine guns and rocket-propelled grenades
left at least 25 people dead and 18 injured in clashes in villages
north of Mogadishu, witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
   The clashes lasted for more than five hours Monday in villages
near Johwar, 55 miles north of the capital.
</P>
<P>
   The violence began when more than 100 gunmen from the Galjaal
subclan attacked a village largely inhabited by members of the
Hawadle subclan, witnesses who asked not to be identified said by
telephone Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Somalis meeting in neighboring Djibouti elected
their first president and parliament in a decade, but neither has
yet established a permanent presence in the wartorn country. A
government has yet to be named, and there is no public security
force to impose order.
</P>
<P>
   Somalia has not had a functioning central government since
January 1991 when President Mohamed Siad Barre was ousted and the
country dissolved into clan-based fiefdoms controlled by armed
bands.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of Monday's clashes was believed to be related to an
incident last week in which Hawadle gunmen ambushed a truck and 20
people were killed. Johwar and its surrounding villages were tense
Tuesday, but there were no reports of renewed fighting.
</P>
</TEXT>
