<HEADLINE> Entertainment Highlights in History  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Entertainment highlights during the week of Sept.
10-16:
<TEXT>
<P>
   80 years ago: The ad in Variety for the new film ''One Week''
called Buster Keaton ''a new stellar comedian.''
</P>
<P>
   55 years ago: ''Back to Bataan,'' starring John Wayne and
Anthony Quinn, opened.
</P>
<P>
   45 years ago: ''Gunsmoke,'' which began on radio in 1952,
premiered on CBS. The program ran for nearly 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   And Little Richard recorded ''Tutti Frutti.''
</P>
<P>
   35 years ago: ''The Jack Paar Show'' had its final broadcast.
Paar's dog was the only member of the TV studio audience.
</P>
<P>
   And ''Lost in Space'' and ''Green Acres'' premiered on CBS.
</P>
<P>
   30 years ago: More than 18,000 people attended a Woody Guthrie
memorial concert at the Hollywood Bowl. Joan Baez, Bob Dylan and
Guthrie's son, Arlo, were among the performers.
</P>
<P>
   Joan Crawford's last movie opened. It was ''Trog,'' a horror
film.
</P>
<P>
   And a poll in Britain's Melody Maker magazine found that Led
Zeppelin was the most popular band. It was the first time in eight
years that the Beatles had not topped the list.
</P>
<P>
   25 years ago: Bob Dylan appeared on a TV special about music
talent scout John Hammond. In the early 1960s, the staff at
Columbia Records had referred to the newly signed Dylan as
''Hammond's folly.''
</P>
<P>
   20 years ago: David Bowie opened on Broadway in the title role
of Bernard Pomerance's play ''The Elephant Man.''
</P>
<P>
   15 years ago: Jane Fonda, Anne Bancroft and Meg Tilly starred in
the movie ''Agnes of God.''
</P>
<P>
   Sting began his first solo tour in San Diego, Calif., to promote
his album ''Dream of the Blue Turtles.''
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Taylor was named Commander of Arts and Letters,
France's highest award for excellence in the arts.
</P>
<P>
   Jackie Gleason, a bandleader before he became a full-time
comedian, was invited out of the audience to conduct the Chicago
Footwarmers Hot Dance Orchestra through a 1920s number. The concert
was in Chicago's Raccoon Club. Gleason's character on ''The
Honeymooners'' TV show was a member of the International Order of
the Friendly Raccoons.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Golden Girls'' sitcom debuted on NBC, starring Bea Arthur,
Betty White, Rue McClanahan and Estelle Getty.
</P>
<P>
   And Greta Garbo celebrated her 80th birthday with a few friends.
</P>
<P>
   10 years ago: The film ''Postcards From the Edge'' opened,
starring Shirley MacLaine, Meryl Streep and Dennis Quaid.
</P>
<P>
   George Michael's second solo album, ''Listen Without
Prejudice,'' was released.
</P>
<P>
   And the five highest-earning entertainers were, in order, Bill
Cosby, Michael Jackson, the Rolling Stones, Steven Spielberg and
New Kids on the Block.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago: TV viewers voted to keep the swimsuit
competition in the Miss America pageant.
</P>
<P>
   Fans sang one of Earth, Wind &AMP; Fire's hits, ''Shining Star,'' as
the rock band received a star on Hollywood's Walk of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   And ''ER'' won eight Emmy Awards, equaling the record held since
1981 by ''Hill Street Blues'' for most wins by a new TV series and
most wins in one year.
</P>
<P>
   One year ago: The guitar John Lennon was playing the day he met
Paul McCartney in 1957 was sold at auction for $224,000. Sotheby's
billed it as the earliest Beatles-related guitar to come on the
market.
</P>
<P>
   Spoken 15 years ago:
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm the kind of guy who'll hand the tapes into the record
company, steal the tapes back and work on them again.'' -- Maurice
White, creator of the rock group Earth, Wind &AMP; Fire, calling
himself a workaholic and an overachiever.
</P>
<P>
   Spoken five years ago:
</P>
<P>
   ''I encourage people to vote. In case we ever stumble into a
democracy, we'll be in practice.'' -- Rock guitarist Little Steven
Van Zandt.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
