<DOCNO> APW20000906.0039 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 12:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Devo Keeps Evolving  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN ROGERS
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- One might ask: Whatever happened to Devo, the
seminal '70s band that dressed in those funky George Jetson
spacesuits and played futuristic music?
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, the band that once represented the
''de-evolution of popular music'' went through its own evolution,
starting out as post-punk pioneers -- its 1978 debut album ''Q: Are
We Not Men? A: We Are Devo'' became a cult sensation -- and emerging
on the other side as purveyors of popular children's music.
</P>
<P>
   That's old news to true Devo fans -- or at least Devo fans with
small children, says Mark Mothersbaugh, the band's frontman, writer
and lead Devotee. But Mothersbaugh sometimes sees a distinct double
take when people learn that the creative force behind ''Whip It,''
''Mongoloid'' and ''Jocko Homo'' also wrote the gentle, infectious
theme to the ''Rugrats'' children's television show on the
Nickelodeon cable channel.
</P>
<P>
   ''But not so much at this point, because we've done a number of
things for a while now,'' says Mothersbaugh, a friendly,
soft-spoken man with a sly sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, for 10 years he and his fellow Devotees have done the
music for ''Rugrats'' and its spinoff movies, including ''Rugrats
in Paris: The Movie,'' which is due out later this year.
</P>
<P>
   Devo's latest project is a Mothersbaugh-produced album, ''Heroes
&AMP; Villains,'' featuring music inspired by ''The Powerpuff Girls,''
one of the most cutting edge of the new wave of TV shows aimed at
the just-out-of-diapers set.
</P>
<P>
   The girls, as any 4-year-old with access to the Cartoon Network
knows, were created by Professor Utonium, who accidentally added
''Chemical X'' to his mixture of ''sugar and spice and everything
nice.''
</P>
<P>
   The result was a trio of crime-fighting heroines with perfect
hair, the latest designer clothes and the occasional fit of pique
common to kindergartners.
</P>
<P>
   However, ''The Powerpuff Girls: Heroes &AMP; Villains'' (Rhino
Records) is not a soundtrack but a collection of songs inspired by
the antics of Blossom, Buttercup and Bubbles.
</P>
<P>
   And with music from such alternative bands as Shonen Knife, The
Apples in Stereo and Devo, it is that musical oddity: a record with
appeal for both the under 5 and over 30 crowds.
</P>
<P>
   That's not necessarily what Mothersbaugh had in mind.
</P>
<P>
   From the time he was 7 -- when he got his first pair of
eyeglasses -- all Mothersbaugh wanted to do was create artistic
images -- first visually and later with sound.
</P>
<P>
   ''For all intents and purposes, I was legally blind,'' he says,
explaining both his childhood and those bottle-bottom-thick
eyeglasses that he wears. ''I couldn't read the big E on the eye
chart from 5 feet away. I remember the first day I got glasses. I
saw clouds, birds, the sun. ... It was a pretty amazing
discovery.''
</P>
<P>
   Inspired by a teacher, he set out to draw it all -- except on
Saturday afternoons when he had to take his weekly organ lessons.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was absolutely certain music had been invented to torture
me,'' he says of those days.
</P>
<P>
   That opinion would change one Sunday night in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a cliche, but I was watching Ed Sullivan. And he said,
'Tonight, we have something special for you youngsters, the
Beatles!''' recalls Mothersbaugh, doing a fair impersonation of
Sullivan, host of a popular variety show.
</P>
<P>
   At that moment, Mothersbaugh came to this realization: ''So
that's why I had to learn music; why I had to spend all those years
being tortured.''
</P>
<P>
   Within days, he was playing in a band.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were awful, of course.''
</P>
<P>
   A decade later, when Mothersbaugh and fellow Devotee Jerry
Casale crossed paths at Ohio's Kent State University, the Beatles
were gone and rock music had grown stale, drifting toward big,
showy arena performances that shouted ''that's entertainment'' more
than ''that's different.''
</P>
<P>
   Bored by it all, the two amused themselves by melding Casale's
blues guitar riffs with Mothersbaugh's electronic keyboard
experimentation. The result sounded so strange, their brothers were
the only ones who would play it. To make it even more weird,
Mothersbaugh began taking old record albums and cutting little
loops into the tracks.
</P>
<P>
   ''You'd get these skips in the vinyl,'' he recalls, breaking
into a repetitive, Devo-like voice. ''And I'd write music on guitar
or a little keyboard along with that. And it was just awful cool.''
</P>
<P>
   Cool enough that when someone at A&AMP;M Records heard ''Jocko
Homo,'' the company sent for Devo, which was now Mothersbaugh,
Casale and their respective siblings, Bob and Bob.
</P>
<P>
   The label declined to sign them, but Devo decided to stay in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ''We had vowed once we crossed the state line from Akron, Ohio,
that we were never going back,'' Mothersbaugh says, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   At the height of its popularity, Devo was hailed as the
forerunner of New Wave music, introducing a sci-fi sound to the
music world with its heavy synthesizers and electronic music. The
group released five albums between 1978 and 1982, but as the '80s
wore on, the band was relegated to cult status and critical
indifference.
</P>
<P>
   Then Pee-wee Herman needed someone to do the music for a new
children's show, ''Pee-wee's Playhouse,'' and he called on
Mothersbaugh.
</P>
<P>
   The offer came just at the right time. Devo was an alternative
band hitting middle age, unhappy with its record contract and not
particularly happy with the music business or life on the road.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's like a really great job when you're in your 20s,'' say
Mothersbaugh, 50, of being a rock star. ''In your 30s, it's kind of
OK. And when you're in your 40s, it sucks. You realize that you
kind of should be doing something else.''
</P>
<P>
   So that's what he and the other Devotees do, working at their
Los Angeles-based company Mutato Muzika and scoring such films as
''Happy Gilmore'' and ''Rocky and Bullwinkle,'' doing commercials
and cartoons, even taking the occasional acting gig.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were the monkeys who escaped from the circus train in the
first 'Rugrats' movie,'' he points out proudly.
</P>
<P>
   They have even done the occasional Devo gig, touring with Beck
not that long ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''But, you know,'' adds Mothersbaugh contentedly, ''it's OK to
move on in life, too.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.rhino.com/
</P>
