<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Neil LaBute Might Bite You  </HEADLINE>
By DOUGLAS J. ROWE
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Careful. Don't get too close.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, ''Nurse Betty'' is a screwball comedy from the director of
those searing indictments of human nature, ''In the Company of
Men'' and ''Your Friends &AMP; Neighbors.''
</P>
<P>
   No, a new Panglossian Neil LaBute is not sitting in front of
you.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you think so, come closer. Let's see if you're right. Maybe
you can pet me, and maybe I'll bite your finger off,'' the
37-year-old director-screenwriter-playwright says with a smile -- as
you keep your hands to yourself.
</P>
<P>
   ''Nurse Betty'' stars Renee Zellweger as a woman so shocked by
her husband's murder (at the hands of hit men Morgan Freeman and
Chris Rock) that she believes her favorite soap opera is real -- and
that she's the long-lost love of its leading man (Greg Kinnear).
It's a little like ''The Wizard of Oz'' meets ''Harvey'': She's a
dreamy gal from Kansas with an imaginary friend -- except he's
played by a flesh-and-blood actor and she travels cross-country to
meet him.
</P>
<P>
   ''By going a little wacky, she actually ends up getting to that
thing that her dreams are made of,'' LaBute says.
</P>
<P>
   His writing-directing debut, ''In the Company of Men,'' which
won the Filmmakers Trophy at the 1997 Sundance Film Festival, is
the story of two men who conspire to leave a pretty, deaf woman in
a crumpled heap by wooing her and then dumping her. ''Your Friends
&AMP; Neighbors'' in 1998 focused on emotional treachery and sexual
dysfunction among people who supposedly like each other.
</P>
<P>
   The camerawork in ''Nurse Betty'' has a fluidity that LaBute's
previous work didn't. And its characters enjoy a certain redemption
and transcendence unlike those in his first two films.
</P>
<P>
   But ''Nurse Betty'' contains some lacerating violence, and it
qualifies as a dark -- as well as a screwball -- comedy. So it's not
totally dissimilar to his earlier movies: The men are
''questionable'' -- to use LaBute's word -- and they're after a
woman.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think this has suddenly made me a sunnier person. I'm
relatively sunny as it goes,'' LaBute says. ''I like, as a viewer
as well as a filmmaker, things that challenge me and make me sit up
and go, 'Whoa, what are they doing here?' So I'm sure I'll continue
to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, his fans might be forgiven for thinking his cynicism and
disgust with the human condition have abated.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've briefly given them a grace period before moving on in my
assessment of humankind,'' the burly, bearded and bespectacled
LaBute says. ''As a writer, I still continue to want to examine,
pretty ruthlessly, the way people behave.''
</P>
<P>
   One publication called his earlier films ''the meanest movies in
Hollywood.'' But he's also been compared to David Mamet, and The
Wall Street Journal has ventured that ''your reaction to Mr.
LaBute's work is a highly personal matter, depending on one's
convictions about human nature and one's threshold for emotional
queasiness.''
</P>
<P>
   LaBute, who grew up outside Spokane, Wash., earned a master's
degree in theater and film history from the University of Kansas
and studied dramatic writing at New York University.
</P>
<P>
   He decided to direct ''Nurse Betty'' because he never imagined
writing or directing a film like it, and he liked the idea that
people would be surprised that he even could make such a film.
</P>
<P>
   ''You should constantly try and surprise an audience. You should
make an audience never quite know where you're going to go, because
I think audiences like to be surprised and not be able to pin you
down completely.''
</P>
<P>
   It's also the first film he's directed that he didn't also
write, although he's directed plenty of theater productions written
by others.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's a distance in it that comes from not writing it. From
saying, 'I'm working more like an editor.' I'm looking at it and
saying, 'I can see what works here, what doesn't, what needs to be
worked on.' In a way, you don't have that feeling when you've
written something; you're really close to it, and it's hard to back
away and figure it out.''
</P>
<P>
   LaBute says it's unfortunate that ''In the Company of Men'' was
tagged with a misogynistic monicker because ''it's hard to shake
something like that.''
</P>
<P>
   His rebuttal: People should see the film firsthand because they
would see it was the men who come out looking bad, not the women.
</P>
<P>
   ''You hate it when things get misread, but then sometimes it's
just inevitable,'' he says, because people often read a thumbnail
quote or review and don't know the work itself.
</P>
<P>
   He had a similar problem when the Mormon church was upset by the
Mormon characters in ''Bash,'' his trio of one-acts produced
off-Broadway last year.
</P>
<P>
   A graduate of Brigham Young University and a practicing Mormon
(''practicing, but probably in need of more practice''), LaBute
says he's not at odds with the church, adding, ''In terms of my
work, I think it's sometimes off-putting to them.''
</P>
<P>
   It can even be off-putting to his wife Lisa, a family therapist.
(They have a 12-year-old daughter and a 9-year-old son.) ''Like
anything, there's stuff that she likes and stuff that she
disapproves of,'' he reports.
</P>
<P>
   As cozy and life-affirming as his home life sounds, he has a
gimlet-eyed view of the world.
</P>
<P>
   ''Who was it that had that lovely quote? It was like Flaubert
who said, 'Live your life quietly so you can be savage in your
work.' Or something like that -- I'm paraphrasing it,'' LaBute says.
''But yes. Two different things. Two beasts. The way you want to
write about things and the way you live your life.''
</P>
<P>
   As the sheriff in ''Nurse Betty'' says when he suspects she
killed her husband: ''Just because I'm thinking it doesn't mean I
like it.'' As LaBute well knows, people sometimes confuse an
observation with an endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   Don't, he cautions.
</P>
<P>
   He's heading off to do a romance now, which he hopes further
surprises -- and entices -- moviegoers to his work.
</P>
<P>
   ''It just allows them to come a little closer. But be careful,
is all I can say. I'm not through yet.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net
</P>
<P>
   http://www.ravecentral.com/nursebetty.html
</P>
<P>
   http://www.areasontolove.com/
</P>
</TEXT>
