<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tycoon Sought in Alleged Russia Plot  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- Prosecutors have launched a nationwide search for
a tycoon suspected of planning to assassinate a prominent governor
and former presidential candidate, security officials said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Mikhail Zhivilo, director of the MIKOM conglomerate, had fought
with Gov. Aman Tuleyev over control of lucrative aluminum plants in
the Kemerovo region in western Siberia. Tuleyev is governor of the
Kemerovo.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Security Service, or FSB, said last month it had
foiled an assassination plot against Tuleyev and summoned Zhivilo
for questioning, but he did not appear.
</P>
<P>
   The FSB branch in the Siberian city of Novosibirsk has issued an
arrest warrant for Zhivilo, a spokesman for the agency said
Wednesday without elaborating. Zhivilo's whereabouts were unclear,
though some Russian news reports said he has been out of the
country for weeks.
</P>
<P>
   MIKOM officials said the case against Zhivilo was groundless and
suggested it was linked to recent disputes in the aluminum
industry, state-controlled ORT television reported Wednesday. MIKOM
offices in Moscow could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Zhivilo is the second high-profile figure linked to the case.
Four-time Olympic biathlon champion Alexander Tikhonov was detained
last month on suspicion of helping arrange to poison Tuleyev and is
being held in Moscow's Lefortovo prison.
</P>
<P>
   Tuleyev, who came in fourth in March presidential elections,
said the plot to kill him appeared linked to control of the metals
industry, one of the most lucrative and allegedly crime-ridden
sectors of the economy.
</P>
<P>
   The governor once sent police into one of MIKOM's steel mills to
oust a top manager. Tuleyev's administration also declared three
plants owned by MIKOM bankrupt earlier this year and assigned
representatives from the rival Siberian Aluminum conglomerate to
take over.
</P>
</TEXT>
