<HEADLINE> Mild Quake Shakes Northwest Turkey  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL, Turkey (AP) -- A mild earthquake shook northwestern
Turkey on Wednesday -- an aftershock of a massive temblor that
devastated the same region a year ago, the Kandilli observatory
said.
</P>
<P>
   There was no reports of damage or injuries.
</P>
<P>
   The quake struck the town of Yalova at 5:23 p.m. It was felt in
Istanbul, some 30 miles to the north, across from the Sea of
Marmara. Seismologists at Kandilli said it was an aftershock of the
7.4-magnitude quake that struck on Aug. 17, 1999, killing some
17,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Turkey lies on the active Anatolian fault.
</P>
</TEXT>
