<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Separatists Targeted Judge  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MADRID, Spain (AP) -- Police believe Basque separatist gunmen
planned to shoot renowned Judge Baltasar Garzon from a window
overlooking his office last month, a newspaper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Citing confidential sources, El Pais said an informer told
police that the Basque separatist group ETA planned to send a
sniper to shoot Garzon from an apartment with a clear view of his
office in the National Court.
</P>
<P>
   Garzon, known for overseeing operations against ETA's
fund-raising as well as for his efforts to extradite former Chilean
dictator Gen. Augusto Pinochet to Spain, offered to continue work
as normal to bait the gunmen for arrest, the newspaper reported.
Instead, police boosted security in the area and replaced Garzon's
office windows with bulletproof glass.
</P>
<P>
   ETA has claimed responsibility for eight killings this summer in
its fight for independence of the northern Spanish Basque region.
Since ending a 14-month cease-fire in December, it has claimed 11
killings and been blamed for a 12th.
</P>
</TEXT>
