<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 13:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Missing British Woman Alarms Japan  </HEADLINE>
By GARY SCHAEFER
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Where's Lucie Blackman?
</P>
<P>
   In the three months since the 22-year-old British woman
vanished, tens of thousands of posters have gone up around Tokyo,
her family has made tearful pleas on national television, and even
British Prime Minister Tony Blair has expressed concern.
</P>
<P>
   Blackman's disappearance, the most talked about missing-person
case this country has had in years, is gripping Japan because it
touches on sensitive social issues, from an influx of foreign
workers to the rise in street crime and the dangers of cults --
which were initially suspected of harboring her.
</P>
<P>
   But above all, it has become a cause celebre because of
something women's rights campaigners have long sought to highlight
-- the dangers of Japan's ''water trade,'' an often shadowy industry
built around nightclubs and bars where women like Blackman pour
drinks and provide companionship for men willing to pay upward of
$100 an hour for the service.
</P>
<P>
   ''We hear a lot of stories of abuse, mostly from women from
Asian countries who are smuggled in,'' said Keiko Otsu, who runs a
women's shelter in Tokyo called HELP. ''What's behind it all is the
mentality in this country that it's normal for men to buy women.''
</P>
<P>
   The job of hostess in Japan is an updated, dumbed-down version
of the role played by the geisha since the 17th century. While
being a geisha involved years of training in music, dance and
etiquette, hostess work mostly requires good looks and -- preferably
-- a knack for risque conversation.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the women's services -- keeping the client's glass filled,
lighting his cigarettes and laughing at his jokes -- are valued in a
culture where entertaining at home is uncommon, and they provide
the backdrop for the sealing of countless business deals.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not easy work,'' said 20-year-old Lisa Lithero, a British
college student spending her summer vacation pouring bourbon at a
hostess club in Tokyo. ''If a customer doesn't speak English or
he's just boring, it can be really tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Blackman, a former flight attendant for British Airways, came to
Japan in May on a three-month tourist visa, speaking no Japanese.
</P>
<P>
   She rented a cheap apartment with a friend and began working
with her at a club in Roppongi, a popular Tokyo entertainment
district. According to her father, she planned to use her earnings
to travel on to Australia.
</P>
<P>
   But after telling her friend she was going to meet a man who had
promised to buy her a mobile phone, she vanished on July 1.
</P>
<P>
   Police acknowledge they have few clues.
</P>
<P>
   ''This sort of thing can happen in any country,'' said Inspector
Toshihiko Mii.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the case has shocked many in Japan and prompted a very
high-profile search.
</P>
<P>
   More than 30,000 leaflets bearing a photo of Blackman in a
cocktail dress have been distributed around Tokyo, and her family
is offering $150,000 for information leading to her discovery.
Blair asked about the status of the search when he was in Japan for
a summit in late July.
</P>
<P>
   ''We believe it is quite unlikely that one individual has held
Lucie for such a substantial amount of time,'' Lucie's younger
sister, Sophie, told reporters last month. ''We feel that perhaps
there is something more like a group of people or an
organization.''
</P>
<P>
   She won't say what sort of group she means. At first suspicion
fell on some sort of cult, but Blackman says the family has ruled
out that theory.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what her fate, Lucie's case is unlikely to put off
women searching for fast cash; Western hostesses can earn nearly
$5,000 a month.
</P>
<P>
   Westerners represent only a small fraction of the hostesses.
Most are from Asian countries, or from as far away as Colombia and
Romania, where women pay criminal syndicates for fake passports or
paper marriages, incurring debts that may take years to pay off.
</P>
<P>
   And in the less respectable clubs, where gangsters procure and
keep the women, the line between hostessing and prostitution is
often nonexistent.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the high-profile investigation into Blackman's
disappearance, their plight attracts little attention.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are Thai parents who are looking for their daughters in
Japan,'' said HELP's Otsu. ''But you never hear about them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
