<DOCNO> APW20000906.0055 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 14:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Latin America Courts Show Power  </HEADLINE>
By WILL WEISSERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   GUATEMALA CITY (AP) -- A little-known judge is to decide Thursday
whether ex-dictator Efrain Rios Montt and 19 other ruling-party
lawmakers should be booted out of Guatemala's Congress and stripped
of immunity in a scandal over a tax on alcoholic drinks.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever his decision, the moment highlights the increasing
power of courts in Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, military governments and internal conflicts
intimidated and controlled judiciaries across the region, leaving
courts impotent and many officials above the law.
</P>
<P>
   But suddenly, Latin America's courts appear to be coming into
their own.
</P>
<P>
   In Chile last month, the Supreme Court removed the legal
immunity of ex-dictator Gen. Augusto Pinochet, who once bragged
that ''not so much as a leaf moves in Chile without me moving it.''
The action opens the possibility of a trial on charges of violating
human rights.
</P>
<P>
   In Argentina, a federal judge has deepened his investigation
into a bribery scandal in the Senate that threatens the
government's efforts to put a sluggish economy back on track.
</P>
<P>
   In Mexico, the Supreme Court recently ordered outgoing President
Ernesto Zedillo to give Congress bank documents that could show
illegal contributions to his 1994 campaign, overruling the
executive's claim it would violate banking secrecy laws.
</P>
<P>
   In Guatemala, an army of lawyers is scrambling to save the
political career of Rios Montt, a former military leader who later
founded Guatemala's majority political party. Rios Montt, 73,
became president of the unicameral legislature and helped propel
his protege, President Alfonso Portillo, into office in January.
</P>
<P>
   In the other corner is Supreme Court Justice Augusto Eleazar
Lopez, a media-shy judge best known for his taste in snappy
designer suits. He was chosen to handle the case by the 12 other
Supreme Court justices, all of whom were appointed by Congress last
year, when it was controlled by the main opposition political
party. The Supreme Court is the highest in Guatemala after the
Court of Constitutionality.
</P>
<P>
   Such court cases could open the door to deeper judicial probes,
like the human rights battle now being waged in Chile. Mexico's new
president, Vicente Fox, has proposed a congressional ''Transparency
Commission'' to investigate past misdeeds and turn them over to the
courts.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is a globalization of justice that is spilling over into
local courts in many of these countries,'' said Rachel Neild, a
senior analyst for the Washington Office on Latin America. ''The
rule of law does seem like it could rise above the political
obstacles for the first time.''
</P>
<P>
   The courts' new aggressiveness applies mainly to high-profile
cases and hasn't yet spilled over into the day-to-day operations of
most Latin American judiciaries, which as a rule are still
inefficient, Byzantine systems dominated by strong executive
branches.
</P>
<P>
   And even in the headline-making cases, many feel the court
systems still have a long way to go.
</P>
<P>
   They believe it was Pinochet's arrest in London on a Spanish
court warrant that lit a fire under Chilean courts, which after
more than a decade of sluggishness ruled that he could be brought
to trial.
</P>
<P>
   While Argentina's courts struggle to unravel the bribery
scandal, the same Spanish court has charged 98 Argentine officers,
including 12 members of a former military junta, with genocide,
terrorism and torture.
</P>
<P>
   The Guatemalan scandal is about something much less weighty:
booze. Congress last month set the tax on alcoholic beverages at 20
percent. Somehow it was published into law as just 10 percent.
Opposition leaders accuse Rios Montt of secretly altering the
figure in exchange for favors from the alcohol lobby.
</P>
<P>
   The irony is not lost on many human rights activists that Rios
Montt, a man who has never apologized for championing a
scorched-earth campaign that left tens of thousands of Indian
peasants dead during his 1982-83 rule, might be toppled by
something as mundane as a tax on drinks.
</P>
<P>
   Frustrated with the past inaction of Guatemala's courts, Nobel
peace laureate Rigoberta Menchu went to Spain's National Court in
December to file genocide charges against Rios Montt and others.
</P>
<P>
   ''The legal process we are seeing now in Guatemala is
encouraging,'' Menchu said recently of the tax scandal. ''But our
cause looks to hold these men responsible for their truly terrible
crimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Seils, legal director of Guatemala City's Center for Human
Rights Legal Action, who is preparing a genocide case against Rios
Montt in Guatemala, said the Latin American court systems have to
start somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ''Should Rios Montt be stripped of his immunity, it opens up
doors that I don't think we expected to be opened anytime soon,''
Seils said. ''If that happens, he will have tripped up on an issue
that is not that big a deal, but the fact will remain that he will
be more vulnerable.''
</P>
<P>
   Neild said that if Pinochet could face charges in the country he
ruled with an iron fist for 17 years, anyone, anywhere in Latin
America, could one day be forced to face justice.
</P>
<P>
   ''Pinochet was such a symbolic figure, doing everything he did
in such a way as to never get caught,'' she said. ''Whatever
happens in Chile now will send a kind of shock wave through the
region that we have not seen before.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
