<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 15:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Falls 102; Dow Rises 50  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Tech stocks fell for a second straight session
Wednesday as analysts cut their ratings on several high-profile
companies. Blue chips moved higher, boosted by news of a major deal
in the financial services industry and surging oil prices.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts also said a government report on higher U.S.
productivity and a new low for the euro currency overseas helped
boost big-name stocks.
</P>
<P>
   In late afternoon trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones
industrial average was up 49.94 at 11,310.55.
</P>
<P>
   But the high-tech driven Nasdaq composite index was off 102.16
at 4,041.02. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was down 9.82 at
1,497.26.
</P>
<P>
   Citigroup, the nation's biggest financial services company, said
it will buy lending company Associates First Capital for about
$31.1 billion in stock. The deal should speed Citigroup's global
expansion in lending to consumers, giving it control of the U.S.'s
largest publicly traded finance company and Japan's fifth largest
consumer finance company.
</P>
<P>
   Citigroup, a Dow component, fell $3.19 to $54.75 in afternoon
trading, but shares of Associates First Capital jumped $10.75,
nearly 39 percent, to $38.75.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Labor Department said Americans' productivity, a
key measure of rising living standards, surged at a 5.7 percent
annual rate in the second quarter. The strong gain pushed unit
labor costs, a key gauge of inflation pressures, down by a rate of
0.4 percent, the lowest since the end of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The report bolstered investors' belief that interest rates will
remain stable for the near future.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, the euro fell to near 87 cents, smashing through last
Thursday's previous low of 88.37 cents. The currency also fell to a
new low against the yen.
</P>
<P>
   Although the downturn could hurt U.S. companies with European
investments, it could translate into a boost for U.S. financial
markets as investors who previously put their money into European
exchanges look for other places to invest.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Wednesday in London, prices of Brent crude for delivery
in October hit a new 10-year high, rising to $33.50 a barrel. Crude
for delivery in October surpassed the previous 10-year high of
$34.37 on the New York Mercantile Exchange, reaching $34.45 before
declining somewhat to $34.35. Higher oil prices are considered by
some to be a potential inflationary pressure, but at least one
analyst wasn't worried.
</P>
<P>
   ''If this truly was a long-term inflationary threat, that would
be showing up at the bond market in the form of higher interest
rates and we don't see that happening,'' said Alan Skrainka, chief
market strategist at Edward Jones of St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Tech stocks were depressed for a second day by analyst
downgrades of prominent companies.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Micron Technology fell $8.06 to $70.19 after
Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette lowered its rating on the memory
chipmaker from ''buy'' to ''underperform.'' Shares of
telecommunications chipmaker Applied Microcircuits were down $8.31
at $181.50.
</P>
<P>
   And telecom giant WorldCom fell $2.19 to $31.56 after analysts
from Lehman Brothers and Wachovia Securities downgraded the stock.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, high-tech stocks declined after a Piper Jaffray
analyst lowered the investment firm's rating on Intel.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 5-to-4 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange. Volume came to 787.78 million shares,
compared to 657.02 million the previous session.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index was down 2.60 at 536.42.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
