<BODY>
<HEADLINE> BC-NY--Buffalo Teachers, 3rd Ld-Writethru,0420  </HEADLINE>
By CAROLYN THOMPSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) - Buffalo's 47,000 public school students -
and their teachers - were back in the classroom Wednesday, after a
late-night round of contract talks proved successful enough to ward
off a threatened teachers strike.
</P>
<P>
   Union leaders, however, left the door open for future action as
negotiations continued on a multiyear contract for the district's
3,800 teachers. They have been working under an expired pact since
June 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ''This does not mean that there still is not a crisis. Anything
can fall apart tomorrow,'' BTF President Philip Rumore said after
talks Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Union officials scheduled a Wednesday evening meeting to discuss
the day's negotiations and determine whether teachers should
continue to report for work.
</P>
<P>
   With a $5.5 million strike fund in place, the teachers were
prepared to walk, even though state law prohibits them from
participating in strikes. In addition to losing pay, they could
face stiff fines.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't want to see the students out in the street but I think
we have to do what we have to do,'' McKinley High School teacher
Tom Mitchell said as he walked an informational picket line with
other teachers before heading into the classroom for the start of
school Wednesday. ''In the long run it's for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Teachers likely would stage ''rotating strikes,'' in which all
of the teachers at randomly targeted schools fail to report to work
on specific days.
</P>
<P>
   Union officials said the contract offered by the board includes
no pay raise in the first year and increases of 1 percent, 2
percent, 1.5 percent and 2 percent in subsequent years. Teachers
also are being asked to work an extra two days a year and the board
wants retirees to accept a cut in health benefits, according to the
union.
</P>
<P>
   The School Board has declined to comment on the reported terms.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo teachers earn an average of $55,000 a year, district
spokesman Andrew Maddigan said, and three-quarters also receive
annual pay increments ranging from 1.5 percent to 5 percent,
depending on their levels of education and service to the district.
</P>
<P>
   While declining to comment on stumbling blocks, city officials
say a tight budget is the general problem. Adding to that is the
fact that the district is about to start making payments of $2
million a year to cover the cost of a lawsuit by teachers settled
for $73 million in March. That lawsuit stemmed from an earlier
contract dispute.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-06-00 1551 </TRAILER>
