<DOCNO> APW20000906.0071 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 15:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Denies Torture Claim  </HEADLINE>
By NICK WADHAMS
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- Russian security officials acknowledged Wednesday
that they couldn't locate Chechnya's parliament speaker four months
after they arrested him, but denied claims by Chechen leaders that
he was tortured to death in prison.
</P>
<P>
   The case of Ruslan Alikhadzhiyev, a leader in the rebel
republic, worries human rights groups because Russian officials
have released little information other than to confirm his arrest.
Even that confirmation came after repeated denials.
</P>
<P>
   Concern was heightened when Chechen President Aslan Maskhadov,
citing unidentified sources, claimed in a statement that
Alikhadzhiyev died in Moscow's Lefortovo prison several days ago
after being tortured.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, a duty officer with Russia's Federal Security
Service said Alikhadzhiyev was detained in the Chechen town of
Shali in May but denied he was ever taken to Lefortovo. The duty
officer, speaking on condition of anonymity, said he could not
confirm that Alikhadzhiyev was still being held and maintained he
did not know where he was.
</P>
<P>
   The office of Russia's chief spokesman on Chechnya said
Wednesday it had no information on Alikhadzhiyev's whereabouts. The
Justice Ministry and the army command in Chechnya also said they
didn't know whether he was in custody.
</P>
<P>
   ''The only thing that is really clear is that this man was
detained,'' said Diederik Lohman, director of the Moscow office of
Human Rights Watch. ''That means that if the Russian authorities
cannot produce a credible story of his release, then they are
responsible to account for his whereabouts and his well-being.''
</P>
<P>
   Both sides in the Chechen war have made exaggerated claims, and
it was impossible to independently confirm the reports about
Alikhadzhiyev. Alikhadzhiyev's relatives in Shali told The
Associated Press in August that they had found no trace of him
despite weeks of searching.
</P>
<P>
   Rebels in Chechnya, located in the Caucasus region in Russia's
south, drove Russian troops out of the republic in a 1994-96 war.
Russian troops returned a year ago to suppress separatist
guerrillas, and now controls large areas of Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights groups have documented several cases when Chechens
disappeared after being detained by Russian troops. But the
disappearance of such a high-level official is unusual.
</P>
<P>
   Alikhadzhiyev is a member of a rebel legislature which was
elected before fighting began in Chechnya last September.
</P>
<P>
   He has advocated negotiations between the Kremlin and rebel
leaders. According to the Kommersant newspaper, he wrote a letter
to Russian President Vladimir Putin saying the Chechen parliament
was ready to help negotiate a solution to the latest conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Also in Chechnya, an Associated Press reporter was detained,
beaten and held in a covered pit overnight by Russian troops
sweeping the republic's capital for rebels.
</P>
<P>
   Reporter Ruslan Musayev, an ethnic Chechen, was buying food at
Grozny's central marketplace Tuesday when Russian troops stopped
him and demanded his documents.
</P>
<P>
   Musayev's passport does not show him as registered as a resident
of Grozny, so the servicemen took him to a military base at
Khankala. Musayev was not carrying documents identifying him as a
reporter.
</P>
<P>
   Musayev said he was then beaten, suffering multiple bruises and
damage to his lower ribs. He was led to a covered pit dug into the
ground, where he spent the night with four other detained Chechen
men.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday morning, an officer demanded to know what Musayev had
of value, Musayev said. Musayev turned over $600 he had hidden in
his clothing and his gold watch.
</P>
<P>
   He was then put on a military truck, taken to the border with
the neighboring Russian region of Ingushetia and released.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-06-00 1555 </TRAILER>
