<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000906.0072 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 16:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cool under pressure, GOP insider campaigns as regular guy  </HEADLINE>
By LAURENCE ARNOLD
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEANECK, N.J. (AP) - Bob Franks is behind schedule, his young
driver is struggling with directions and black clouds threaten to
wash out two Labor Day events before the Republican candidate for
Senate can reach them.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the confusion, Franks is a pillar of calm. Shoes off,
reclining in a center seat of his leased campaign van, he is
exchanging laughs on his cell phone with his 2-year-old daughter,
Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   ''Cool! Love you too, Sweetie,'' Franks says, signing off.
</P>
<P>
   Confident, relaxed and polished, Franks evinces no anxiety at
facing the most daunting challenge of his political career:
defeating Jon Corzine, the immensely wealthy Democrat who will
likely swamp Franks with self-financed television advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Franks, 48, is a true organization man, having served two stints
as chairman of New Jersey's Republican Party. Traveling the state
as an unlikely underdog, he exudes confidence that, come Election
Day, the machinery of politics will grind out a victory for him.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine is a first-time candidate but is running like an
incumbent, largely ignoring Franks and avoiding face-to-face
encounters.
</P>
<P>
   So Franks, a member of the House since 1993 and consummate
political insider, is the one portraying himself as the regular
guy.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm very much like most of the people who call New Jersey
home,'' says Franks - even though most people do not join the state
Legislature at age 28 and go on to win 10 elections in a row.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Corzine, who keeps his family largely off-limits, Franks
posed with his wife and daughter for the front of a handbill
distributed at public events.
</P>
<P>
   His campaign van has a baby seat, stuffed toys and diapers in
the back for days when politicking is a family affair. The van is
equipped with television and VCR, and Franks often watches videos
of country music. Garth Brooks is a favorite.
</P>
<P>
   His campaign manager, Charlie Smith, says these phrases best
describe the candidate: Experienced. Hardworking. In touch.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign pace is busy, but not frantic. During a break after
South Plainfield's Labor Day parade, Franks nurses an iced tea and
a small glass of a New Jersey-brewed beer at an Irish pub while
quietly singing along with Bruce Springsteen's ''My Hometown.''
</P>
<P>
   On the street, Franks practices what might be called
cardio-campaigning. Along the parade route he jogs to one side of
the street, leaps the curb and shakes hands, then jogs to the other
side to do the same.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think politics has too often become a very impersonal
activity in America,'' Franks says.
</P>
<P>
   The banter with voters is one-sided and lacking in punctuation:
''Hi folks I'm Bob Franks I'm running for U.S. Senate have a
terrific day!''
</P>
<P>
   Halfway through the parade, Franks laughs when he sees his
friend Linda Dashuta, the Republican chairwoman of South
Plainfield, waving a bumper sticker popular among the anti-Corzine
crowd: ''Make him spend it all, Bob.''
</P>
<P>
   Franks says the bumper stickers are made by supporters, not by
the campaign. Still, ''I think they're funny,'' he says. ''They
have a wonderful undercurrent of truth to them.''
</P>
<P>
   When Daniel Sherwood of South Plainfield approaches Franks with
a direct question - ''Anti-gun or pro-gun?'' - Franks pauses, then
replies, ''I'm for the Second Amendment.''
</P>
<P>
   ''OK, you've got my vote,'' says Sherwood, a gun owner and
member of the National Rifle Association.
</P>
<P>
   But elaborating minutes later on the gun issue, Franks boasts of
his vote in favor of the Brady Act and his support for closing the
so-called ''gun show loophole.'' The encounter is a reminder of one
common criticism of Franks through his years in Congress, that he
is pragmatic to the point of lacking a strong ideological compass.
</P>
<P>
   But the Senate race seems likely to turn less on Franks' record
in Congress than the precedent-setting spending of his Democratic
opponent.
</P>
<P>
   On this day, Corzine has hit the air with his first two
advertisements of the fall campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The Franks campaign has assembled a script of one of the
commercials and is appalled: It calls Corzine ''the one (candidate)
who supports putting Social Security in a 'lock box,''' even though
Franks voted for such an idea.
</P>
<P>
   Franks flips the channels on the van's television, searching for
a news program that might carry the ads.
</P>
<P>
   The search is fruitless. But the unflappable candidate feigns
delight at finding a tuxedoed Jerry Lewis leading his annual
Muscular Dystrophy Association telethon.
</P>
<P>
   ''Here it is! Jerry!'' Franks exclaims. ''We can watch this for
hours!''
</P>
<P>
   Tomorrow: The Corzine Style
</P>
