<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lost dog journeys by train  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   FAIRFIELD, Conn. (AP) - The disappearance of Alex the Scottish
terrier set off a search by his owner, neighbors and even police.
</P>
<P>
   Little did they know Alex took the 9:14 p.m. train to New Haven.
</P>
<P>
   His owner, June Linsley, said she discovered the 1-year-old dog
missing from her fenced-in yard about 8:30 p.m. Monday. She alerted
neighbors and called Fairfield police.
</P>
<P>
   Officer Tim Stalling, who patrols Linsley's Southport
neighborhood, helped her search for the dog for about 45 minutes.
Neighbors also helped look, but no one could find Alex.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was heartbroken. It was a puppy I had for a month, and I
adored him,'' Linsley said.
</P>
<P>
   About 40 minutes later, Stalling rang her doorbell.
</P>
<P>
   ''He said, 'I think you better sit down. Your dog is in New
Haven,''' Linsley said.
</P>
<P>
   A Metro-North Railroad employee had discovered the dog and,
after reading the tags, called Fairfield police.
</P>
<P>
   The Southport railroad station is close to Linsley's house. Alex
had burrowed through a hole in the fence around Linsley's yard to
get out then apparently caught the next train out of town.
</P>
<P>
   What happened to Alex on the train ride and who, if anyone,
minded him while he traveled for 40 minutes remains a mystery,
Linsley said.
</P>
<P>
   A Metro-North police officer drove Alex back home from New
Haven.
</P>
<P>
   ''The dog was pooped,'' said Linsley. ''It had been very
busy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
