<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 16:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> BC-NY--Toxic Falls, Bjt,0398  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ITHACA, N.Y. (AP) - The federal government is poised to carry
out an emergency cleanup of a recreational gorge contaminated with
high concentrations of lead left behind by a century-old gun
factory.
</P>
<P>
   State environmental authorities documented hazardous levels of
lead at Fall Creek gorge in 1995, but their findings only came to
light after Cornell University sold the city a 10-acre plot next to
the abandoned Ithaca Gun factory for $1 last winter.
</P>
<P>
   With its creek and 150-foot waterfall, the already highly
popular hangout for hikers, swimmers and fishing enthusiasts was to
be turned into a city park.
</P>
<P>
   ''You probably can't find a kid in Ithaca that hasn't swum in
this waterway,'' Walter Hang, an environmental activist who maps
toxic sites around New York state, said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Ithaca Gun, which closed down in the 1980s, was situated on an
upper edge of the gorge and ''literally dumped the lead on the
ground adjacent to the factory on land that happens to be owned by
Cornell,'' Hang said.
</P>
<P>
   In its most recent testing in 1998, the state Department of
Environmental Conservation found lead levels as high as 215,000
parts per million - more than 500 times above acceptable state
levels. Lead, a highly toxic element, can cause damage to the brain
and nervous system if its dust is ingested or inhaled.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency took
soil samples last month and revealed this week that the site
qualifies for emergency cleanup of hazardous waste. The agency
plans to carry out tests in late September to determine the extent
of contamination in the gorge, which runs into Cayuga Lake.
</P>
<P>
   When those results are compiled, possibly by mid-October, the
agency will decide how much money is needed to remove the
contaminated soil and whether to place the site on the federal
Superfund program's national priority list.
</P>
<P>
   Getting placed on that list ''would in effect make it one of the
worst toxic dumps in the country,'' said Hang, who runs a business
called Toxics Targeting.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's very rare that they add sites this late in the game,'' he
said. ''The program began in 1980, so in theory the worst dumps
have all been identified and are moving ahead toward cleanup. But
when it comes to lead, there has been an exemption for hazardous
waste management requirements when bullets are involved.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-06-00 1629 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000906.0085 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 16:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Rejects China Proposal  </HEADLINE>
By PAULINE JELINEK
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The United States will not accept a Chinese
proposal to label Taiwan a ''customs territory of China'' for its
entry into the World Trade Organization, President Clinton said in
a letter made public Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Foreign Relations Committee Chairman Jesse Helms, R-N.C.,
meanwhile, urged his colleagues to ''stand up for Taiwan'' in the
debate over China trade.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Sen. John Kyl of Arizona blasted a Beijing proposal
that the document setting out terms for membership in the WTO make
it clear that Taiwan, Hong Kong and Macau all are part of China, in
effect using the WTO to assert its disputed claim to Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   ''We should hold out the prospect of legislative action,'' said
Kyl. He did not specify what that legislation would do.
</P>
<P>
   Under an agreement signed in 1992, once China joins the WTO,
Taiwan would immediately follow. Hong Kong is already a member as
it is treated as a separate customs territory.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, in an Aug. 31 letter to Kyl, said his administration
has rejected China's proposal to call Taiwan ''a separate customs
territory of China.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We have advised the Chinese that such language is
inappropriate ... and that we will not accept it,'' Clinton's
letter said.
</P>
<P>
   As the bill to normalize trade with China went into its second
day of debate in the full Senate, Helms' committee held a separate
hearing on issues related to Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   ''In a just world,'' said Helms, Taiwan would long ago have been
admitted to the 137-member trade organization because it is more
advanced economically than China and has for years met the
requirements for membership.
</P>
<P>
   Helms and Kyl called for some kind of pressure to prevent China
from blocking Taiwan's WTO membership.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think ... Congress ought to go ahead and do something,''
said Helms.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think we ought to stand up for Taiwan now.''
</P>
<P>
   Fellow Republican Sen. Craig Thomas of Wyoming argued against an
amendment to the China trade bill, saying it would delay passage.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think we need to find a way to get that message'' to China
without holding up permanent normal trade status, said Craig.
</P>
<P>
   China trade was the first order of business Tuesday as the
Senate returned from its summer recess with leaders of both parties
determined to approve the permanent normal trade relations (PNTR)
before lawmakers close shop to campaign before the November
elections.
</P>
<P>
   While supporters believe they have a solid majority in the
Senate, they face two main problems -- time limitations as Congress
rushes to finish its work for the year and the determination of
some senators to link normalized trade to China's weapons
proliferation and human rights record.
</P>
<P>
   The House approved the China trade bill last May on a 237-197
vote, and the concern is that any Senate amendments to that bill
would effectively kill it for the year because there wouldn't be
time for the two chambers to work out differences between the
measures.
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate debate Wednesday, Democratic Sen. Max Baucus of
Montana urged support of the bill, saying rejection of PNTR will
likely lead to an indefinite delay in Taiwan's entry into the WTO.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The bill is H.R. 4444.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Congressional legislation: http://thomas.loc.gov
</P>
<P>
   Business coalition for U.S.-China trade:
http://www.business4chinatrade.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-06-00 1638 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000906.0086 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 16:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Assemblyman, state agency spar over timing of Con Ed refunds  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - A state assemblyman is again at odds with a
Pataki administration agency, this time over the timing of refunds
the state has ordered for Consolidated Edison Co. ratepayers.
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman Richard Brodsky, a Democrat from Westchester County,
accused the state Consumer Protection Board Wednesday of taking the
''unprecedented'' action of siding with Con Ed in the refund case
and not with consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Consumer Protection Board exists to protect the consumers
of this state, not the corporations who have acted negligently,''
Brodsky complained.
</P>
<P>
   He filed a comment with the state Public Service Commission
asking that the utility-regulating agency ignore a Consumer
Protection Board request to delay by a month the distribution of
refunds by Consolidated Edison.
</P>
<P>
   Under a state law approved by the Legislature and Gov. George
Pataki earlier this year, about 3 million Con Ed customers are
supposed to get $162 million in refunds beginning Monday.
</P>
<P>
   For residential ratepayers, the refunds would amount to about
$14 in New York City and $21 in Westchester County, Con Ed's
service territory.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, however, a federal judge in Albany has
scheduled oral arguments for Sept. 19 to hear Con Ed's challenge to
the law ordering it to refund the money. He has also set this
Friday as a deadline for the filing of papers into a preliminary
injunction requested by the utility asking that the refunds be
delayed until its claim against the state is decided.
</P>
<P>
   The utility will argue that the refund statute violates the U.S.
Constitution under a number of provisions, including equal
protection and due process clauses.
</P>
<P>
   Con Ed is contending that to give back the money and then to be
allowed to collect it again will cause ''confusion and resistance''
among its customers.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, the Consumer Protection Board agreed with the utility.
While saying it believes the constitutionality of the law will be
upheld, the Consumer board said it will do no harm to delay the
refund until on or about Oct. 10. By that time, the board is
arguing before the PSC, it'll be known if a federal judge will
issue a temporary injunction against enforcement of the refund law
- a crucial indicator of whether the statute will eventually be
struck down or upheld.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the Consumer Protection Board is asking that
interest be accumulated on the refunds held by Con Ed during
September, with that extra money added to the checks if and when
they are sent to ratepayers.
</P>
<P>
   ''If anything, we'll be avoiding confusion and the consumers
will be held harmless by waiting to see what the court says about
this with the interest accruing at our request,'' said Consumer
Protection Board spokesman Jon Sorensen. ''There will be no
financial loss. The only thing that be lost will be confusion on
the part of Con Ed customers.''
</P>
<P>
   He called Brodsky's criticism ''another example of where the
assemblyman is grasping for the headline first.''
</P>
<P>
   Brodsky and the Republican Pataki administration have clashed
repeatedly, especially over Pataki's environmental policies.
Brodsky chairs the Assembly's environmental conservation committee.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
