<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 16:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UConn, ANC join forces to catalog apartheid's paper trail  </HEADLINE>
By WILLIAM J. KOLE
<TEXT>
<P>
   STORRS, Conn. (AP) - They are the ghosts of South Africa's
bloody struggle against apartheid.
</P>
<P>
   More than 5,000 boxes of documents and diaries, including some
of Nelson Mandela's anguished personal letters, will be catalogued
at the University of Connecticut under a partnership with the
African National Congress launched Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   South African officials said the archive will ensure the world
never forgets how their country's decades of white rule and brutal
policy of racial separation were overcome - or underestimate the
chances that it could happen again somewhere else.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is a disease which, if we are not able to cure it, will
repeat itself in the 21st century,'' warned Frene Ginwala, the
speaker of South Africa's parliament and a prominent ANC leader.
</P>
<P>
   The effort is being paid for with $1.1 million in grants from
the Andrew W. Mellon Foundation, the United Negro College Fund and
the U.S. Agency for International Development. It will focus on
documents that for years were kept secret by ordinary South
Africans as well as ANC leaders in exile around the world.
</P>
<P>
   The records range from schoolchildren's drawings to the
correspondence of leaders such as Mandela, South Africa's former
president; Chris Hani, the late leader of the ANC's military wing;
and longtime ANC leader Walter Sisulu.
</P>
<P>
   Amii Omara-Otunnu, a UConn history professor leading the archive
effort, said much of the ANC's history still hasn't been told. The
movement was forced underground for decades by South Africa's
repressive government.
</P>
<P>
   The project, he said, will prevent invaluable historical
documents from ending up as ''dead things rusting and collecting
dust.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the archive will take several years to set up, scholars
worldwide are expected to examine the records, making UConn's Dodd
Research Center one of North America's leading centers devoted to
the history of the 50-year struggle. Apartheid ended in 1994 when
South Africa held its first all-race elections.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to examining and cataloguing documents, experts will
train South African researchers who will fan out and record oral
histories from the tens of thousands of people ''whose survival at
times depended on not putting things in writing,'' said UConn
President Phillip E. Austin.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Sam Gejdenson, D-Conn., a member of the House
Committee on International Relations, said the project would help
guard against future revisionists who might deny that apartheid
ever existed, much as some today question the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   ''It doesn't take long for a new generation to come around and
find it almost unbelievable,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
