<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Ends Down 118; Dow Gains 50  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Tech stocks fell for a second straight session
today as analysts cut their ratings on several high-profile
companies, while Blue chips moved higher on news of a major deal in
the financial services industry.
</P>
<P>
   The high-tech driven Nasdaq composite index was off 117.80 at
4,025.38, according to preliminary calculations.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average closed up 50.03 at 11,310.64,
and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was down 13.40 at 1,493.68.
</P>
<P>
   Citigroup, the nation's biggest financial services company, said
it will buy lender Associates First Capital for about $31.1 billion
in stock. The deal should speed Citigroup's global expansion in
lending to consumers, giving it control of the U.S.'s largest
publicly traded finance company and Japan's fifth largest consumer
finance company.
</P>
<P>
   Citigroup, a Dow component, fell $2.13 to $55.81, but shares of
Associates First Capital jumped $10.63, nearly 38 percent, to
$38.63.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said a government report showing higher U.S.
productivity also bolstered investors' belief that interest rates
will remain stable for the near future.
</P>
<P>
   The Labor Department said Americans' productivity, a key measure
of rising living standards, surged at a 5.7 percent annual rate in
the second quarter. The strong gain pushed unit labor costs, a key
gauge of inflation pressures, down by a rate of 0.4 percent, the
lowest since the end of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Tech stocks, however, remained depressed for a second day,
primarily because of more analyst downgrades of prominent
companies. On Tuesday, high-tech stocks declined after a prominent
analyst lowered his rating on Intel.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Micron Technology fell $9.50 to $68.75 on Wednesday
after Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette lowered its rating on the memory
chipmaker from ''buy'' to ''underperform.'' Shares of
telecommunications chipmaker Applied Microcircuits were down $10.77
at $179.05.
</P>
<P>
   And telecom provider WorldCom fell $2.25 to $31.50 after
analysts from Lehman Brothers and Wachovia Securities downgraded
the stock.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think those downgrades are concerning people about
third-quarter earnings, so you're seeing weakness in those
stocks,'' said Barry Berman, managing director of equity trading
for Robert W. Baird &AMP; Co. in Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of MP3.com fell 69 cents -- more than 8 percent -- to $7.88
after a federal judge ruled Wednesday that the company had
willfully violated copyrights of music companies and awarded
Universal Music Group $25,000 per CD, a penalty that could reach as
much as $250 million.
</P>
<P>
   Also Wednesday, crude for delivery in October surpassed the
previous 10-year high of $34.37 on the New York Mercantile
Exchange, reaching $34.45 before declining somewhat to $34.35.
</P>
<P>
   Higher oil prices are considered by some to be a potential
inflationary pressure, but at least one analyst wasn't worried.
</P>
<P>
   ''If this truly was a long-term inflationary threat, that would
be showing up at the bond market in the form of higher interest
rates and we don't see that happening,'' said Alan Skrainka, chief
market strategist at Edward Jones of St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, the euro fell to near 87 cents, smashing through last
Thursday's previous low of 88.37 cents. The currency also fell to a
new low against the yen.
</P>
<P>
   While the downturn could hurt U.S. companies with European
investments, it also might translate into a boost for U.S.
financial markets as investors who previously put their money into
European exchanges look for other places to invest.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 4-to-3 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange. Volume came to 992.30 million shares,
compared to 836.45 million the previous session.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index was down 2.91 at 536.11.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 0.32 percent.
Germany's DAX index was down 0.84 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100 was
down 0.86 percent, and France's CAC-40 was down 0.87 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
