<BODY>
<HEADLINE> House Subpoenas SmithKline Papers  </HEADLINE>
By CLAUDE R. MARX
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House Commerce Committee, investigating
alleged Medicare overcharging by seven drug companies, on Wednesday
subpoenaed five documents describing SmithKline Beecham's pricing
procedures for its drug Kytril.
</P>
<P>
   SmithKline has until noon on Monday to turn over the documents.
If it fails to comply with the subpoena it could be subject to a
contempt charge that could result in a prison sentence of up to one
year and/or a $100,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   ''Discussions continued today and the committee has been very
accommodating. After continued discussions it became clear that the
company would force Chairman (Tom) Bliley to issue a subpoena,''
said committee spokesman Peter Sheffield. ''The committee feels
strongly that the five documents requested are imperative to the
completion of the investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   SmithKline spokesman Jeremy Hymsfeld said they had received the
subpoena and ''we intend to keep cooperating with the committee and
we hope to resolve to come to a satisfactory resolution of the
issues.''
</P>
<P>
   The investigation follows a Health and Human Services Department
report that the Health Care Financing Administration pays more for
22 drugs, including Kytril, because drug companies charge higher
prices to physicians being reimbursed by Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Kytril, an anti-nausea drug used mostly by chemotherapy
patients, is the only SmithKline product being investigated.
</P>
<P>
   SmithKline, whose American headquarters is in Philadelphia, had
previously turned over most of the documents that the committee
requested in May. But it held out on the five, maintaining they are
protected by attorney-client privilege.
</P>
<P>
   Bliley, R-Va., has frequently maintained that the privilege does
mot apply in this case.
</P>
<P>
   SmithKline announced last Thursday that it would sell Kytril to
Roche AG, of Switzerland, for $1.23 billion in cash. The
divestiture is part of SmithKline's effort to win regulatory
approval for its pending $75 billion merger with another British
drug maker, Glaxo Wellcome. The deal, which has been approved by
both companies' shareholders, is scheduled to close on Sept. 25.
</P>
<P>
   Glaxo Wellcome markets Zofran for chemotherapy.
------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   House Commerce Committee: www.house.gov/commerce
</P>
<P>
   SmithKline Beecham:www.SB.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
