<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 17:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> RFK Jr. endorses Clinton; other environmentalists on fence  </HEADLINE>
By BETH J. HARPAZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - Robert F. Kennedy Jr., an environmentalist whose
father faced carpetbagger accusations when he ran for Senate in New
York in 1964, gave Hillary Rodham Clinton his personal endorsement
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was here in 1964 campaigning across the state with my father
and I heard the same thing all across the state then - that he's a
carpetbagger and how could he be a good senator for New York
State,'' said Kennedy, who was 10 when his father, who was from
Massachusetts, campaigned for Senate in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ''Is somebody who was not born in this state capable of coming
in and offering leadership? My answer to that is resoundingly,
yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, director of the Environmental Law Project at Pace
University and the Hudson Riverkeeper program, also gave Clinton
his blessing for her positions on environmental issues.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Clinton won the endorsement of the Sierra Club.
</P>
<P>
   But two other important environmental groups, Friends of the
Earth and the New York League of Conservation Voters, remain
undecided between her and her Republican opponent, Rep. Rick Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   ''We made it very clear to both of them that this is a tough
call,'' said NYLCV Chairman Paul Elston. He said the LCV invited
both candidates to debate environmental issues in the next month
but has not gotten commitments from either one.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have fought some real important battles side by side with
Rick Lazio in the past and found him to be committed to the
environment,'' said Mark Helm, spokesman for Friends of the Earth.
''The first lady has no track record to speak of in this area, and
it's important to have environmental champions on both sides of the
aisle. Therefore it would be real difficult to make a call at this
date.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy sits on NYLCV's board, as does Larry Rockefeller, an
environmental lawyer and a nephew of late governor Nelson
Rockefeller. Rockefeller, a Republican, often crosses party lines
to endorse Democrats, but said Wednesday that he was waiting until
the board meets closer to the election to make up his own mind on
the Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy said he had been tutoring Clinton on local environmental
issues and added that she had been ''supportive'' in getting help
from the White House on maintaining protections for New York City's
upstate watershed in conflict with two federal agencies, the Army
Corps of Engineers and the Environmental Protection Agency.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy acknowledged that he had also sought help from Lazio on
the watershed issue, and that Lazio ''wrote a very good letter'' to
the Army Corps of Engineers.
</P>
<P>
   But he criticized Lazio's overall environmental record, saying
he felt the congressman had not ''demonstrated environmental
leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio spent the day fund-raising in Texas, Alabama and
Louisiana. An invitation letter to his Dallas fund-raiser was
signed by Charles Wyly, who, with his brother Sam, financed a
controversial ad about Sen. John McCain's environmental record. The
ads, which were criticized as being inaccurate, were paid for with
so-called ''soft money'' from an organization the Wyly brothers
formed called ''Republicans for Clean Air.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lazio campaign said Wyly was not attending the fund-raiser,
but merely signed the letter for it to help bring in guests.
</P>
<P>
   ''I find it interesting that Lazio's going to Texas to raise
money from Mr. Wyly, who ran such a really unfair ad against John
McCain using soft money in the Republican primary that totally
distorted Sen. McCain's record,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spokeswoman Karen Dunn called it ''hypocrisy'' for Lazio
to appear in ads with McCain to promote campaign finance reform
while allowing Wyly to help him raise money.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio campaign spokesman Dan McLagan returned the charge of
hypocrisy, saying: ''For her to make soft money an issue while
she's raising and spending millions and while Rick has yet to spend
a dime of it is beyond chutzpah.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-06-00 1717 </TRAILER>
