<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 17:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Five teens arrested for killing deliveryman  </HEADLINE>
By DONNA DE LA CRUZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - Five hungry teen-agers apparently wanting some
Chinese food, but not wanting to pay for it, placed a $60 delivery
order to a vacant Queens house Friday night, and when the
deliveryman arrived, they allegedly beat him to death.
</P>
<P>
   ''They were just looking for a free meal,'' a law enforcement
source, speaking on condition of anonymity said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Sheng Jin Liu, 44, arrived at the vacant house last Friday night
carrying two bags of food, police said.
</P>
<P>
   The four males and one female - ranging in age from 14 to 17 -
took only one bag of food, leaving the other behind to be nibbled
on by cats. They also left behind the several hundred dollars in
cash Liu was carrying, said Deputy Chief Patrick Timlin, commanding
officer of the Queens Detective Borough.
</P>
<P>
   The teen-agers, all friends from Queens, were identified as:
Robert Savage, 14; James Stone, 16; Stacy Royster, 17; Jamel
Murphy, 17; and Darryl Tyson, 17. All were charged with
second-degree murder; first-degree manslaughter, robbery and
criminal possession of a weapon offenses.
</P>
<P>
   According to a criminal complaint, the defendants admitted
''they were going to forcibly take the food from the victim,'' said
Detective Douglas Diesu of the 113th Detective Squad in Queens.
</P>
<P>
   Royster called the Golden Wok restaurant in St. Albans, Queens,
Friday and placed several orders of food before 11:30 p.m., Timlin
said.
</P>
<P>
   Royster, who was to start at Queensborough Community College
Wednesday, met Liu as he drove up to the house. The four others
joined her, Timlin said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The four male defendants held the victim, put a sheet over his
head, beat him with their fists, and then defendant Savage struck
the victim in the head with a brick,'' Diesu said in the complaint.
</P>
<P>
   The teens admitted they took one bag, fled the scene, and ate
the food, Timlin said. They had ordered General Tso's chicken,
chicken and broccoli, shrimp lo mein and shrimp egg foo yung.
</P>
<P>
   Liu's wife called police when he did not return to the
restaurant within 15 minutes - Liu was killed about a mile from the
restaurant. A trace of the delivery order brought police to the
crime scene, where they found Liu dead. The medical examiner's
office said the cause of death was multiple blunt impact injuries
to the face, scalp and torso.
</P>
<P>
   Police were led to the teens by tracing the telephone call
Royster used to place the order to her cellular telephone, Timlin
said. All the teens, who have no prior criminal records, were
arrested at their homes Tuesday and brought to the 113th Precinct
for questioning.
</P>
<P>
   Queens District Attorney Richard A. Brown said Liu's death was a
terrible, tragic case.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was killed without provocation and without reason,'' Brown
said. ''It was a shocking crime which leaves us all shaking our
heads as to why these kids would do what they are accused of
doing.''
</P>
<P>
   According to friends and neighbors, Liu came to the United
States about 10 years ago from Fuzhou, in southern-China. He worked
for several years at other restaurants before opening three Chinese
takeout restaurants of his own in Queens.
</P>
<P>
   Liu's wife and two teen-age children came to New York two years
ago, and all work in the restaurants. Liu made the deliveries
himself, said Lin Yun, the manager of King's Wok, a few blocks from
the Golden Wok.
</P>
<P>
   One of Liu's regular customers said Liu had delivered her food a
few hours before he died.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was a nice man, very hardworking,'' said Thelma Grandison.
''I don't know why they had to kill him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-06-00 1726 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000906.0110 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 17:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Government Ends Trucker Talks  </HEADLINE>
By JOCELYN GECKER
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS (AP) -- French truckers stepped up a blockade of the
nation's fuel depots Wednesday as the government said it would make
no more concessions and demanded an end to protests that have
forced some gas stations to run dry.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Lionel Jospin took a tough line with the
truckers, saying their strike had ''inflicted a major handicap on
the French economy,'' and the government had reached its limit.
</P>
<P>
   ''The government will not go any farther. There will be no more
negotiations,'' Jospin told reporters after meeting with Transport
Minister Jean-Claude Gayssot, who spent the past two nights
negotiating with union leaders.
</P>
<P>
   French truckers have sealed off roads to nearly 100 of the
country's oil refineries and fuel depots since Sunday to protest
soaring fuel prices.
</P>
<P>
   France has the second highest fuel prices in the European Union
after Britain. Unleaded gasoline costing $3.70 per gallon, of which
about 75 percent is tax. Diesel fuel in France costs $2.84 per
gallon, compared to a current average of $1.58 per gallon in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Since the blockade began Sunday, hundreds of gas stations have
run dry and local governments have begun rationing fuel as
motorists line up bumper-to-bumper at the pump.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities in many regions have had to reserve gas for
emergency and police use. Some drivers crossed into neighboring
countries to fill their tanks.
</P>
<P>
   The dwindling fuel supply caused flights out of the Lyon airport
to be canceled or rerouted on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Jospin's ultimatum to truckers came after his Green party allies
warned of a crisis within their coalition, saying his concessions
to truckers broke promises to promote environmental policies. The
Greens say France should favor rail traffic over the more polluting
trucks to carry freight.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a crisis, essentially, for the government, which has two
seemingly contradictory policies,'' said Green Party spokesman Yves
Cochet. He said the party planned to discuss whether its two
ecology ministers would step down from the Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   The government has offered to give truckers a 20-cent
reimbursement per gallon of fuel this year, and a 14-cent refund
per liter on gasoline taxes next year. But the main union wants an
additional tax break of 5.6 centers per gallon in 2001, said a
statement by the National Federation of Truck Drivers, the
country's largest trucker union.
</P>
<P>
   Two of France's three principal freight unions refused to accept
the government's offer Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The truckers' federation rejected the government's offer as
''insufficient'' and vowed to continue its nationwide blockades.
</P>
<P>
   A smaller union, Transport and Logistics of France, signed a
deal with the government Wednesday, while the head of the nation's
second-largest union, UNOSTRA, left negotiations saying union
members had to continue consultations before accepting the
government's terms.
</P>
<P>
   The movement was expected to snowball Thursday, with ambulance
drivers, taxi drivers and farmers voicing demands for lower taxes.
Taxi drivers planned a protest in Paris, which would likely cause
traffic jams and a shortage of cabs around the capital.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday morning, taxis staged what they called ''Operation
Escargot,'' in which taxis driving in from Paris' airports slowed
their speed to a snail's pace.
</P>
<P>
   The truckers' protest was inspired by last week's strike by
fishermen, who blocked ports for several days. The demonstrations
ended when the Agriculture Ministry agreed to compensate them for
rising fuel prices.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
