<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 17:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Critics Howl on UK Millennium Dome  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Things could perhaps be worse for Britain's
Millennium Dome. But it's hard to see how.
</P>
<P>
   Outraged critics had a field day Wednesday after the
announcement of a $70 million public bailout for the giant
space-age structure on the Thames -- the latest in a series of woes
to plague the project.
</P>
<P>
   ''The time has come to pull the plug on Domefoolery,''
Conservative Party leader William Hague thundered a day after the
emergency infusion of cash was announced.
</P>
<P>
   Criticizing Prime Minister Tony Blair's government for
''throwing tens of thousands of pounds more into a black hole,''
Hague called for the dome's immediate shutdown and the firing of
the government minister responsible for it.
</P>
<P>
   London Mayor Ken Livingstone also jumped into the fray, telling
British Broadcasting Corp. radio he would never have built the $1.2
billion exhibition complex, which has drawn fewer visitors than
expected, garnered lukewarm reviews and gone through repeated
management shakeups.
</P>
<P>
   Press coverage was scathing. The Independent newspaper ran a
front-page photo of the riverside complex in southeast London,
dominated by ominous-looking gray clouds. ''Close it today,''
blared the tabloid Express.
</P>
<P>
   Conceived as a millennium attraction that would wow the world,
the dome debuted to enormous fanfare at New Year's, with Blair and
Queen Elizabeth II in attendance. But it was all downhill from
there.
</P>
<P>
   The project had already swallowed up more than $800 million in
government funding since its opening, and the latest bailout came
despite a pledge by the dome's management to seek no more public
cash.
</P>
<P>
   Dome operators, meanwhile, scrambled to deny that a company
backed by the Japanese investment bank Nomura International might
pull out of negotiations to take over the complex next year.
</P>
<P>
   Nomura said it hadn't been told ahead of time of Tuesday's
bailout, but a Nomura spokesman, Andrew Dowler, said plans to
acquire the site were moving ahead.
</P>
<P>
   David James, the dome's new executive chairman, expressed
confidence the deal would go through, and predicted that Nomura and
its partners would ''make a killing on this place.''
</P>
<P>
   But like almost everyone else embroiled in dome dealings these
days, James distanced himself from the complex's original planning
and previous finances. ''Nobody asked for my opinion at the
beginning,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lord Falconer, the government minister responsible for the dome,
said closing it now would cost even more money, and cause the loss
of tens of thousands of jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ''I want to stick with the project, and seek to deliver the
benefits that the project brings,'' he told BBC radio.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
