<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 17:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 38 people, 11 companies indicted in construction industry racketeering </HEADLINE>
By SAMUEL MAULL
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - A Manhattan grand jury indicted 38 people and 11
companies Wednesday on charges of siphoning millions of dollars
from city construction projects through bribery, bid-rigging and
other crimes.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment said the defendants, called ''The Lucchese
Construction Group'' by investigators, illegally used nonunion
labor on eight public and private projects and paid workers less
than the legal wage.
</P>
<P>
   But the 57-count indictment, alleges crooked contractors in the
group billed public agencies and private developers as if they were
paying wages in compliance with the law.
</P>
<P>
   The difference between what the contractors billed the project
sponsors and their actual labor costs financed the bribes given to
corrupt union officials who let them use nonunion labor, District
Attorney Robert Morgenthau said.
</P>
<P>
   Morgenthau said the bribes constituted a ''mob tax'' of at least
5 percent of a contract's value, and the payoff was possible only
with the cooperation of the corrupt contractors.
</P>
<P>
   ''If the contractors didn't go along, the deal couldn't go
forward,'' Morgenthau said. ''These contractors knew what they were
doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, federal prosecutors announced a six-count indictment
which names six defendants, all of whom are named in the state
indictment, and charges them with basically the same crimes charged
by the state.
</P>
<P>
   Morgenthau said he was unaware of the federal indictment, but
said it is not unusual for state and federal officials to run
parallel investigations.
</P>
<P>
   Morgenthau said 31 of the 38 state defendants were in custody
and the others were being sought. He said they include three groups
- Lucchese crime family members and associates, union members, and
contractors.
</P>
<P>
   The defendants were to be arraigned late Wednesday in
Manhattan's State Supreme Court. All are charged with enterprise
corruption, which is punishable by up to 25 years in prison, and
with related crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Under the federal indictments, the six defendants are charged
with conspiracies involving wire fraud or extortion or both. They
face prison terms that range from five to 20 years on each count
upon conviction. They are scheduled to be arraigned on Sept. 14 in
Manhattan's U.S. District Court, said Marvin Smilon, spokesman for
U.S. Attorney's Office.
</P>
<P>
   The state indictment charges that during the three years of the
investigation, defendants created ''no-show'' and ''no-work''
positions for ''made'' (formally inducted) mobsters of the Lucchese
crime family.
</P>
<P>
   Those jobs, in which the ''worker'' does not show up, or if he
shows up he does not work, were meant to provide what appeared to
be a legitimate income, as well as medical coverage and pension
benefits, for the employee.
</P>
<P>
   Three public projects investigated during the three-year probe
included two school construction jobs in Queens and one in the
Bronx, worth a total of $32 million and paid for by the state
School Construction Authority.
</P>
<P>
   Two other projects paid for with a total of $1 million in public
money included road resurfacing at the Triborough Bridge, and road
resurfacing and cable repair on the Queensborough Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   The three privately financed projects included the renovation of
the Park Central Hotel at Seventh Avenue and 56th Street, the
construction of the Doral Arrowwood Conference Center in Ryebrook,
N.Y., and the addition of five floors of apartments in the building
at 354 Broadway.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-06-00 1742 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000906.0119 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 17:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judiciary Opposes Camera Bill  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A bill aimed at cracking open federal
courtroom doors to television, radio and photo coverage got a
Senate subcommittee hearing Wednesday, but a chief sponsor of the
proposed legislation acknowledged it faces major hurdles -- among
them the chairman of the Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Charles Grassley, R-Iowa and chairman of a subcommittee on
courts oversight, said the bill he and Sen. Chuck Schumer, D-N.Y.,
introduced seeks ''to let the sun shine in on our federal courts.''
</P>
<P>
   But Edward Becker, a federal appellate judge from Philadelphia,
testified that the U.S. Judicial Conference, the federal
judiciary's policymaking body, vigorously opposes the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our mission is to administer the highest possible quality of
justice to each and every litigant,'' Becker said. ''We cannot
tolerate even a little bit of unfairness based on media coverage,
notwithstanding that society as a whole might in some way benefit,
for that would be inconsistent with our mission.''
</P>
<P>
   Becker questioned the educational value of having broadcast
coverage of federal trials and appellate hearings, contending that
the public most often would see only snippets of such proceedings.
''The courtroom is just a backdrop,'' he contended. ''What you get
out of this is a lot of nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Schumer said that same logic could lead federal judges to
conclude that the public and print news media should be banned from
all trials. The Supreme Court has ruled that the public and news
media have a constitutional right to attend courtroom proceedings,
specifically criminal trials.
</P>
<P>
   ''Public exposure of the processes of government is almost
always in the public interest,'' Schumer said.
</P>
<P>
   A federal trial judge, Nancy Gertner of Boston, testified in
favor of the bill. ''When the majority of Americans get their
information through a screen, our obligation to make proceedings
public has to include allowing those proceedings to be televised,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would let presiding judges decide whether to allow
electronic media coverage on a case-by-case basis. ''It's curious
to me that the Judicial Conference argues for more judicial
discretion all the time, but doesn't trust its judges to make
decisions regarding cameras in the courtroom,'' Grassley said.
</P>
<P>
   Another subcommittee member Sen. Russ Feingold, D-Wis., also
supported the legislation. But Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah and
chairman of the full Senate Judiciary Committee, released a
statement citing his agreement with the Judicial Conference that
''cameras and electronic media in the courtroom could interfere
with the federal courts' primary mission of dispensing justice.''
</P>
<P>
   In a brief interview after the two-hour hearing ended, Grassley
cited Hatch's opposition and said he did not plan to take the bill
to the full Judiciary Committee before 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The House passed a similar measure recently but that bill would
require the consent of all parties in a case before federal judges
could allow electronic media coverage.
</P>
<P>
   The bill is S. 721.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-06-00 1744 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000906.0120 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 17:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Ends Down 130; Dow Gains 50  </HEADLINE>
By LISA SINGHANIA
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Tech stocks tumbled for a second straight
session Wednesday as analysts cut their ratings on several
high-profile companies, while blue chips moved higher on news of a
major deal in the financial services industry.
</P>
<P>
   The high-tech driven Nasdaq composite index was off 129.84 at
4,013.34.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average closed up 50.03 at 11,310.64,
and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was down 14.83 at 1,492.25.
</P>
<P>
   Tech stocks fell for a second day, primarily because of more
analyst downgrades of prominent companies. On Tuesday, the
high-tech stocks slipped after a prominent analyst lowered his
rating onf Intel.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Micron Technology fell $9.50 to $68.75 Wednesday after
Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette lowered its rating on the memory
chipmaker from ''buy'' to ''underperform.''
</P>
<P>
   And telecom provider WorldCom fell $2.25 to $31.50 after
analysts from Lehman Brothers and Wachovia Securities downgraded
the stock.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think those downgrades are concerning people about
third-quarter earnings, so you're seeing weakness in those
stocks,'' said Barry Berman, managing director of equity trading
for Robert W. Baird &AMP; Co. in Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of MP3.com fell 69 cents -- more than 8 percent -- to $7.88
after a federal judge ruled Wednesday that the company had
willfully violated copyrights of music companies and awarded
Universal Music Group $25,000 per CD, a penalty that could reach as
much as $250 million.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo!, which has been on a slide in recent sessions, fell $5.06
to $112.06, and continued to fall in after-hours trading, after the
company's CEO said at an investment conference that the Internet
company plans to cut back advertising spending.
</P>
<P>
   With tech stocks already in a slump, the news from Yahoo! could
prompt continued selling when trading begins on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Financial stocks were also a focus Wednesday after Citigroup,
the nation's biggest financial services company, said it was buying
lender Associates First Capital for about $31.1 billion in stock.
The deal should speed Citigroup's global expansion in lending to
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Citigroup, a Dow component, fell $3.02 to $54.92, but shares of
Associates First Capital jumped $10.50, nearly 37.5 percent, to
$38.50.
</P>
<P>
   The news increased speculation that Deutsche Bank might be
eyeing J.P. Morgan as a potential takeover target. Shares of
Morgan, also a Dow component, closed up $7.81 at $167.75; its
advance accounted for much of the Dow's rise Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said a government report showing higher U.S.
productivity had little effect on trading although it bolstered the
belief that interest rates will remain stable for the near future.
</P>
<P>
   The Labor Department said Americans' productivity, a key measure
of rising living standards, surged at a 5.7 percent annual rate in
the second quarter. The strong gain pushed unit labor costs, a key
gauge of inflation pressures, down by a rate of 0.4 percent, the
lowest since the end of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Also Wednesday, crude for delivery in October surpassed the
previous 10-year high of $34.37 on the New York Mercantile
Exchange, reaching $34.45 before declining somewhat to $34.35.
</P>
<P>
   Higher oil prices are considered by some to be a potential
inflationary pressure, but at least one analyst wasn't worried.
</P>
<P>
   ''If this truly was a long-term inflationary threat, that would
be showing up at the bond market in the form of higher interest
rates and we don't see that happening,'' said Alan Skrainka, chief
market strategist at Edward Jones of St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 4-to-3 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange. Consolidated volume on the Big Board came
to 992.3 million shares, ahead of Tuesday's pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index was down 2.70 at 536.21.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 0.32 percent.
Germany's DAX index was down 0.84 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100 was
down 0.86 percent, and France's CAC-40 was down 0.87 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
