<HEADLINE> Groups go to court in effort to stop bear hunt  </HEADLINE>
By AMY WESTFELDT
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) - Animal rights advocates and a northern New
Jersey town asked an appellate court Wednesday to overrule a state
regulation ordering the first bear hunt in nearly 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey Animal Rights Alliance, the town of West Milford
and some residents filed an appeal to the state Fish and Game
Council's order to allow hunters to shoot black bear beginning
Sept. 18.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge filed with the Superior Court's appellate division
argues that the Fish and Game Council, a policy arm of the state
Division of Fish and Wildlife, does not have the legal authority to
order a hunt, and should have conducted more research about
alternatives to bear hunting.
</P>
<P>
   ''They have not followed through on what they are legislatively
mandated to do, as far as the scientific research,'' said Janine
Motta, a spokeswoman for the New Jersey Animal Rights Alliance.
</P>
<P>
   The Fish and Game Council ordered the first bear hunt in 29
years to curb a population it has estimated at more than 1,000.
Residents in northern New Jersey, the heart of the bear population,
have complained the animals have broken into cars and homes, killed
pets, destroyed property and scared people.
</P>
<P>
   The hunt's opponents say the division has overestimated the
number of bears and hasn't researched enough alternatives to
hunting them, such as birth control and deterrence.
</P>
<P>
   More than 20 towns, including West Milford, have passed
resolutions opposing a bear hunt. Most residents are not threatened
by the animals creeping around, said William Strazza, a Union
Township attorney who filed the appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a quality of life issue,'' Strazza said. ''People who
choose to live in that area in part are doing it because they
choose to live amongst wildlife.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the state Department of Environmental
Protection, which the Fish and Wildlife Division is part of,
declined comment on the challenge Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The state Senate overwhelmingly passed a bill to cancel the
hunt, but the Assembly did not take up the bill before it ended its
session for the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Strazza said he will ask DEP Commissioner Robert Shinn within
two days to postpone the hunt until the appeal is heard. If Shinn
refuses, he said he will seek an emergency hearing before an
appellate judge to postpone the hunt.
</P>
<P>
   The state has begun how-to seminars for hunters who are
accustomed to shooting at deer to make sure they are prepared to
shoot the much larger bear. The hunt is limited to 175 bear for the
season.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents say that even if they learn how to shoot them, the
hunters can't be sure they're killing the bears who are causing
problems with residents.
</P>
<P>
   ''The one who's in the woods and was killed was killed,'' Motta
said. ''The one who's in your back yard, he didn't learn that he
was not supposed to go into your back yard and eat birdseed. Nobody
learned anything except there's a dead bear in the woods.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
