<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 17:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sen. Pushes To Close Loophole  </HEADLINE>
By JANELLE CARTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration should move quickly
to close a Medicaid loophole that lets states inflate how much they
are spending for medical services to generate large federal
reimbursements, the Senate Finance Committee chairman said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''This has turned a program intended to provide health insurance
coverage to vulnerable low-income pregnant women, children, senior
citizens and individuals with disabilities into a bank account for
state projects having nothing to do with health care,'' said Sen.
William Roth, R-Del. ''Let me be very clear, this cannot and will
not be permitted to continue.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials have said the loophole has the potential to
cost the government tens of billions of dollars in overpayments.
This year, the government is estimated to lose $2 billion under the
loophole, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Timothy Westmoreland, director of the Center for Medicaid and
State Operations for the Health Care Financing Administration, told
lawmakers the agency hoped to have a proposed rule to close the
loophole issued by the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
   While some states have used the extra money for health related
projects, Westmoreland said several states have used to extra money
to fill budget gaps, reduce the state debt and even pay for
education programs. Because there is a loophole in the law, such
practices are not considered illegal.
</P>
<P>
   ''These practices. . . are inconsistent with the Medicaid
statute, congressional intent and administration policy,''
Westmoreland said.
</P>
<P>
   And Michael Mangano, principal deputy inspector general for the
Health and Human Services Department, said, ''We believe that
widespread manipulation by states. . . could undermine the
stability of the Medicaid program.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's how the loophole works. The Medicaid program, the
government's health care program for the poor, is a joint project
with the federal government paying at least 50 percent of the
costs. States with larger poor populations get a larger share from
the federal government. States set the amount they will pay health
providers, but the federal government provides a cap for payments.
</P>
<P>
   Under the loophole, a state will charge the maximum amount for
services at a local or county-owned facility even though the
services may actually cost substantially lower. The additional
money is then transferred back to the state and used for a number
of projects.
</P>
<P>
   There are currently 20 states with plans in place that allow
them to take advantage of the loophole, federal officials said.
Several others have plans pending to participate.
</P>
<P>
   States eligible to use the loophole are Alabama, California,
Illinois, Indiana, Iowa, Massachusetts, Michigan, Minnesota,
Nebraska, New Hampshire, New Mexico, New York, North Carolina,
North Dakota, Oregon, Pennsylvania, South Carolina, Tennessee,
Washington and New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://finance.senate.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-06-00 1758 </TRAILER>
