<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nothing New in Estonia Ferry Film  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL TARM
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLINN, Estonia (AP) -- Investigators of the Estonia ferry
accident that killed 852 people have studied new underwater film
footage of the 1994 wreck and say they saw nothing to warrant a
fresh probe.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can say there are no new facts requiring a new
investigation. None at all,'' said Kari Lehtola, a Finnish member
of the tri-nation commission that investigated the maritime
disaster, Europe's worst since World War II.
</P>
<P>
   A 1997 report by the Estonian-Finnish-Swedish commission blamed
the ferry's sinking in the Baltic Sea on faulty locks on the 50-ton
bow door and a slow reaction from the crew. But conspiracy theories
abound, including that a bomb exploded on board.
</P>
<P>
   Many survivors and victims' relatives have pressed for a new
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Four other official investigators who screened a half-hour
excerpt of the film, taken by a privately funded diving expedition
last week, all agreed nothing new was disclosed, according to
Finnish investigator Tuomo Karppinen.
</P>
<P>
   The film was shot by a diving team led by Gregg Bemis Jr., a
businessman from New Mexico who claimed that he may have found a
hole in the hull, possibly indicating a blast sank the ship.
</P>
<P>
   A 30-second segment of the alleged hole was previewed Monday. An
elongated black spot was visible on the hull but it wasn't clearly
a hole.
</P>
<P>
   Karppinen said Tuesday the alleged hole was most likely a
shadow.
</P>
<P>
   ''Before Mr. Bemis went down, he said he'd show the world an
explosion hole. So what's he showing us now? Footage of a sandbed
and a shadow. That's his hole,'' Karppinen said.
</P>
<P>
   The Estonia sank quickly to more than 250 feet deep in a Sept.
28, 1994, storm off the coast of Finland as it was en route from
Tallinn to Stockholm, Sweden.
</P>
<P>
   In Stockholm, Swedish Deputy Industry Minister Mona Sahlin said
it was too early to comment on the potential for a new inquiry, but
the government and opposition parties had agreed to send experts to
review the footage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
