<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study: Cop Program May Miss Goal  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL J. SNIFFEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A federally financed study concluded Wednesday
that President Clinton's program to put 100,000 police officers on
the street focused on the highest crime areas and fostered
community policing but estimated it might fall short of its
numerical goal.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department's Tom Frazier, director of the Community
Oriented Policing Services (COPS) program, responded that
additional grants had been made and technical assistance improved
since the researchers stopped gathering data in mid-1998. Frazier
predicted the six-year, $8.8 billion program would put 100,000 more
officers on the street by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the numerical dispute, Jeffrey Roth, director of the
Urban Institute's crime control policy studies, said his study
found that COPS ''had broad national impact on the levels and
styles of policing'' and its resources ''went where they were most
needed: high-crime areas.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the study did not try to quantify the program's impact
on crime, Roth said, ''We cannot rule out the possibility the
program accounts for part of the drop in national crime
statistics'' since the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   The evaluation by the Urban Institute, a private research group,
was funded by the Justice Department's National Institute of
Justice.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Justice Department's inspector general predicted
the program would fall 40,000 short of the original goal of putting
100,000 additional state and local cops on the street by the end of
2000.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, administration officials have altered their claims.
They now say that by May 1999 they completed funding of state and
local police department applications to hire or free from desk work
100,000 more officers.
</P>
<P>
   But the hiring and training new officers or hiring civilians or
buying equipment that would allow existing officers to move from
behind desks to street work can delay the arrival of new cops on
the street for up to several years, the administration says.
</P>
<P>
   Enacted in 1994, COPS provides money to state and local
departments to pay up to 75 percent of each new officer's salary
and benefits for three years. The departments are required to
submit a plan for retaining the new officers after that with their
own money, but not all of them have been retained.
</P>
<P>
   Citing data through mid-1998, the Urban Institute estimated that
because of retention problems and limited productivity gains from
new technology the program would reach a peak of between 69,000 and
84,600 new or transferred officers on the streets in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The institute estimated the long-term increase would fall to
between 62,800 and 83,900 new or transferred officers in 2003 and
beyond.
</P>
<P>
   ''To those who considered the level of policing in 1994
inadequate,'' the report said, ''this constitutes success, though
it falls well short of the Clinton administration's target of
100,000 new cops on the beat.'' The report said the exact increase
in officers may never be known because of the difficulty in
measuring the transfers of officers to the street that result from
productivity gains.
</P>
<P>
   The study found that the one percent of COPS grantees with the
highest murder rates received 31 percent of all funds through 1997.
These areas accounted for 54 percent of all U.S. murders that year.
</P>
<P>
   The report credited the program with energizing a national
movement toward community policing, in which police officers work
with citizen, government, church and business groups on crime
prevention and problem-solving.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few departments actually shared decision-making with
community groups, but many launched truancy prevention efforts,
foot or bicycle patrols or late-night recreation programs, among
others.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
