<HEADLINE> Wireless Auction Challenge Nixed  </HEADLINE>
By KALPANA SRINIVASAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal regulators denied a challenge
Wednesday to a fall auction of valuable chunks of the airwaves that
companies are eyeing for wireless phone and Internet services.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Communications Commission said Wednesday it plans to
go forward with a re-auction of frequencies that were awarded
several years ago to NextWave Telecom, a company that later filed
for bankruptcy. The FCC declared that the licenses held by NextWave
were automatically canceled because the company had failed to meet
its payment deadlines.
</P>
<P>
   The commission announced Wednesday it would re-auction the
licenses -- expected to fetch the government billions of dollars in
bids -- on Dec. 12, pushing the auction back slightly from a
previously scheduled date.
</P>
<P>
   NextWave had petitioned the agency to reconsider its decision to
cancel the company's licenses and re-auction them. NextWave had
offered to pay its debt in full and argued that the commission
acted unlawfully by revoking licenses while the business was trying
to reorganize.
</P>
<P>
   ''Commission review presented a good opportunity to end the
litigation and allow NextWave to put its spectrum licenses to use
immediately to benefit consumers and competition,'' said Michael
Wack, NextWave's deputy general counsel. ''The interests of
consumers, taxpayers and NextWave's creditors and investors could
have been harmonized in a win-win resolution.''
</P>
<P>
   Wack said the company plans to appeal the FCC's decision to the
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia and will
likely seek a stay of the auction.
</P>
<P>
   The commission has held firm that it must protect the integrity
of the auction process by requiring bidders to meet their payment
deadlines. FCC officials fear that allowing bankrupt companies to
hold on to the licenses -- and eventually pay only a portion of what
they bid -- will undermine the entire process and stall the rollout
of future wireless services.
</P>
<P>
   ''Enabling American consumers to access the Internet with
handheld wireless devices is one of the most exciting advances in
telecommunications,'' said FCC Chairman William Kennard Wednesday.
''We can ill afford to delay bringing new communications services
to the public.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say the licenses are worth billions more now than the
$4 billion NextWave originally bid for them because of the
increasing demand for wireless voice and data services. The
upcoming re-auction will allow the nation's largest wireless
companies to also vie for some the frequencies, which were
originally reserved for small businesses. That means businesses
like Verizon Wireless, SBC Communications and others can bid on
certain licenses under the modified auction rules.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Federal Communications Commission site:
http://www.fcc.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-06-00 1816 </TRAILER>
