<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Officials have ambitious proposals, but time is limited  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Gov. Christie Whitman wants new campaign
finance laws by Election Day. She also has plans for health care
reform.
</P>
<P>
   Senate President Donald T. DiFrancesco, R-Union, wants his $400
million property tax reform plan approved. He also has a $60
million prescription drug proposal in the works.
</P>
<P>
   Assembly Speaker Jack Collins, R-Salem, says he has ideas for
the fall legislative session on education and school construction.
</P>
<P>
   But the state Senate's first voting session is Sept. 21, and the
Assembly isn't due back until Oct. 5.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not optimistic,'' Assembly Minority Leader Joseph V.
Doria, Jr. said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   That's not partisan politics from the Hudson County Democrat.
It's pragmatism.
</P>
<P>
   ''The time for us to do these things is really limited,'' Doria
said.
</P>
<P>
   Even bipartisan slam dunks like health care and property tax
relief still need to be reviewed by committees in both houses and
approved by the Legislature, Doria said.
</P>
<P>
   As appealing as property tax relief sounds, legislators still
need to examine DiFrancesco's proposals, Doria said.
</P>
<P>
   ''In order for us to do our jobs responsibly, we need to
carefully review the things that are being presented to us,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   DiFrancesco's $400 million tax relief plan would raise the
Homestead Rebate for the first time in 10 years and double the NJ
Saver rebate. DiFrancesco also wants to put $100 million over three
years into grants for direct municipal property tax relief.
</P>
<P>
   His $60 million drug plan would offer middle-income seniors and
disabled residents low-cost prescriptions. Another $60 million in
programs include funding for hospital charity care programs,
Medicaid reimbursements to physicians and emergency room clinics in
urban hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is an ambitious agenda,'' DiFrancesco spokeswoman Rae
Hutton said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The intent in unveiling it late this summer was so we could
hit the ground running in the fall,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   DiFrancesco will make ''every effort'' to have the majority of
the bills pass the Senate by early December, Hutton said. The
prescription drug measure is designed to be working by February,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Legislators already have cleared major issues like funding for
the Transportation Trust Fund and court-ordered school
construction, Collins said. With those major issues hurdled,
lawmakers can focus on other measures, including tax relief and
health care, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''What's the best way to do that, that's what we'll be talking
about,'' the Assembly speaker said.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman announced Aug. 29 her plans to change campaign finance
law and a state panel to aid patients in challenging HMO insurance
decisions. Disappointed patients should be able to sue insurance
companies, Whitman said.
</P>
<P>
   Another consumer protection proposal would target home
improvement contractors. If it becomes law, all contractors would
be registered with the state. Whitman also wants to increase
criminal penalties for consumer fraud.
</P>
<P>
   ''Whatever the governor wants us to take a look at, we will,''
Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman spokeswoman Jayne O'Connor said the governor believes
the campaign finance package can become law by early November. The
other issues should see action by the end of the fall, O'Connor
said.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman is not daunted by the fact no hearings have been
scheduled or bills posted.
</P>
<P>
   ''She's still committed to that time frame,'' the spokeswoman
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
