<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cholera bacteria found in Ocean City lagoon  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   OCEAN CITY, N.J. (AP) - A series of tests have determined the
presence of cholera bacteria in a lagoon where a victim reported
swimming before his diagnosis with the disease, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   All six samples of water taken from the 17th Street lagoon along
Ocean City's back bay showed Vibrio cholera bacteria, a
non-epidemic type of cholera, according to Louis Lamanna, public
health coordinator for Cape May County.
</P>
<P>
   The bacteria matched what was found in the stool of an
unidentified 30-year-old Ocean City man treated for cholera last
month. He was hospitalized but survived the rare intestinal
disease, which can be fatal.
</P>
<P>
   The samples were taken Aug. 24. A new round of samples were
taken at 18th Street and in the open water at the mouth of the two
lagoons, Lamanna said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are anxious to gather more information to see how
widespread this problem is,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lamanna said the findings do not necessarily mean the man
contracted the disease from swimming in the lagoon. He told
officials he swam there with his dog, but he also said he ate
undercooked softshell crabs and raw clams shortly before he became
sick.
</P>
<P>
   His physician, Dr. Athanasios Papastamelos of Linwood, has said
he believes tainted shellfish was to blame.
</P>
<P>
   ''We can't say for sure whether he got it from the water or from
the seafood. He may have gotten a double whammy, or both. Or it may
be one of those where we never know how he got it,'' Lamanna said.
</P>
<P>
   Normally associated with exposure to untreated water or sewage,
cholera is rare in the United States. According to the federal
Centers for Disease Control, about five people in the nation are
diagnosed with it annually.
</P>
<P>
   Swimming and bathing in the lagoon, already discouraged by city
officials, is now prohibited by order of the county health
department.
</P>
<P>
   Residents, meanwhile, are keeping a wide berth. Some won't even
let their dogs swim in the lagoon anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have Jet Skis and Waverunners and we won't take them out,''
said Kathy Gillespie, 24, a summer resident of 17th Street. ''I
have a chocolate Labrador and I won't let him go in, either. I
don't want cholera.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
