<HEADLINE> Pattern of child abuse noted by doctor in death penalty case  </HEADLINE>
By DIANE SCARPONI
<TEXT>
<P>
   WATERBURY, Conn. (AP) - A man accused of beating his
girlfriend's 2-year-old daughter to death listened Wednesday as a
doctor testified about the severe abuse the toddler suffered in the
days before she died.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors claim Ivo Colon, 20, killed Keriana Tellado on July
17, 1998 by smashing her head repeatedly against a shower wall. He
has pleaded innocent to charges of murder and capital felony. Colon
could face the death penalty if convicted, because the victim was a
child.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Peter Jacoby, the head of the emergency department at St.
Mary's Hospital, used a dozen photos of Keriana's body to show the
jury injuries that ranged from a broken arm to a mark behind her
ear - an indication, he said, of a severe blow to the head. Other
gouges, scratch marks, bruises and discolorations crisscrossed her
body. A chunk of skin was missing from the top of her shoulder, and
some hair had been pulled from her scalp, Jacoby said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The child was abused. This child had injuries in various
stages of development,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Colon reportedly told investigators he couldn't deal with the
child's lack of toilet training.
</P>
<P>
   Family members packed the courtroom on the opening day of the
trial, sometimes making emotional outbursts. Many wore T-shirts
that showed a picture of Keriana and read: ''In memory of Keriana
1-27-96 to 7-17-98.''
</P>
<P>
   The girl's father, Francisco Tellado, said he wants Colon to be
executed.
</P>
<P>
   ''I just wish the jury would get to the deliberations and get to
the death penalty. The fact is that he did it, and the defense is
trying to twist everything around,'' Tellado said.
</P>
<P>
   The girl's mother, Virginia Quintero, is charged with failing to
protect her daughter and lying to police about what happened. She
is being tried separately and may be called to testify against
Colon.
</P>
<P>
   Hospital notes show that Keriana was blue and cold when she came
into the emergency room.
</P>
<P>
   Jacoby said when an emergency room worker questioned Quintero
about what happened, she said Keriana fell in the shower.
</P>
<P>
   Jacoby said he did not think that statement was true, since the
girl's hair was dry and she had injuries all over her body.
</P>
<P>
   A neighbor, Juana Rivera, testified that Colon came to her
apartment the day Keriana died and asked to use the telephone to
call his mother.
</P>
<P>
   ''He said, 'My baby got hurt,''' Rivera said, adding that he
later said Keriana had fallen out of a window.
</P>
<P>
   Rivera said she told Colon to call police or an ambulance, but
he called his mother instead to pick up the child.
</P>
<P>
   Rivera testified that she saw Keriana as Colon's mother was
taking her out of the apartment house.
</P>
<P>
   ''The baby's eyes was turned back. She was bruised. The skin
tone was yellowish,'' Rivera said.
</P>
<P>
   She said the girl's mother and a sister, Crystal Tellado,
''looked scared.'' She noticed a big bruise on Crystal's leg.
</P>
<P>
   Before Quintero started seeing Colon, she and her three
preschool-aged daughters were frequently seen around the apartment
house, Rivera said. The girls' grandmother cared for them while
Quintero was at work.
</P>
<P>
   After Colon moved in, Rivera said she rarely saw the girls.
</P>
<P>
   A jury of seven women and five men was chosen to hear the case
before Superior Court Judge Frank D'Addabbo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
