<HEADLINE> Penn Traffic still reels from reorganization but is improving  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) - Still reeling from its restructuring, Penn
Traffic on Wednesday reported a net loss for the second quarter of
$23.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   However, Penn Traffic said its earnings for the quarter before
interest, taxes, depreciation and amortization - a popular
financial measure also known as ''EBITDA'' - were $28.2 million, an
increase of 12.7 percent over the second quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ''It has now been more than a year since our company completed
its financial restructuring and we began implementing a business
strategy designed to generate sales and operating income growth,''
said Joseph V. Fisher, chief executive officer for the troubled
supermarket chain. ''Our same-store sales were positive in the
first half of this fiscal year.''
</P>
<P>
   The company said the EBITDA rise stemmed from a 1.3 percent
increase in same-store sales, an increase in allowance income from
the company's vendors, and the benefits of numerous cost-saving
measures.
</P>
<P>
   Revenues for the second quarter were approximately $629.7
million, compared to $632.7 million a year ago, a decrease of a
half percent.
</P>
<P>
   The company said its $100 million, 18-month capital expenditure
program was proceeding on schedule. Since the beginning of the
fiscal year, Penn Traffic has completed 14 major store remodelings.
Nine have re-opened since the beginning of the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   In June, Penn Traffic announced a program to buy back up to $10
million of its common stock. So far, it has repurchased 48,000
shares at an average price of $7.15 per share, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   Penn Traffic owns and operates 220 supermarkets in upstate New
York, Ohio, West Virginia, Pennsylvania, Vermont and New Hampshire
under the Big Bear, Big Bear Plus, Bi-Lo, Quality, and P&AMP;C names.
It also operates wholesale food distribution businesses serving 84
licensed franchises and 65 independent operators.
</P>
</TEXT>
