<HEADLINE> Officials: Joel O'Keefe caught prepping for next escape attempt  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   DANNEMORA, N.Y. (AP) - Inmate Joel O'Keefe is back in solitary
Wednesday after officials at Clinton Correctional Facility say they
found him allegedly squirreling makeshift hooks and ropes.
</P>
<P>
   O'Keefe, 40, formerly of Argyle in Washington County, bolted
from a State Police car on Sept. 23, 1994, Hundreds of police
combed the area for more than two weeks, using helicopters and
police dogs. But O'Keefe dodged the dragnet, making his way to
Bennington, Vt., and wasn't captured until a Subway sandwich shop
clerk recognized him ordering a six-inch meatball sub.
</P>
<P>
   After four years housed in administrative segregation at Attica
Correctional Facility, a court settlement required O'Keefe be
permitted to mix with other prisoners. He was moved to Clinton in
December of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   According to state Department of Correctional Services
Commissioner Glenn Goord, a correction officer saw a suspicious
looking bag among a group of unattended bags by the mess hall about
7:30 a.m. Tuesday. The officer noted that O'Keefe picked up the bag
about 7:30 a.m. Tuesday as he was heading toward a work assignment
in the facility tailor shop.
</P>
<P>
   A search of the bag revealed an 8-inch wide by 14-inch long
plywood grappling hook attached to an approximately 25-foot long
hand-woven cloth. Guards found three more pieces of cloth tied
together under O'Keefe's desk in the tailor shop, prison officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Last year, a court settlement required that I take (O'Keefe)
out of administrative segregation and place him in less-restrictive
general confinement housing,'' Goord said. ''Today's discovery
validates our decision to place O'Keefe in restrictive housing.''
That settlement also required the state to pay O'Keefe $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   Less than two weeks ago, prison officials denied O'Keefe's
request to attend his father's funeral. O'Keefe told officials he
attempted the escape because he was ''despondent'' about missing
the event.
</P>
<P>
   O'Keefe was convicted of burglary based on charges he sodomized
a woman at knifepoint. Those charges plus the escape charges
resulted in sentences totaling 10 to 20 years in state prison.
</P>
<P>
   O'Keefe now faces charges of attempted escape and possession of
prison contraband.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
