<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 18:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hamilton Twp. teachers ordered back to work; no other strikes expected </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   HAMILTON, N.J. (AP) - A state Superior Court judge Wednesday
ordered striking teachers in the Hamilton Township district to go
back to work Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Anthony J. Parrillo at a hearing Wednesday afternoon also
ordered the township school board to hold a negotiating session
with the teachers union within 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Joseph, a spokeswoman for the New Jersey Education
Association, said teacher contracts are yet to be settled in 80
other districts in the state, but no other strikes are expected.
</P>
<P>
   The Hamilton Township Education Association, representing about
1,450 teachers and other staff in the Mercer County district, went
on strike Wednesday morning. Schools in the district, which has
13,000 students, opened, but students were told to go home a short
time later.
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey School Boards Association condemned the strike
and criticized the union for using ''students as pawns in its
attempts to influence the negotiations process.''
</P>
<P>
   The township school board asked the judge to issue a temporary
restraining order barring the teachers from striking. He did so at
a 2 p.m. court hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph said the union has scheduled a meeting for 5:30 a.m.
Thursday to discuss the judge's order.
</P>
<P>
   The union represents teachers, aides, custodians, bus drivers,
and clerical and cafeteria workers.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Schwartz, president of the Hamilton Township Education
Association, said the union and school board have not agreed on
salary increases. The union has requested 5 percent raises in each
of the three years of the contract; the board has offered raises of
4 percent in the first year of the contract, 4.1 percent in the
second year and 4.2 percent in the third year.
</P>
<P>
   Schwartz also said the board ''isn't willing to treat our
members equally, when it comes to discussing certain benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   Messages left at Board of Education offices were not returned
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph said the Hamilton Township Education Association and the
Board of Education have had four negotiating sessions.
</P>
<P>
   A state-appointed mediator has assisted in the negotiations, the
School Boards Association said.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of districts throughout the state settled contracts in
recent weeks. Of the 186 public school districts where teacher
contracts were to be renewed, 80 were not settled as of Wednesday.
Two weeks ago, teachers in 117 districts were without contracts.
</P>
<P>
   ''They do settle this time of year,'' Joseph said. ''As school
opens it's important that school employees go back with a
contract.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to salaries and benefits, many of the districts are
negotiating the length of the work day. Districts are seeking to
increase instructional time to help them meet new curriculum
standards, said Frank Belluscio, spokesman for the school boards
association.
</P>
<P>
   The average teacher salary increase for the 2000-2001 school
year was 4 percent. The average teacher salary in New Jersey was
$51,692 for the 1998-99 school year, the latest figure available.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
