<HEADLINE> Iran Parliament To Probe Attacks  </HEADLINE>
By ALI AKBAR DAREINI
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEHRAN, Iran (AP) -- Iran's reformist-controlled parliament voted
Wednesday to investigate attacks on a student pro-democracy seminar
last month that led to rioting and the death of a policeman.
</P>
<P>
   A majority in the 290-seat parliament voted in favor of
launching an investigation into clashes that erupted in the western
city of Khorramabad when hard-line vigilantes attacked the meeting
of Iran's largest reformist student group.
</P>
<P>
   Several legislators will travel to Khorramabad to investigate
the violence later this month, said lawmaker Rajabali Mazrouei. He
gave no further details.
</P>
<P>
   The students' Office for Fostering Unity ended its annual
weeklong seminar two days early after the attack when provincial
authorities said they would not be able to protect them.
</P>
<P>
   Iran's judiciary, which is controlled by hard-liners, launched
an investigation into the unrest last month but is yet to issue a
report on its findings.
</P>
<P>
   But student leaders said they had little faith in the
judiciary's fairness and that a parliamentary investigation was
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ''The parliament is the best body to probe the savagery
committed by pressure groups. But investigation alone is not
enough. We want the establishment to deal with the perpetrators,''
Ebrahim Sheikh, a leader of the Office for Fostering Unity, told
The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   ''Usually the verdicts issued by judiciary officials are in line
with their political affiliations and not with justice,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Hard-liners control key government institutions, including the
broadcast networks, the military and police and have been trying to
stifle the social and political reforms initiated by President
Mohammad since he took office in 1997. In recent months,
hard-liners have closed down 24 reformist newspapers and jailed
dozens of writers and intellectuals.
</P>
<P>
   Student groups are currently at the forefront of the fight for
reforms, which are backed by a large majority of Iranians.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
