<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 19:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Labor Council goes to court to block city's new parade regulations  </HEADLINE>
By SAMUEL MAULL
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - The Central Labor Council, a group of about 500
labor unions in the city, has gone to court to stop the city from
enforcing new parade rules during the Labor Day Parade next
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The new rules include: no open flame cooking; no food service
from parked vehicles; a maximum height of 12 feet for floats; and
''a zero tolerance policy for alcohol consumption. Violators will
be issued a summons.''
</P>
<P>
   The council says in court papers that the unions will lose
hundreds of thousands of dollars if the city is allowed to enforce
rules that it has sprung on parade organizers and participants at
''the 11th hour.''
</P>
<P>
   Many locals have already paid for food, services and equipment
to accommodate an expected 500,000 people at this year's
festivities, court papers say, with some union locals spending
close to $20,000.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Menagh, lawyer for the council, said the city is due in
Manhattan's State Supreme Court on Thursday to explain why it
should not be barred from enforcing the new rules, which were
announced last month.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant Corporation Counsel Gabriel Taussig says that the
rules about which the council is complaining are not new.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are enforcing existing law,'' Taussig said. ''There is law
against having an open flame, and we are going to enforce it.
Likewise there is a law against having an open container of alcohol
(at a parade). These are not new rules.''
</P>
<P>
   Taussig confirmed that the city will respond to the council's
court order on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The city announced the rules, including the ban on alcohol sales
at outdoor events, last month mostly because of the dozens of
sexual assaults that followed the Puerto Rican Day Parade on June
11,
</P>
<P>
   Menagh said police officials who met with parade organizers
during the past three months did not say until Aug. 30 that rules
for the Sept. 9 Labor Day Parade would be different.
</P>
<P>
   ''The city's administrative code says that if they change the
rules, they have to give adequate notice to the people who are
affected,'' Menagh said. ''Ten days is not adequate notice.''
</P>
<P>
   Menagh said he and his clients are not concerned about the
alcohol ban but they are worried about the money the unions could
lose.
</P>
<P>
   The parade is to form at 44th Street and continue north on Fifth
Avenue to 72nd Street. About 500 unions are expected to be
represented in the march.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-06-00 1902 </TRAILER>
