<HEADLINE> Clinton Speech Short, Yet Too Long  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- It was one of President Clinton's shortest
speeches ever. And yet it was too long.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is famous for talking at length, reluctant to give up
the microphone as long as anyone is willing to listen. He was
assigned five minutes Wednesday to address the United Nations
Millennium Summit, a gathering of about 160 world leaders.
</P>
<P>
   He spoke for a little more than eight minutes. No one complained
that he went into overtime, perhaps because he called it ''the last
opportunity I will have as president to address this General
Assembly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
