<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Corzine goofs while accepting Sierra Club endorsement  </HEADLINE>
By RALPH SIEGEL
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Democrat Jon Corzine got the coveted
endorsement of the Sierra Club Wednesday in his race for U.S
Senate, but in accepting it committed a freshman mistake at the
microphone that dulled some of the shine.
</P>
<P>
   Promoting himself as an unreserved supporter of all efforts to
save open space, Corzine praised New Jersey's million-acre
preservation program approved by the voters in a November 1998
referendum.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters asked if the Democrat - known for having missed
several elections during his Wall Street days - actually voted on
that one, and he said he had. Staff for Republican candidate Bob
Franks had distributed a news release saying he had not.
</P>
<P>
   ''That is incorrect. I voted in 1998. Check the records,''
Corzine said sharply. ''Every instance in which there is a
referendum on open space or protecting the environment, almost, in
my memory, I have always voted.''
</P>
<P>
   A few hours after the news conference, Corzine aide Tom Shea
called The Associated Press to correct the candidate's memory,
saying he had not voted in 1998 after all. ''He supported the bond
issue, but he didn't make it to vote on that particular day,'' Shea
said.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Tittel, New Jersey director of the Sierra Club, said
Corzine's error on his record as a voter does not change their
endorsement of him. ''Missing a vote is regrettable, but I don't
think it matters,'' Tittel said. ''When we did the endorsement
process, we were looking toward the future.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sierra Club did, however, look into the past in evaluating
Franks, saying that while the four-term congressman had voted in
support of some environmental initiatives, his overall record was
spotty and mediocre.
</P>
<P>
   The Sierra Club endorsed Franks over Democrat Maryanne Connelly
in his successful 1998 re-election bid in the 7th Congressional
District. Tittel said his track record has slipped since then.
</P>
<P>
   The Franks campaign brushed off the endorsement, saying Franks
had a proven record of leadership on environmental votes and bill
changes to help New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Franks campaign manager Charlie Smith said Corzine's error in
recalling whether he had voted on the 1998 open-space referendum
revealed serious flaws.
</P>
<P>
   ''Is it a small matter? Three times he answered that question,
ultimately untruthfully,'' Smith said. ''The Corzine campaign has
been insisting on very few public appearances possibly for exactly
this reason.''
</P>
<P>
   Corzine said environmental concerns must be at the top of the
political agenda, from clean water to preventing sprawl. ''Without
a clean environment, none of the other things will happen,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   After the Sierra Club endorsement at the Statehouse, Corzine
visited an abandoned factory site in a depressed area of the city.
He called for more upfront funding from federal agencies to assess
such sites more quickly for cleanup and new development.
</P>
<P>
   The site of the former Magic Marker plant he visited has been
untouched for 11 years because testing to assess cleanup needs has
not been completed, local officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine pledged to support the federal Clean Water Act when it
comes up for renewal next year. Tittel said the Sierra Club was
scornful of Franks' votes on the same measure in 1994. The
Republican-sponsored version Franks had voted for was opposed by
environmental groups as a trick to weaken water-treatment rules,
and it was ultimately scuttled by the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   Smith acknowledged the 1994 vote by Franks went against the
grain of groups like the Sierra Club. But he said Franks had played
a key role with many votes and amendments to strengthen laws
controlling the quality of water in rivers, the ocean and the
household tap.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-06-00 1917 </TRAILER>
