<HEADLINE> State Officials: No sign of West Nile virus in humans  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - Investigations into the illnesses of 39
people across Connecticut have shown no link to the West Nile
virus, state health officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Public Health has looked into 25 human cases
of encephalitis, 15 cases of aseptic meningitis and one case of
fever, in an effort to determine if the West Nile virus was
responsible. Test results in 37 of those cases showed no sign of
the virus. Officials were still awaiting results in two cases
Wednesday
</P>
<P>
   Eight human cases of West Nile virus have been reported in New
York this year.
</P>
<P>
   In Connecticut, 223 birds - the vast majority of which were
crows - have tested positive for the virus in 35 communities.
Southington and Middletown were added to that list Wednesday . The
virus also has been found in three pools of bird-biting mosquitoes
in Stamford and Norwalk.
</P>
<P>
   The virus is transmitted to humans by mosquitoes and can
sometimes lead to a deadly swelling of the brain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
