<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 19:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Redskins Defense Paying Dividends  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASHBURN, Va. (AP) -- In the aftermath of Washington's 20-17
victory over Carolina on Sunday, it's not clear whether owner Dan
Snyder's spending spree created a Super Bowl-caliber team.
</P>
<P>
   The following is certain: the defense is greatly improved.
</P>
<P>
   The unit, ranked 27th overall in 1999, shot up to No. 8 after
yielding 236 yards to Carolina's potent offense, which averaged 355
last season. The Panthers' passing game -- rated second in the NFL
in 1999 -- gained only 124 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Why the impressive upgrade?
</P>
<P>
   The defense is much more intense. An attack-style approach shut
down the Panthers in the second half and helped record six sacks
overall. At that pace, the Redskins would finish with a
league-record 96 sacks.
</P>
<P>
   New defensive coordinator Ray Rhodes is credited with instilling
more aggressiveness in his players. His predecessor, Mike Nolan,
used an otherwise passive game plan.
</P>
<P>
   ''Seemed like every play we were coming after the offense, and
we weren't reacting to what they were going to do,'' defensive end
Ndukwe Kalu said. ''We set the tone and let them react to us. Just
from reading the papers last season, a lot of guys were complaining
that our defense wasn't aggressive enough. No way we can complain
about that this year.''
</P>
<P>
   A major reason for that is Bruce Smith, one of Snyder's marquee
acquisitions. The NFL's No. 2 career sack leader terrorized
Carolina's linemen, particularly left tackle Clarence Jones, and
had 1&AMP;frac12; sacks. He drew double teams, giving left end Marco Coleman
(2&AMP;frac12; sacks) a wide path to quarterback Steve Berlin. Linebackers
Derek Smith and Kevin Mitchell each had a sack.
</P>
<P>
   ''Having Bruce Smith on the other side sure helps,'' Coleman
said. ''Seems like the whole offensive line is on him. I'm going to
do everything I can to take advantage of that.''
</P>
<P>
   The ferocity of another high-priced newcomer, safety Mark
Carrier, was evident late in the second quarter. With the Panthers
driving for a touchdown to put them up by 10 points, Carrier broke
up a pass around the 10-yard line with a jarring hit on tight end
Wesley Walls, who remained sprawled on the field for several
minutes. Two plays later, Carolina's Richie Cunningham missed a
27-yard field goal.
</P>
<P>
   Cornerback Deion Sanders, who was quiet Sunday, is another huge
defensive asset.
</P>
<P>
   ''We just have guys on defense who have the potential to make
big plays,'' Coleman said. ''When you add guys like Deion Sanders,
Mark Carrier, Bruce Smith, every play you're looking to see who's
going to make that big play. That's the biggest attribute.''
</P>
<P>
   The defense showed a weakness in the first half. Carolina
running back Tim Biakabutuka ran through some gaping holes for 66
yards. He once gained 41 yards after maneuvering around the right
end. But the defense clamped down in the second half, when he
tallied only 22 yards.
</P>
<P>
   This Sunday, the Redskins will be on the road facing a Detroit
offense that produced only 187 yards and six points in a 14-10
victory over New Orleans. Stoney Case, substituting for the injured
Charlie Batch, was 13-of-25 for 100 yards. But Batch, who led the
Lions to a 6-2 record by the midpoint of last season, is almost
healthy enough to return as the starter, according to Lions coach
Bobby Ross.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit also is coming off a 33-17 victory over the Redskins
last year in the Silverdome, and Kalu knows the Redskins' defense
can't take the Lions lightly.
</P>
<P>
   ''We can't let such a good game (against Carolina) get to our
head because we all know what happened last year against Detroit,''
he said. ''So it's going to be a big test for us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-06-00 1939 </TRAILER>
