<HEADLINE> Lawyer will submit bill to Albany for McKenna's defense  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - One of two police officer found innocent of
beating a College of Saint Rose basketball in a police garage was
cleared of departmental charges Wednesday, allowing him to return
to the beat after some three years on paid leave.
</P>
<P>
   The case stemmed from an October 1997 bar brawl between then
21-year-old Jermaine Henderson and the officers, who were off duty
at the time. Henderson was arrested after the fight and taken back
to the police garage where he said he was assaulted while
handcuffed.
</P>
<P>
   The case was closely watched by the Albany chapter of the Albany
chapter of the National Association for the Advancement of Colored
People, which says black youth frequently report being roughed up
by city police.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution was dealt a setback when Henderson refused to
testify in court, citing his Fifth Amendment right against
self-incrimination. Prior to the trial, Henderson agreed to settle
his civil rights lawsuit against the city for $60,000.
</P>
<P>
   A jury cleared 0fficers William Bonnani and Sean McKenna in
March of 1999, saying there wasn't enough evidence to convict.
</P>
<P>
   The arbitration hearing was the final step in clearing Bonnani.
A decision on McKenna is still pending.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson, of Sharon, Mass., is the son of former NBA guard
Gerald Henderson, who played for the New York Knicks and Boston
Celtics during his 13-year career.
</P>
</TEXT>
