<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Williams Brings Force to Bills  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN WAWROW
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORCHARD PARK, N.Y. (AP) -- Pat Williams has surprised everyone in
the NFL. Everyone, that is, except for the Buffalo Bills.
</P>
<P>
   Signed as an undrafted free agent for the NFL minimum salary in
1997, the defensive tackle Williams is emerging as a force in the
Bills' new-look scheme. Lining up alongside fellow heavyweight nose
tackle Ted Washington, the two 310-plus-pounders provide an
effective and -- after one game -- unstoppable one-two punch.
</P>
<P>
   ''It worked good. Not anybody can stop me or Ted,'' Williams
said after practice Wednesday. ''(Washington) softens then up for
me, and then I go out and punish them a little more.
</P>
<P>
   ''So Ted punishes them, I punish them, and they be done.''
</P>
<P>
   That pretty much sums up what happened to the Tennessee Titans
in the Bills' season-opening 16-13 victory Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Facing Titans star back Eddie George, the Bills added a wrinkle
to their defense by inserting Williams alongside Washington and
veteran end Phil Hansen on first-down plays.
</P>
<P>
   The help limit George -- the NFL's leading rusher over the past
three years -- to a mere 37 yards. In all, the two combined for 10
tackles and a sack.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to Titans center Kevin Long, who took much of the
brunt, Williams said: ''We pounded on him that he didn't want to
play no more. You could see it in his eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   So much for the concerns on how the Bills will replace defensive
end Bruce Smith.
</P>
<P>
   And so much for the teams that passed on Williams, a Texas A&AMP;M
product, in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a great story,'' Bills coach Wade Phillips said. ''He was
a good player in college, good athlete, had some potential but
didn't get drafted. We signed him. We liked him. I think he's an
outstanding player right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Realizing how good he was, the Bills restructured Williams'
contract last March, extending it into a five-year $8.7 million
deal, plus a $3.8 million signing bonus.
</P>
<P>
   The new scheme works simply. Williams, Washington's backup last
year, lines up just off center. Washington faces the weak-side
guard. Hansen moves to the strong side, while outside linebacker
Sam Rogers plays just off the line as a pass rusher.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Washington attracts the double team, allowing
Williams and Rogers room to penetrate.
</P>
<P>
   ''We worked on it in training camp,'' Bills defensive
coordinator Ted Cottrell said. ''Luckily, no one saw it. And then
we popped it on Tennessee. I guess it surprised them a little
bit.''
</P>
<P>
   The Green Bay Packers, who visit Buffalo on Sunday, won't be as
surprised. But it still won't be easy to deal with, said Packers
coach Mike Sherman.
</P>
<P>
   ''You put those 300-plus-pounders inside right there ... they
pretty much shut everything down,'' Sherman said. ''That was great
on their part and boded well for their defense.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-06-00 2013 </TRAILER>
