<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Elections regulators reject professor's complaint  </HEADLINE>
By RICH HARRIS
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - Sen. Joseph Lieberman can run for both
the vice presidency and re-election to the Senate, the state
Elections Enforcement Commission confirmed Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The panel's general counsel, Jeffrey Garfield, rejected the
complaint of a politics professor who said Lieberman's re-election
campaign was ''frivolous'' and ''irresponsibly self-indulgent'' and
urged that he be eliminated from the Senate ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman had already announced his intention to run for
re-election when Al Gore selected him to be his running mate. If
elected to both offices, Lieberman would have to resign from the
Senate to serve as vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Garfield said a 1964 written opinion by the attorney general
found that state election laws permitted such a dual candidacy.
That opinion was written when then-Sen. Thomas Dodd, who was
running for re-election, was under consideration for the Democratic
vice presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ''Nothing in that regard has changed since 1964,'' Garfield
said.
</P>
<P>
   Garfield said he had informed Fairfield University Professor
John Orman of his decision. Orman had argued that the commission
had a legal duty to prevent ''frivolous'' candidates from appearing
on the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Orman had also argued that Lieberman's Senate campaign
benefitted unfairly from expenditures on his vice presidential
campaign. If so, the state commission said, that would be a matter
for federal regulators.
</P>
<P>
   Orman said Wednesday the 1964 decision was an effort by three
cohorts of former Democratic National Chairman John M. Bailey to
''clear the decks'' for Dodd to get the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ''Here we are 36 years later. We don't operate under the Bailey
machine rules,'' Orman said.
</P>
<P>
   Orman said he would wait to see the formal response from the
elections commission and Secretary of the State Susan Bysiewicz
before deciding whether to pursue the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the Senate race Wednesday, Lieberman said, ''The
U.S. Senate seat is too important to fill on the run. I am going to
stay on the ballot.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides its effect on presidential politics, Lieberman's Senate
race has implications for the balance of power in Congress. If
Lieberman were elected to both jobs and resigned from the Senate,
it would fall to Republican Gov. John G. Rowland to appoint a
replacement who would serve until the next statewide election in
2002. Rowland has said he will appoint a Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, who has a large lead over Republican Philip Giordano
in recent polls, could drop out of the Senate race as late as Oct.
27 and still be replaced by a Democratic Party nominee.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-06-00 2019 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000906.0155 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> White Sox Eldred Hasn't Decided  </HEADLINE>
By NANCY ARMOUR
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Despite a stress fracture in his pitching arm,
Cal Eldred isn't ready to say his season is over.
</P>
<P>
   Tests showed the Chicago White Sox right-hander has a stress
fracture just below his right elbow. He said Wednesday he wants to
consult with doctors some more before deciding what to do next.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can't really tell you what we're going to do,'' he said.
''There's nothing really final. We're waiting to see what our
options are and we'll go from there.''
</P>
<P>
   Eldred plans to meet with doctors Thursday, and general manager
Ron Schueler said he hopes to announce a decision before Thursday
night's game. While Schueler said it's possible Eldred could pitch
again this year, he wasn't exactly optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not going to rule it out yet,'' Schueler said. ''I'd be
thrilled if he did come back. But I'm not going to count on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Eldred has been on the disabled list since July 17 because of
nerve problems in his right elbow. It's the sixth trip to the DL in
five years for Eldred, who had ligament replacement surgery in
1995.
</P>
<P>
   His rehabilitation was going well -- so well, in fact, that
manager Jerry Manuel hoped he'd pitch this Friday against
Cleveland. But during his second rehab start Sunday at Triple-A
Charlotte, the pain returned and Eldred pulled himself out after
two innings.
</P>
<P>
   He went through a battery of tests Tuesday, and results showed
the stress fracture. The fracture isn't related to the nerve
problems. Eldred said he had a similar injury in 1998 and showed
symptoms of another one last year.
</P>
<P>
   The fractures eventually heal, but it takes time. With the
playoffs beginning in about three weeks, that's something neither
Eldred nor the White Sox have.
</P>
<P>
   ''To lose a guy like that our of your rotation, at this time of
year, it's difficult to overcome,'' Manuel said. ''He means a lot
more to us than just a guy that came out of spring training as a
fifth starter. He not only became one of the horses, he emerged as
one of the clubhouse leaders.''
</P>
<P>
   Eldred showed the same form early on that he had when he was the
Milwaukee Brewers' ace from 1992-94. He went 10-2, throwing two
complete games and a shutout. He was the AL Player of the Month in
June.
</P>
<P>
   His performance was one of the keys in Chicago's fast start, and
the White Sox have struggled without him.
</P>
<P>
   ''It hasn't been easy the last month and a half,'' Eldred said.
''I feel bad. I feel, in a way, that I've let the team down.''
</P>
<P>
   The timing hasn't exactly been good from a personal standpoint,
either. Eldred is a free agent after this season, and he hasn't
talked to the White Sox about next year.
</P>
<P>
   Schueler said last month he wasn't going to negotiate with
anyone until after the season to avoid distractions.
</P>
<P>
   ''When there's no one there to pay the bills next year, that's
not very attractive,'' said Eldred, 32. ''But it's part of the game
and you have to deal with it.''
</P>
<P>
   And Eldred does plan to be back next season. Asked if the latest
injury made him wonder if it was time to retire, a horrified look
crossed his face.
</P>
<P>
   ''Don't say that,'' he said. ''When I'm healthy, I think this
year proved I can pitch. And that's a whole lot of fun.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-06-00 2019 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000906.0156 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Broncos' Gary Stunned by Injury  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN MOSSMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER (AP) -- Olandis Gary has listened to the doctors and seen
the X-rays. He still can't quite believe it.
</P>
<P>
   Despite feeling something ''give'' in his right knee during the
third quarter of Monday night's 41-36 loss to St. Louis, the Denver
Broncos running back continued to play, and even ripped off gains
of 25 and 13 yards in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Because of looseness in the joint, Gary underwent an MRI exam
that was termed precautionary on Tuesday morning. The results,
however, stunned him and his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   He had completely torn the anterior cruciate ligament in his
knee and will require season-ending reconstructive surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was shocking because even after the game, I didn't have any
ill effects with my knee,'' Gary said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''I thought it was just going to be a precautionary thing with
the MRI, and then coming in and them telling me I tore my ACL. ...
It was a terrible thing, a tough pill to swallow. It's still kind
of tough to deal with.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary, whose 1,159 yards rushing last season in relief of the
injured Terrell Davis figured to make him a valuable backup to
Davis this season, walked without a limp Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's like I told coach, I still feel like I can play and give
Atlanta all they want this weekend,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gary believes he was injured while pass blocking, but didn't
think it was serious.
</P>
<P>
   ''I really didn't,'' he said. ''I came out for a second and the
docs looked at it. They gave me a little test and I ran around a
little bit and passed the test. Then I went back out there in the
third and continued to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary, assuming the rushing duties after Davis sprained his left
ankle, led the team with 80 yards on 13 carries.
</P>
<P>
   He suggested he could have damaged the knee earlier, perhaps in
a preseason game.
</P>
<P>
   ''I had had problems with it before that,'' he said, ''but it
was stable. They kept giving me the tests, and it was stable.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Davis, who had reconstructive knee surgery last October,
has been helpful in preparing him for the surgery and
rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
   ''I tried to let him know what to expect as far as rehab time,''
Davis said. ''You're going to have situations where you get pretty
down about it because you're not going to see any improvement or
any progress in your rehab. I think the thing you have to maintain
is your excitement level and the belief that you can come back from
the injury.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis also said Gary probably is in ''a state of denial. You
don't want to believe it is happening. I've been there.''
</P>
<P>
   As if to prove it, Gary said he is seeking a second medical
opinion from a specialist in California.
</P>
<P>
   ''Just to make sure,'' Gary said. ''It's 99 percent, but it's
that 1 percent. We'll just see what they say, and we pretty much
know what they're going to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Mike Shanahan said the Broncos encourage any player to
seek a second opinion. But he added, ''When four radiologists look
at it (MRI) and they say it's a tear and the doctors look at it and
they say it's a tear... Believe me, I asked 15 times, 'Are you sure
it's a tear?' Usually they go the other direction and say, 'Let's
look at it one more time.' But, unfortunately, those MRIs don't lie
very often.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-06-00 2020 </TRAILER>
