<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 20:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cardinals' Rice OKs Deal, Vanishes  </HEADLINE>
By MEL REISNER
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. (AP) -- Holdout defensive end Simeon Rice showed up
unannounced at the Arizona Cardinals' practice facility Wednesday,
agreed to a $4.25 million, one-year tender offer, took a physical
and then disappeared without consummating the deal.
</P>
<P>
   The vanishing act drew a heated reaction from general manager
Bob Ferguson.
</P>
<P>
   ''This happens too much in this business, and I'm tired of it,''
Ferguson said. ''We can't deal with these guys with kid gloves all
the time, and there comes a time when you've got to draw the line.
</P>
<P>
   ''This guy is a great football player who has a contract on the
table that is one of the top five in the league, because that's the
way it has to be with a franchise designation. That's there. I
don't know what else has to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson acknowledged telling Rice in no uncertain terms about
his obligation to the team, but denied causing Rice to change his
mind.
</P>
<P>
   Rice, a possible antidote to Arizona's dismal pass rush, spoke
with Ferguson for about five minutes in the morning. His visit was
unexpected, so the team had to scramble to line up a doctor for the
mandatory physical.
</P>
<P>
   Rice rode to and from the physical with an assistant trainer,
but instead of returning to Ferguson's office after they arrived
back at the team headquarters, he got into his car and drove away.
</P>
<P>
   Before the physical, Rice declined to speak with reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he had signed, he glowered and shot back, ''No.''
</P>
<P>
   Last winter, Rice characterized Phoenix as the ''armpit of the
world'' while fighting his designation as Arizona's franchise
player.
</P>
<P>
   But Ferguson said there were no recriminations during the
discussion. He asked Rice to consider the effect of his actions on
the team, which had no sacks and put little pressure on New York
Giants quarterback Kerry Collins during the season-opening 21-16
loss Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ''When are we going to stop playing games and play football?''
Ferguson asked. ''We aren't playing it very well right now, but
we've got a team that can.''
</P>
<P>
   Rice had 44 sacks in his first four NFL seasons -- more than the
career total for Arizona's starting front four last week.
</P>
<P>
   He tied the NFL rookie record with 12&AMP;frac12; sacks in 1996 and set the
Cardinals franchise record last year with 16&AMP;frac12;.
</P>
<P>
   ''Exceptional quickness to rush the passer -- that's probably the
No. 1 asset that Simeon has,'' coach Vince Tobin said. ''He's an
unbelievably coordinated athlete that makes things happen as far as
rushing.''
</P>
<P>
   But Tobin, speaking in advance of Rice's disappearance after
learning during practice about his visit, also said experience had
taught him not to count on a player until he suited up.
</P>
<P>
   ''We prepared without Simeon,'' Tobin said. ''We planned all
along if he wasn't in, because we couldn't do anything about it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-06-00 2040 </TRAILER>
