<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 21:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bengals' Smith Eager to Play  </HEADLINE>
By JOE KAY
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI (AP) -- Donovan McNabb led a drubbing of Dallas.
Daunte Culpepper ran for three touchdowns. Cade McNown threw for
two touchdowns and ran for another. Tim Couch kept Cleveland close
for a half.
</P>
<P>
   What was Akili Smith doing while the rest of the quarterback
class of '99 was strutting its stuff? Watching on television,
feeling left out.
</P>
<P>
   The Cincinnati Bengals opened the season with a bye, making
Smith a spectator for the first week. He didn't like it.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm real anxious to get out there,'' Smith said Wednesday. ''I
was sitting back and watching the stats of all the younger
quarterbacks and everybody had a pretty good opening day. I want to
go out there and kind of do the same things they did.''
</P>
<P>
   Couch wasn't bad, going 19-of-27 with a touchdown in the Browns'
27-7 loss to Jacksonville. Couch and the Browns will visit Sunday
for the first regular-season game at Paul Brown Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   It will be Smith's most important game since Oct. 10 last year,
when he made his first NFL start in Cleveland, led a last-minute
touchdown drive for an 18-17 win and pounded his chest at the
Browns' bench, rekindling a rivalry.
</P>
<P>
   This time, he's starting the first meaningful game in the new
stadium that's supposed to mark the beginning of a new era for the
NFL's most forlorn team.
</P>
<P>
   ''I know this game is about teammates and that stuff, but I know
there's a lot of pressure on me to get it done and I'm ready to
take it on,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Publicly, Smith is putting less emphasis on his second game
against Cleveland, the team that chose Couch instead of him for the
No. 1 overall pick last year. He wouldn't talk about his
chest-thumping celebration or his old grudge.
</P>
<P>
   ''What's said was last year and I'm going to move on,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   First, he's got to make up some ground. Smith noticed that the
other first-round quarterbacks from '99 got a lot of media
attention in the preseason, while he and the Bengals were glossed
over.
</P>
<P>
   Even though there's a good reason for it -- the Bengals had the
NFL's worst record in the 1990s -- Smith felt overlooked.
</P>
<P>
   ''Yeah, I watched all those shows,'' he said. ''It's nothing I
haven't been dealing with my whole career. I just haven't had a
chance to prove myself yet. I'll get my chance on Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bengals decided to start Smith against Cleveland last season
because it represented his best chance to make a successful debut --
playing a winless expansion team.
</P>
<P>
   The game against Cleveland on Sunday also represents a good
chance to look good. Even though the Browns' defense had four sacks
and was more resilient against Jacksonville, it allowed Mark
Brunell to throw for 301 yards and lead drives of 15, 12, 10 and 17
plays.
</P>
<P>
   Smith will get to attack it more directly this year.
</P>
<P>
   ''In his first game last year against Cleveland, he was still
kind of getting the concept of playing quarterback in this
league,'' offensive tackle Willie Anderson said. ''The game plan is
going to be bigger than it was last year for him. It will give him
a lot more shots to get the ball down the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith has been studying film of the Browns' defense since
preseason. He was so eager to get acquainted with the game plan
that he stuck around Paul Brown Stadium until late Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was here last night until like 9 o'clock watching film and
waiting for us to give him the game plan,'' coach Bruce Coslet
said. ''He just stayed and had dinner with us.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's doing everything he can to be good and it started in
February, so I have nothing but praise for him. He's earned it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-06-00 2106 </TRAILER>
