<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 21:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Texas Ends Year With Surplus  </HEADLINE>
By NATALIE GOTT
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- Texas ended its fiscal year with $45
million more in the bank than July estimates showed, pushing its
surplus to $1.45 billion, the state comptroller said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The state's budget became a presidential campaign issue in July
when a legislative report projected that $610 million in cost
overruns in some programs would cut into the surplus.
</P>
<P>
   Some Texas Democrats blamed the overruns on a $1.7 billion tax
cut that Gov. George W. Bush, the Republican presidential nominee,
advocated and signed into law in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Legislators said the newly announced surplus would more than
cover any excess spending. The state ended its fiscal year on Aug.
31.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Comptroller Carole Keeton Rylander, a Republican, also
said the state will put about $103 million -- $55 million more than
originally estimated -- into its rainy day fund because of
additional revenues collected from natural gas severance taxes.
</P>
<P>
   In July, the chairman of the Senate Finance Committee said the
state might have to use about $610 million of the budget surplus,
which amounted to more than $1 billion at the time, to keep the
overall $98.2 billion budget out of the red.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers blamed the overruns on higher Medicaid prescription
drug costs, a larger prison population in county jails and bad
budget assumptions by two state agencies.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Mario Gallegos, a Houston Democrat who had accused
the state of cooking the budget figures to fatten the surplus, said
Wednesday he would not believe a surplus exists until he knew how
much those departments faced in shortfalls.
</P>
<P>
   ''Before we start the balloons and the confetti on the surplus,
I'd like to know what kind of cut we are going to take,'' Gallegos
said.
</P>
<P>
   On a July campaign visit to San Antonio, Democratic presidential
candidate Al Gore said the budget shortfall demonstrated that
Bush's economic proposals would return the country to deficit
spending and raise its debt.
</P>
<P>
   ''This confirms what the governor has been saying -- that he has
worked with the Texas Legislature to be fiscally responsible and as
a result, the state is ending the fiscal year with a sizable
surplus,'' Linda Edwards, a gubernatorial spokeswoman for Bush,
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign declined to comment Wednesday, saying it
needed more details.
</P>
<P>
   In her report, Rylander said the state ended the fiscal year
with $3.8 billion in the general fund, which includes funds
dedicated to various special purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, state spending was lower than originally estimated by
state budget analysts, she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-06-00 2106 </TRAILER>
