<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 21:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Official: Sailors Died Immediately  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- A deputy prime minister said Wednesday that there
had never been any contact with the 118 Russian sailors aboard the
Kursk nuclear submarine after it sank Aug. 12, and they were
probably all killed instantly.
</P>
<P>
   Navy officials had said several times that they heard tapping
from inside the submarine the first few days after it went down
during exercises in the Barents Sea, indicating some crew members
were alive. That encouraged rescuers who spent a week trying to
open the vessel.
</P>
<P>
   But Deputy Prime Minister Ilya Klebanov, who leads the
government commission handling the disaster, said Wednesday,
''Almost certainly, once it was on the sea floor, no one was left
alive.''
</P>
<P>
   The reports of tapping ''turned out to be mistaken ... because
of a mistaken analysis,'' he said in remarks aired on Russia's
television networks. He did not elaborate. Other, lower-ranking
officials had acknowledged before that there had been no pounding.
</P>
<P>
   When divers finally made it inside nine days after the
explosions that disabled the vessel, they found a flooded ship and
no survivors.
</P>
<P>
   The navy was widely criticized for bungling the rescue effort
and being slow to accept foreign help. Throughout the tense rescue
effort, navy and government officials -- including Klebanov -- gave
contradictory and confusing accounts of what was going on.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-06-00 2115 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000906.0175 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 21:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Heat Wave Can't Stop Texas Football  </HEADLINE>
By JIM VERTUNO
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- The grass is brown and brittle. At 112
degrees, it's so hot even the dust seems reluctant to move.
</P>
<P>
   If this were Hollywood, tumbleweeds would be blowing through the
end zone.
</P>
<P>
   But this is Texas, where high school football is king, and
nothing like a few hot days, or even a lot of them, are enough to
stop the game.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's never too hot to play football,'' Connally High School
quarterback Deron Ellis says.
</P>
<P>
   With the late afternoon sun pounding his black helmet, Ellis
bends over for a drink of water from a sideline cooler. He blinks
furiously to keep his eyes moist in the face of a fierce wind that
feels like blast of air from an oven.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is bad. We usually get a cool breeze to help. This is
more like a hot smack in your face,'' Ellis says.
</P>
<P>
   A combination of drought, low humidity and a stationary dome of
hot air sent temperatures in Austin soaring to a record 112 degrees
Tuesday, beating the previous high of 110 set a day earlier. While
Ellis and his teammates were running around a football field, it
was cooler in Death Valley, Calif., which topped out at 101.
</P>
<P>
   As of Wednesday, the temperature in Austin has topped 100
degrees on 37 days this year. The thermometer has been in triple
digits for 58 days in Del Rio, 45 days in College Station, 44 days
in Dallas-Fort Worth, and 21 days in San Antonio. Wednesday's highs
hit the 90s as a weak cool front pushed through the state, but Del
Rio still managed to hit 110.
</P>
<P>
   ''You look at the five-day forecast and everything is the
100s,'' Connally coach Matt Monzingo said. ''It's ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, a break may be on the horizon. Temperatures across the
state are expected to cool off into the high 90s by Thursday and
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The heat has forced high school coaches and officials to make
adjustments to protect their players against heat exhaustion or
heat stroke.
</P>
<P>
   Some schools have pushed back starting times for night games and
even canceled some junior varsity and middle school games.
</P>
<P>
   Others have shortened practice times or forgone the use of
shoulder pads during the heat wave.
</P>
<P>
   ''I let the kids know anytime they feel weak or lightheaded,
they need to take a little break,'' Dallas Samuell coach Steve
Pierce said. ''We provide ice water and sport drinks and push them
to hydrate themselves as much as possible before they even go
out.''
</P>
<P>
   At Connally, about a dozen water coolers line the practice
field. Players drape towels soaked in ice water over their heads.
The team takes about four or five water breaks during the two-hour
practice but each player is allowed to get a drink when he wants
one.
</P>
<P>
   The coaching staff encourages players to drink a lot of water
during the day before practice even starts.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've only had one kid drop out of practice because he felt he
was dehydrated,'' Monzingo said. ''The other staff in school have
been good about reminding the kids to drink a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, high levels of activity in extreme temperatures can be
dangerous, says Dr. Mark Hutchens, director of athletic medicine at
the University of Texas. ''Anything over a hundred and you're
pretty much in danger level.''
</P>
<P>
   Generally, heat exhaustion is caused by loss of body fluids and
important salts. If untreated, heat exhaustion can lead to heat
stroke, a medical emergency.
</P>
<P>
   Symptoms of heat exhaustion include headache, nausea, fatigue,
dizziness or lightheadedness. Victims may faint.
</P>
<P>
   Heat stroke symptoms include headache, flushed skin, rapid
pulse, incoherent speech and disorientation. Victims could lose
consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   Garland coach Joe Martin said the heat is mentally taxing as
well.
</P>
<P>
   ''We try to put it out of our minds and not talk about how hot
it is,'' Martin said. ''The other day, when it was 112 or whatever
it was, the kids were lining up to start practice talking about how
cool it was.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you stand out by our door at the field house, you won't
hear too many say it's hot, but you'll hear, 'Boy, it's cool out
here,' and everybody will laugh,'' Martin said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
