<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 21:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2nd Athlete Kicked off Canada Team  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO (AP) -- A second athlete in as many days has been kicked
off the Canadian Olympic team following a positive drug test.
</P>
<P>
   A director for the Canadian Centre for Ethics in Sport, which
performed the test, said Wednesday that equestrian rider Eric
Lamaze has tested positive for cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, hammer thrower Robin Lyons was removed from the team
after testing positive for an anabolic steroid.
</P>
<P>
   She has appealed the results of the tests taken last month at
the Canadian Olympic trials where she set a meet record with a toss
of 205 feet, 8 inches.
</P>
<P>
   Athletics Canada helped Lyons protest the infraction to the CCES
in hopes of clearing her in time to compete in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   CCES director Casey Wade said the Centre would not comment
further on Lamaze's situation.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the Canadian Equestrian Federation said they
were expecting test results from CCES on Thursday and would not
confirm the report.
</P>
<P>
   ''We can't say anything,'' federation media relations
co-ordinator Jennifer Ward said.
</P>
<P>
   She said she is aware that ''there is something under review''
but added they ''do not know what or with which athlete.''
</P>
<P>
   Ward said Lamaze has withdrawn from this weekend's Masters
competition at Spruce Meadows in Calgary and the Canadian team will
be replacing him on the Nation's Cup team Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   He was to compete in the team and individual jumping events in
Sydney. Lamaze, riding Millcreek Raphael, was selected in July to
the Olympic team.
</P>
<P>
   Terrance Millar, manager of the equestrian team, called news of
the positive test ''devastating'' and ''sad.''
</P>
<P>
   ''He's had a brilliant year,'' Millar said. ''Here's a guy who's
at the very top of his game.''
</P>
<P>
   The loss is expected to hurt the team's chances in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was maybe the top horse-rider combination,'' Millar said.
''He was a lynch pin on our team.''
</P>
<P>
   Lamaze, a former Canadian equestrian champion, also tested
positive in 1996 and was suspended from competition for four years.
His suspension was commuted to seven months after he appealed on
the grounds he took cocaine four times in three months before the
1996 Olympic trials for personal use rather than to gain any
competitive edge.
</P>
<P>
   Lamaze could not be reached at his Torrey Pines Stables in
Stromberg, Ontario, for comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
