<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressLawrence Fellows:
<TEXT>
<P>
   WESTPORT, Conn. (AP) -- Lawrence Fellows, a former foreign
correspondent and chief Connecticut correspondent for The New York
Times, died Saturday of a heart attack. He was 75.
</P>
<P>
   Fellows began his career with the Times as a general assignment
reporter in Manhattan and as a correspondent at the United Nations
from 1953 to 1978. He went overseas from 1959 to 1972, based in
Jerusalem; London; Nairobi, Kenya; and Bonn, Germany. He then spent
six years as chief correspondent in Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   As a correspondent based in Israel from 1959 to 1962, Fellows
covered the trial of Adolf Eichmann and violence in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
   While in London from 1962 to 1965 he covered the scandal
surrounding the war minister, John Profumo, who resigned after
lying about his affair with a call girl. Fellows then returned to
Cyprus to cover fighting between Greeks and Turks.
</P>
<P>
   In 1968, the Times published a long dispatch from Sudan in which
Fellows reported on an untold number of casualties in a six-year
revolt.
</P>
<P>
   In 1972, Fellows reported on the kidnapping and murder of
Israeli athletes by Arab terrorists at the Munich Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his wife, he is survived by two daughters and
three grandchildren.
R.H. Harris:
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- R.H. Harris, a gospel pioneer and the last
surviving member of the original Soul Stirrers, died Sunday. He was
84.
</P>
<P>
   Gospel expert Anthony Heilbut called Harris, whose Chicago-based
band was inducted into the Rock 'n' Roll Hall of Fame in 1989,
''the most influential figure in soul music.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris joined the group in 1931, two months before the band
changed its name to the Five Soul Stirrers.
</P>
<P>
   Using falsetto while singing a high second lead, Harris enabled
four-part harmonies and a back beat that musical historians say
became a model for soul and rhythm and blues and quartets that
performed with Duke Ellington and Cab Calloway.
George ''Moose'' Musso:
</P>
<P>
   EDWARDSVILLE, Ill. (AP) -- George ''Moose'' Musso, a lineman who
played on four Chicago Bears championship teams and was inducted
into the Pro Football Hall of Fame, died Tuesday. He was 90.
</P>
<P>
   Musso was a Bear from 1933 to 1944 and was inducted to the Hall
of Fame in 1982. He played in seven NFL championship games under
Bears founder and coach George Halas, including the 72-0 thrashing
of the Washington Redskins in 1940.
</P>
<P>
   While in college, he played against two future presidents,
Ronald Reagan at Eureka and Gerald Ford at Michigan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
