<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Wednesday, Sept. 6, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Pushes Accord at Summit
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- President Clinton labored today without apparent success to
impress Israeli and Palestinian leaders with a sense of urgency as their
deadline for a settlement loomed only a week away. White House spokesman Joe
Lockhart made no claim of progress after Clinton's back-to-back meetings with
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat. Clinton
had faced long odds in trying to relaunch his flagging peace process by meeting
with the Mideast leaders on the fringes of the U.N. Millennium Summit.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Appeals Court Sets Hearing for Lee
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) -- A federal appeals court agreed today to set a
hearing for Wen Ho Lee's lawyers to argue that the accused nuclear scientist
should be released from jail. The Denver-based 10th U.S. Circuit Appeals Court,
which last week superseded a bail-release order signed by a federal judge in
Albuquerque, set the hearing for Monday in Denver. The hearing will be closed to
the public for security reasons. The defense had petitioned the court to release
the fired Los Alamos scientist, who has been jailed since Dec. 10 while he
awaits trial.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Western Fire Crews Heading Home
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   HELENA, Mont. (AP) -- Firefighters are leaving Montana by the planeload as
officials begin demobilizing from the worst fire season in decades. At least 300
firefighters have returned to their homes in the southeastern and southwestern
United States, and more were expected to head to other fires across the country
by the end of the week. ''The pendulum has now swung the other way,'' said Bill
Cowin, incident commander for a fire camp that has been set up in Missoula to
handle demobilization.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Official: Kursk Crew Died Instantly
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- Deputy Prime Minister Ilya Klebanov said Wednesday that there
had never been any contact with the 118 Russian sailors aboard the Kursk nuclear
submarine after it sank Aug. 12, and they were probably all killed instantly.
Navy officials had said several times that they heard tapping from inside the
submarine the first few days after it went down during exercises in the Barents
Sea, indicating some crew members were alive. That encouraged rescuers who spent
a week trying to open the vessel.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Judge: MP3.com Broke Law, Is Liable
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A judge ruled today that MP3.com willfully violated
copyrights of music companies and awarded Universal Music Group $25,000 per CD,
a penalty that could reach as much as $250 million. U.S. District Judge Jed S.
Rakoff said it was necessary to send a message to the Internet community to
deter copyright infringement.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
French Get Tough With Striking Truckers
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PARIS (AP) -- French truckers stepped up a blockade of the nation's fuel
depots Wednesday as the government said it would make no more concessions and
demanded an end to protests that have forced some gas stations to run dry. Prime
Minister Lionel Jospin took a tough line with the truckers, saying their strike
had ''inflicted a major handicap on the French economy,'' and the government had
reached its limit. France has the second highest fuel prices in the European
Union after Britain.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Legislators Look at Privacy Bills
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Shocked at how simple it is for law enforcement to get
court permission to see the telephone numbers people dial, legislators today
discussed new bills aimed at tightening surveillance laws and put final touches
on a plan to address workplace privacy. The proposed wiretap bill would make it
more difficult for prosecutors to obtain court permission to monitor the
telephone numbers dialed by a suspect. The bill would require the same standard
of evidence now needed for permission to tap a telephone conversation. Two very
similar bills, the Electronic Communications Privacy Act and the Digital Privacy
Act, spawned from citizen concerns about their privacy online.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Fall in Early Trading
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks fell early Thursday after technology shares
slipped in Wall Street trading, as the Nikkei shed 124.29 points, or 0.76
percent, to 16,275.58 in the first 30 minutes of trading. The dollar was higher
against the yen. On Wednesday, the average closed down 52.40 points, or 0.32
percent. In New York, the Nasdaq composite index lost 129.84 to 4,013.34 at
Wednesday's close. The Dow Jones industrial average rose 50.03 points to close
at 11,310.64.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Angels Beat Tigers, 1-0
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   DETROIT (AP) -- Scott Schoeneweis shut out Detroit on two singles for eight
innings and the Anaheim Angels stopped a season-high six-game losing streak,
defeating the Tigers 1-0 tonight.
AP NewsBrief by GRETCHEN SCHWARTZ 
</P>
