<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 22:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NYC activist's body identified in Indonesia  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - The body of a Queens-based lawyer and activist
was identified Wednesday among five corpses found in Indonesia,
where he had campaigned for peace in his violence-ridden home
province, activists said.
</P>
<P>
   Jafar Siddiq Hamzah, 35, was definitively identified by an
autopsy in which doctors found evidence of a colon operation he
underwent in New York in 1998, said Sidney Jones, Asia director for
Human Rights Watch.
</P>
<P>
   Hamzah's family, who live on the Indonesian island of Sumatra,
had said earlier that they did not recognize him among five badly
decomposed bodies found in a ravine about 40 miles southwest of the
North Sumatran capital of Medan.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors were uncertain whether Hamzah, 35, was stabbed or shot,
Jones said. His body was expected to be released to his family on
Thursday, she added.
</P>
<P>
   Hamzah moved to New York several years ago and founded the
International Forum on Aceh to campaign for peace in Aceh, a
province on the northern tip of Sumatra where government troops
have been battling separatist rebels for the past 25 years. He was
a native of Aceh and had worked on human rights issues there since
the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Hamzah actively campaigned against Indonesian military violence
and had reported receiving death threats in the days before his
disappearance. He was last seen Aug. 5 in Medan, Indonesia's
third-largest city.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said his death fit a long-standing pattern of military
abuse connected to the conflict in Aceh. Four other Aceh activists
have been found dead this year, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The thing there's still an element of uncertainty about is who
did it,'' she said. ''Is this something that's being directed by a
central authority? Is it some unit of the military that's just
decided to take things into its own hands? There's even a slight
possibility that it's a faction of the guerrilla movement. We just
don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Activists have called for a full, civilian investigation of the
deaths.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
