<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 200 U.N. diplomats no easy picture  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) - It took three other photographers, 200
selected escorts and a crash course in diplomacy, but Terry Deglau
says he caught the United Nations Millennium moment.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. hired Deglau, who is Eastman Kodak Co.'s manager of
photographic trade relations, to direct the official summit photo
shoot Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Deglau's work began well before Wednesday. He had to take
political considerations under advisement in deciding where each
official would stand.
</P>
<P>
   There wasn't much room. The U.N. vetoed an outdoor shot for
security reasons so Deglau had to settle on the U.N.'s trustees'
room, which was too small for all the leaders' entourages.
</P>
<P>
   So he had to work with UN officials to arrange an escort for
each official - one who spoke the native language of the dignitary.
</P>
<P>
   Before joining Kodak 15 years ago, Deglau ran his own portrait
studio in Latrobe, Pa. for 25 years and was Arnold Palmer's
photographer for 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   The shoot is great publicity for Kodak, Deglau said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a big deal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
