<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 22:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Athletics 6, Red Sox 4  </HEADLINE>
By HOWARD ULMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON (AP) -- Mike Mulder, struggling through a tough rookie
season, pitched six strong innings and slumping Matt Stairs homered
as the Oakland Athletics beat the Boston Red Sox 6-4 Wednesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Oakland won for the fourth time in five games and moved 1&AMP;frac12; games
behind AL West leader Seattle, which lost to Toronto 7-3.
</P>
<P>
   The A's and Red Sox trail AL wild card leader Cleveland by three
games.
</P>
<P>
   Mulder (8-10) was 2-8 in his previous 11 starts and entered the
night with opponents hitting .318 against him, the highest in the
AL.
</P>
<P>
   But on Wednesday, he gave up just two runs on five hits and left
with a 4-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Stairs was at the opposite extreme. The .220 average he took
into the game was the lowest in the majors among regulars. He
followed Oakland's three-run second inning by hitting Rolando
Arrojo's first pitch of the third for his 20th homer of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Adam Piatt's RBI single off Rod Beck gave Oakland a 5-2 lead in
the eighth before Boston scored twice in the bottom of the inning
on Dante Bichette's RBI single and Troy O'Leary's grounder. But
Doug Jones struck out Jason Varitek, ending the rally, and Stairs
hit a sacrifice for Oakland in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Mecir pitched the last two innings for his fifth save in 11
chances.
</P>
<P>
   Mulder allowed two singles in the first three innings, then gave
up solo homers to Bichette in the fourth and Jose Offerman in the
sixth. Bichette's first homer since being traded from Cincinnati on
Aug. 31 made it 4-1, while Offerman's sixth of the year cut the
lead to 4-2.
</P>
<P>
   Arrojo (4-2) lasted three innings, his shortest outing in eight
starts since being traded by Colorado on July 27.
</P>
<P>
   He got out of the first without allowing a run despite giving up
two singles. In the second, he allowed three runs on four hits.
Singles by Piatt and Sal Fasano put runners at first and third with
two outs. Terrence Long then singled in one run and Randy Velarde
doubled in two.
</P>
<P>
   Varitek nearly tied the game at 4 with a homer after O'Leary
started the seventh with a single. But center fielder Long reached
over the fence in front of Boston's bullpen to make the catch. Then
Brian Daubach struck out as the first of four pinch-hitters in the
inning.
</P>
<P>
   The next one, Midre Cummings, walked. Lefty Trot Nixon then was
announced as a hitter for Darren Lewis, lefty Mike Magnante came in
to pitch and righty Bernard Gilkey batted for Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   All those maneuvers failed as Gilkey hit the first pitch back to
Magnante for the inning-ending out.
Notes: The Red Sox recalled RHP Rick Croushore from Triple-A
Pawtucket. ... The A's have 11 homers in the last five games. ...
Arrojo was 4-0 in his previous five starts and pitched well in his
first loss with the Red Sox when he gave up three hits in Oakland's
5-2 win July 30. Two of them were homers by Fasano, including a
grand slam. ... Mulder entered the game as one of the AL's worst
starters, ranking first in most hits and runners allowed per nine
innings and in highest batting average allowed. ... Boston
relievers Rheal Cormier and Tim Wakefield followed Arrojo with four
hitless innings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-06-00 2233 </TRAILER>
