<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dodgers' Perez Out for Season  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Carlos Perez, who heard derisive cheering by
Los Angeles Dodgers fans when he left Tuesday night's game with an
injured left shoulder, is done for the season and is expected to
undergo arthroscopic surgery next week.
</P>
<P>
   An MRI and CAT scan on Wednesday detected a bone spur that had
broken loose from the back of the shoulder capsule. Perez won't be
able to throw for 2-3 months, but should be ready for the start of
spring training, according to team physician Dr. Frank Jobe.
</P>
<P>
   ''The fact that it was bothering him before last night, and he
was hiding it, didn't make matters any easier,'' manager Davey
Johnson said Wednesday. ''But he's a tough guy. He's going to want
to go out there and pitch. He never goes for treatment.''
</P>
<P>
   Perez, 1-6 with a 6.43 ERA in his last 15 starts, has been a
lightening rod this season for frustrated Dodgers fans who expected
more from a team with an $88 million, opening-day payroll. Perez is
owed $7.5 million next season, the final year of a three-year deal
worth $15.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   When he left the mound after throwing his 96th pitch to
Pittsburgh's Brian Giles, Perez had gone only 3 2-3 innings and
would eventually be charged with six runs and 10 hits. Overall, he
is 5-8 with a 5.56 ERA and 25 home runs allowed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
