<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 23:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Outside UN Summit, baby stands against slavery with Sudanese mother </HEADLINE>
By VERENA DOBNIK
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - One small, silent face spoke louder than the
competing lineup of noisy protests near the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Majak Bak, a 14-month-old boy, stood outside the Sudanese
Mission on Wednesday with his young mother, who says she was a
slave herding goats in Sudan when her master tried to rape her
three years ago. She escaped, to her new life in Buffalo, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   When Abuk Bak was 12, she says, Muslim horsemen galloped into
her Catholic village, ''burned our houses, and killed many people -
including my grandfather, right there in front of my eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   It was 1987 - the beginning of her decade of slavery, says Bak.
</P>
<P>
   As the U.N. Millennium Summit began, about 60 protesters outside
the mission on Third Avenue demanded the arrest of Sudanese
President Omar el-Bashir for allegedly directing his forces to
create slaves. As many as 100,000 Sudanese are kept in slavery,
according to Charles Jacobs, president of the Boston-based American
Anti-Slavery Group, which organized the protest.
</P>
<P>
   Through a translator, Bak said in Arabic: ''I am dismayed to
learn that el-Bashir is walking the streets of New York City, a
great city of freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sudanese government has repeatedly denied it engages in
slavery, though el-Bashir said in January that he would continue to
fight a ''holy war'' on behalf of Islam.
</P>
<P>
   Bak, now 25, offered her years of bloodied memories as a member
of Sudan's Dinka tribe ''on behalf of those who were not lucky
enough to escape,'' she says. ''Some have been killed. Others
suffer in silence. ... They believe that no one loves them.''
</P>
<P>
   In the raid on Achuru, her village in southern Sudan, she said,
many men were fatally shot, including her grandfather and male
cousins. The attacking Muslim militiamen sold the women and
children into slavery as domestics and shepherds, Jacobs says, and
many of the women were genitally mutilated.
</P>
<P>
   Isolated from her relatives, Bak says, ''I was like an animal,''
with her nomadic master ordering her whipped or stoned if she lost
one of his goats in the Sudanese countryside.
</P>
<P>
   ''I escaped one night after he tried to rape me,'' she told The
Associated Press. ''I resisted, and he cut my leg with a knife. I
slipped away, got on a goat truck and hid among the animals.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, she ended up in the Sudanese capital Khartoum and
met a fellow Dinka named Majak. In 1998, he arranged for her to
marry his brother in Cairo. Bak was resettled in America by the
United Nations six months ago with her husband, now a 27-year-old
metalworker in Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   Their son Majak is named after the man who saved her - now her
brother-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday afternoon, the young mother stepped into St.
Patrick's Cathedral on Fifth Avenue with her child. As he sucked on
the milk from his baby bottle, the boy's eyes lit up at the
brightly illuminated stained glass.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm happy, because he is free,'' his mother said in broken
English.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs says the United States and other Western nations are
doing little to stop the abuse in Sudan and Mauritania, where he
says as many as 1 million people are enslaved, including Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   ''Slavery is the stepchild of the human rights movement,'' says
Jacobs, who quit his work as an international management consultant
with a Ph.D. in education from Harvard to form the anti-slavery
group.
</P>
<P>
   He is urging those who have money invested in oil-rich Sudan to
divest.
</P>
<P>
   About 25,000 Sudanese slaves have been freed - bought at about
$50 each - with the help of another organization, Christian
Solidarity International, based in Zurich, Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   A group affiliated with the nondenominational Highland Church in
the New York borough of Queens is funding a new orphanage in Sudan
and mobile medical units to replace destroyed hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   ''They have no insulin, and no incubators,'' says Dana Antel, a
group member who visited Sudan recently. Many hospitals were
decimated in the civil war that has taken millions of lives since
1983, when fighting erupted between rebels from Sudan's Christian
and animist south and government troops from the Arab and Muslim
north.
</P>
<P>
   A memorial service is planned Saturday in front of the United
Nations for the Sudanese casualties. On Wednesday, a leaflet was
passed out with a photo showing a young man who was critically
burned, with the slogan: ''Christians Slaughtered for their
Faith.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-06-00 2301 </TRAILER>
