<HEADLINE> U.S. Women's 400 Relay Team Set  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRISBANE, Australia (AP) -- Barring any unforeseen circumstances,
the U.S. women's 400-meter relay team for the Olympic final will
consist of Chryste Gaines, Gail Devers, Inger Miller and Marion
Jones.
</P>
<P>
   That foursome has yet to run together, but women's team coach
Karen Dennis, who was with the team's sprinters during a recent
European swing, said Thursday the plan was to run that group Sept.
30.
</P>
<P>
   Gaines, Devers, Miller and Jones were scheduled to run at
Brussels on Aug. 25, but the race was canceled.
</P>
<P>
   In the previous meet, at Monte Carlo, a team of Gaines, Devers,
Miller and Torri Edwards won in 42.15 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   After the Brussels cancellation, Miller returned home to train
and Edwards also went home because of her grandmother's death. So a
patchwork team of Gaines, Dawn Burrell, Passion Richardson and
Jones ran 42.95 at Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis said there still was plenty of time for the final four to
work together.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the four also will compete in individual events at the
games -- Jones in the 100 and 200 meters and long jump, Miller in
the 100 and 200, Devers in the 100 hurdles, and Gaines in the 100.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis said she had not yet decided about her final lineup for
the 1,600 relay, also to be run Sept. 30.
</P>
<P>
   She can choose from a group including Jones, who has said she
will attempt to win five gold medals, Jearl Miles-Clark, LaTasha
Colander-Richardson, Michelle Collins, Mikele Barber, Andrea
Anderson and Monique Hennagan.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'll wait until I see how the 400 shakes out,'' she said of
the Sept. 25 race. ''I'll see who's running the strongest.''
</P>
<P>
   Colander-Richardson, Collins and Hennagan are entered in the
400, Miles-Clark in the 800, and Anderson and Barber are part of
the relay pool.
</P>
<P>
   No matter whom she chooses for the 1,600 relay, Dennis is
confident about both relays.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think we can break some records,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Men's coach John Chaplin has not yet decided upon his relay
teams, but he is leaning toward a quartet of Jon Drummond, Bernard
Williams, Tim Montgomery and Maurice Greene for the 400, and Angelo
Taylor, Alvin Harrison, Antonio Pettigrew and Michael Johnson for
the 1,600.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
