<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 23:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Protests Abound At UN Summit  </HEADLINE>
By LUKAS I. ALPERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP)-- They were railing against China on East 35th
Street, deploring slavery in the Sudan on Third Avenue, championing
the Iranian government in exile on First Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Everywhere New Yorkers turned Wednesday, they found protesters
seizing a bit of the spotlight from the United Nations Millennium
Summit, their voices mingling with the honking of horns on
Manhattan streets.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, shopowners cooled their heels behind police barricades,
cut off from customers by tight security measures.
</P>
<P>
   ''You lose some business, but on the other hand you pick up with
the foreigners coming in to buy converters and adapters,'' said Bob
Kramer, co-owner of Kramer's Hardware, which was frequently blocked
by motorcades passing along Second Avenue and 49th Street.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-two protests were officially registered with police
Wednesday, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of Falun Gong practitioners from around the world
gathered in the morning at a park opposite the Chinese Mission to
protest a crackdown on the movement's followers that began last
year in China.
</P>
<P>
   They sat, stock still, in silent meditative protest, and
listened to statements read by practitioners who said they had been
detained and beaten in China for practicing Falun Gong. The group
then rose in unison and marched in orderly rows to the United
Nations.
</P>
<P>
   ''We really hope that (Chinese President) Jiang Zemin will stop
persecuting people who want to do this. We have no other intentions
than peaceful ones,'' said Dong Li, a computer programmer from
Mamaroneck, who has practiced Falun Gong for a year.
</P>
<P>
   The march brought the Falun Gong protesters past the Sudanese
Mission on Third Avenue, where a group of 60 protesters demanded
the arrest of Sudanese President Omar el-Bashir.
</P>
<P>
   ''Why should the president of a slaving nation be allowed to
walk free on the streets of New York?'' asked Charles Jacobs,
president of the American Anti-Slavery Group, a Boston-based
organization that tries to raise awareness of forced labor around
the world. Sudan has denied allegations that its army was enslaving
captives taken in the country's civil war.
</P>
<P>
   Upon arriving at the United Nations, Falun Gong followers
silently hunkered down into the lotus position and began
meditating, while raucous neighbors nearby on Dag Hammerskjold
Plaza protested against Iraqi President Saddam Hussein and Israeli
Prime Minister Ehud Barak.
</P>
<P>
   Later, they were all replaced by a new shift of demonstrators --
Iranians, sandwiched between Bangladeshis and anti-Castro Cubans.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is an insult to the free world that this man (Castro) is
here while the Dalai Lama was not allowed to attend'' last week's
international religious conference, said Yvonne Conde, a
Cuban-American writer who lives in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Later, about a dozen sympathizers of the Iranian National
Council of Resistance, a Paris-based group that considers itself
Iran's government in exile, sat in the middle of First Avenue near
the U.N., screaming that Iranian President Mohammad Khatami was a
terrorist.
</P>
<P>
   Police arrived shortly and arrested them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
