<DOCNO> APW20000906.0220 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 23:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Pushes for Mideast Accord  </HEADLINE>
By BARRY SCHWEID
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- President Clinton labored Wednesday without
apparent success to impress Israeli and Palestinian leaders with a
sense of urgency as their deadline for a settlement loomed only a
week away.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Joe Lockhart made no claim of progress
after Clinton's back-to-back meetings with Israeli Prime Minister
Ehud Barak and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat. The spokesman also
gave no indication what Clinton might do next in trying to relaunch
Mideast peacemaking.
</P>
<P>
   ''We did not expect today to be a breakthrough day in the
process,'' Lockhart said. ''That is true, but the process has not
broken down.''
</P>
<P>
   An Israeli official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said it
was difficult to remain optimistic but said Barak was still waiting
for an answer from Arafat to his proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Despite dimming prospects, the Clinton administration kept up
its diplomatic effort. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright went
from a dinner with the Russian foreign minister, Igor Ivanov, to
Barak's hotel for a meeting with the Israeli leader just before
midnight.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart credited the two sides with a continuing commitment to
come to terms, and he dismissed the deadline they set last year for
an accord as artificial. That deadline is next Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''While there is a chance to reach an agreement we will remain
engaged,'' Lockhart said. ''It was useful to talk to these leaders
face to face.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton had faced long odds in trying to relaunch his flagging
peace process by meeting with the Mideast leaders on the fringes of
the U.N. Millennium Summit.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he forged ahead, meeting first with Barak, for 50
minutes, at an East Side hotel, which was surrounded by throngs of
New York City police. The streets were virtually impassable, with
scores of police cars providing a further shield.
</P>
<P>
   A 90-minute meeting with Arafat followed.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat, in a speech to the Millennium Summit, gave no quarter on
Jerusalem, a key stumbling block. ''We have agreed to share the
city, eliminate barriers and borders therein, in contrast to
attempts at monopolizing it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He called the city ''the cradle of Christ and the site of
Prophet Mohammed's ascension to heaven,'' making no mention of
Jews' attachment to the city for more than 2,000 years. He said the
Palestinians had compromised on Jerusalem and urged the Israelis to
do the same.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, in turn, asked Arafat to join him in making painful
concessions for peace. ''We are at the ' and no one of us can cross
it alone,'' Barak said as Arafat listened impassively, his face
grim.
</P>
<P>
   With the Israeli and Palestinian leaders far apart on the core
issues and exchanging acrimonious sallies, Clinton all but gave up
on achieving a settlement by Sept. 13, the deadline they set last
year with his blessing.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think we can work through that if there is a sense of
progress,'' Clinton said as he met with Russian President Vladimir
Putin.
</P>
<P>
   ''The main thing they have to decide,'' he said, is that ''they
are going to have an agreement by what is the real calendar -- which
is the clock that is ticking in the Middle East.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the tough core issues still eluding resolution are the
disposition of hundreds of thousands of Palestinian refugees and
the future of east Jerusalem, which Arafat demands be put under
Palestinian sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't expect an agreement over the city, unless the
Americans bring something new,'' said Palestinian negotiator Ahmed
Qureia.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestine Liberation Organization's Central Council meets
Saturday in Gaza City. The top item on the agenda is whether to
declare statehood on the West Bank land Israel has already turned
over to the Palestinians. Arafat plans to attend.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Israeli parliament meets next month. Barak's
critics there have been outraged by his offers to Arafat of nearly
all the occupied territory and control over part of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton cautioned that the opportunity for a peace agreement
''is fleeting and about to pass.''
</P>
<P>
   In a speech at the U.N. General Assembly, he appealed to world
leaders: ''To those who have supported the right of Israel to live
in security and peace, to those who have championed the Palestinian
cause these many years, let me say to all of you: They need your
support now more than ever to take the hard risks for peace.''
</P>
<P>
   The president also set up meetings with Crown Prince Abdullah of
Saudi Arabia and King Abdullah of Jordan to try to rally Arab
support.
</P>
<P>
   Albright met with Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa and
Prince Saud, the Saudi foreign minister. She set up a meeting with
Arafat before Clinton's, and talked for 45 minutes with Barak on
Tuesday night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-06-00 2331 </TRAILER>
