<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 23:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Strike Threat Fades in Philly  </HEADLINE>
By HOPE YEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Teachers for the nation's sixth-largest
school district reported some progress during another round of
contract talks Wednesday as the immediate threat of a strike
appeared to fade.
</P>
<P>
   The Philadelphia Federation of Teachers said it was unlikely the
union would call a strike before next week because a court order
allows teachers to work under terms of their old contract until 5
p.m. Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ''It gives us a little bit of breathing room, so students and
teachers can go back to the classroom, which is what everybody
wants, while talks go on,'' union spokeswoman Barbara Goodman said.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations came to a head earlier this week after the union's
rank-and-file members authorized a strike in the district of
205,000 students and 256 schools.
</P>
<P>
   The union has rejected district proposals to extend the school
day and school year, increase co-payments for health insurance,
base pay on performance rather than experience and level of
education, and give principals more say in job assignments.
</P>
<P>
   The union wants smaller classes, stronger early childhood
education, a new reading program and tighter school security.
</P>
<P>
   Another round of talks was scheduled for Thursday, the first day
of classes.
</P>
<P>
   ''The good news is that we talked seriously about a lot of
important issues,'' school district spokeswoman Alexis Moore said
Wednesday.
------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   School district: http://www.phila.k12.pa.us
</P>
<P>
   Teachers union: http://www.pft.org
</P>
</TEXT>
