<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Thursday, Sept. 7, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Pushes for Mideast Accord at Summit
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- President Clinton labored today without apparent success to
impress Israeli and Palestinian leaders with a sense of urgency as their
deadline for a settlement loomed only a week away. White House spokesman Joe
Lockhart made no claim of progress after Clinton's back-to-back meetings with
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat. Clinton
had faced long odds in trying to relaunch his flagging peace process by meeting
with the Mideast leaders on the fringes of the U.N. Millennium Summit.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Bridgestone Chief Apologizes Before Congress
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The CEO of Bridgestone/Firestone Inc. apologized today
before angry members of Congress for dozens of fatal accidents that may be
linked to his company's tires. The chief executive of Ford Motor Co. insisted
his company could not be blamed but promised to notify Americans from now on
when problems occur overseas. At the same time, internal Bridgestone/Firestone
documents obtained by The Associated Press showed the company had data
indicating safety problems years before the Aug. 9 recall of 6.5 million tires.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
US Gave Russians Data on Sub Loss
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- In a highly unusual exchange, senior U.S. government
officials responded to Russian requests for technical data on the Aug. 12
sinking of the Russian nuclear submarine Kursk, officials said Wednesday. A
State Department official who spoke on condition of anonymity said President
Clinton's national security adviser, Sandy Berger, provided some information
Wednesday to his Russian counterpart, Security Council Secretary Sergei Ivanov,
during a meeting in New York. Also, the U.S. Navy's top officer, Adm. Vernon
Clark, sent a note to his Russian counterpart providing some detailed
information based on acoustical data collected by U.S. ships on the day of the
incident.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Western Fire Crews Heading Home
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   HELENA, Mont. (AP) -- Firefighters are leaving Montana by the planeload as
officials begin demobilizing from the worst fire season in decades. At least 300
firefighters have returned to their homes in the southeastern and southwestern
United States, and more were expected to head to other fires across the country
by the end of the week. ''The pendulum has now swung the other way,'' said Bill
Cowin, incident commander for a fire camp that has been set up in Missoula to
handle demobilization.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Man Pleads Guilty to '72 War Protest
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PHOENIX (AP) -- An anti-Vietnam War activist whose criminal past was
uncovered when he ran for a suburban city council pleaded guilty today to
charges related to his 28-year flight from authorities. Howard Mechanic, 52,
lived in Arizona under the name Gary Tredway, establishing a career as a
successful business owner and activist whose role in the public sphere
ultimately was his downfall. After a reporter learned his identity earlier this
year, Mechanic turned himself in on a 1972 conviction for throwing a cherry bomb
during a protest at Washington University in St. Louis. He began the five-year
sentence in February.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Legislators Look at Privacy Bills
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Shocked at how simple it is for law enforcement to get
court permission to see the telephone numbers people dial, legislators today
discussed new bills aimed at tightening surveillance laws and put final touches
on a plan to address workplace privacy. The proposed wiretap bill would make it
more difficult for prosecutors to obtain court permission to monitor the
telephone numbers dialed by a suspect. The bill would require the same standard
of evidence now needed for permission to tap a telephone conversation. Two very
similar bills, the Electronic Communications Privacy Act and the Digital Privacy
Act, spawned from citizen concerns about their privacy online.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Fall in Early Trading
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks declined Thursday morning, slumping after weakness
in U.S. technology shares. The dollar edged higher against the yen. The
benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average shed 98.47 points, or 0.60 percent, to
16,301.40 at the end of the morning session. In New York, the Nasdaq composite
index lost 129.84 to 4,013.34 at Wednesday's close. The Dow Jones industrial
average rose 50.03 points to close at 11,310.64.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Davenport Beats Serena Williams
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Serena Williams fractured her racket on the court as her
game fell apart, and Lindsay Davenport emerged from the shadows as a forgotten
former champion to a berth in the U.S. Open semifinals. Williams, the defending
champion who was so eager to meet her sister, Venus, in the final, succumbed to
her own impatience and Davenport's deep, sizzling groundstrokes in a 6-4, 6-2
rout today that took everyone by surprise.
AP NewsBrief by GRETCHEN SCHWARTZ 
</P>
