<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 23:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Outlines Economic Plan  </HEADLINE>
By SANDRA SOBIERAJ
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND (AP) -- In a cadence mimicking former President Bush's
''read my lips,'' Al Gore reached Wednesday for the mantle of
fiscal conservative, asking voters to ''read my plan'' in a hefty
budget book coupling balanced budgets and ambitious economic goals.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic presidential candidate denounced what he called
the ''cross-your-fingers economics'' of GOP rival George W. Bush,
the former president's son, and the broad income tax cuts at the
center of Bush's agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Gore campaign was eagerly awaiting a vote
Thursday by leaders of the Teamsters that they expected would give
Gore the union's endorsement -- and the manpower that comes with it.
The Teamsters, because of their fierce opposition to Gore's
free-trade advocacy, which Bush shares, have been a holdout while
other major unions long ago endorsed the vice president.
</P>
<P>
   In his 191-page budget plan, heralded by President Clinton's
former Treasury secretary Robert Rubin as unprecedented in a
political campaign, Gore blended government activism and fiscal
caution. The only new proposal was to leave $300 billion of the
expected federal surplus unspent as a hedge against overly sunny
economic forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm doing this because I don't want you to have to read the
tea leaves,'' Gore told an audience of union activists and other
Democratic Party loyalists in a Cleveland State University
auditorium.
</P>
<P>
   ''Instead, you can just -- read my plan.'' His pauses, emphasis
and tone on the last three words recalled the elder Bush's 1988
''no-new-taxes'' campaign promise, in which he, too, emphasized
fiscal conservatism.
</P>
<P>
   ''The other side believes it's OK to spend more than the entire
surplus and then hope that the economy does better than anyone
expects,'' said Gore, who says Bush's plan devotes so much money to
a tax cut that there wouldn't be money left for important programs.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's campaign also bought a full-page ad in Thursday editions
of The New York Times to tout his newly unveiled economic plan and
criticize Bush's proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Campaigning at the Wilkes-Barre airport in Pennsylvania, Bush
countered: ''My plan has been endorsed by Nobel prize winners. His
plan has been endorsed by Bill Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   And in Wilmington, Del., running mate Dick Cheney targeted
Gore's targeted tax cuts -- for families saving for college tuition
or paying for long-term care, or for businesses making investments
in research, energy-efficient equipment or employee health
insurance.
</P>
<P>
   ''The vice president says he supports tax cuts but only for a
few,'' Cheney said, calling Gore's plan a ''200-page press
release'' that offers ''lots of taxing rhetoric and little tax
relief.''
</P>
<P>
   Economist Robert Bixby of the fiscally conservative Concord
Coalition saluted Gore's focus on paying off the national debt
within 12 years but noted the plan is premised on surplus
projections. ''He can't guarantee that any more than he can
guarantee a nice day on Jan. 1, 2012,'' said Bixby.
</P>
<P>
   Still, as Bixby pored over Gore's new softcover book, he said
the budget aimed to achieve more debt reduction than anything he
had seen from Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Crossing paths with Bush, Gore was also in Detroit and the
Scranton, Pa., area on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin introduced Gore at the Cleveland campaign stop as a former
White House colleague and ''a force for doing what was right even
when it was politically hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore listed what he planned to achieve over a decade through
previously proposed targeted tax cuts and spending:
</P>
<P>
   -- Increase home ownership to 70 percent and family incomes by
one-third.
</P>
<P>
   -- Halve the wage gap between men and women.
</P>
<P>
   -- Create 10 million high-tech jobs.
</P>
<P>
   -- Give families their lowest tax burden in 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   -- Reduce the poverty rate to one in 10 people.
</P>
<P>
   He credited his Democratic primary rival, former Sen. Bill
Bradley, for introducing the cause of fighting poverty into this
year's White House race.
</P>
<P>
   During a round of satellite TV interviews pitching his budget
plan to stations in other states, Gore showed a rare flash of
irritation in what has been a good couple of weeks for his
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is crazy,'' he said, yanking out his earpiece. ''They're
screaming in my ear, there's singing.''
</P>
<P>
   But he was at the top of his game later as he threw batting
practice for the Detroit Tigers an hour before they met the Anaheim
Angels.
</P>
<P>
   As his number crunchers worked on a detailed dissection of
Bush's budget for release on Thursday, Gore told a $50,000
fund-raiser for Cuyahoga County Democrats that America needed a
leader who would not be ''playing around with funny numbers on
whether the budget adds up or not.''
</P>
<P>
   At Detroit's Fox Theater, Gore was raising $500,000 for the
Democratic National Committee. He planned to hammer his economic
message again Thursday in Scranton.
</P>
<P>
   Running mate Joseph Lieberman, speaking Wednesday at Southwest
Missouri State University, said he feared the Bush plan would ''be
a crushing blow for the financial markets and cause tremors around
the globe.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the plan would raise interest rates, driving up the cost
of business loans, mortgages, car payments, credit card bills and
student loans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
